nged which is a positive thing but in context of a person with academic background in performing research based on text-based documents, one of the pain-points I have been facing is analyzing and curating the contents from lengthy documents.Extractive Summarization \r\n\r\nSimilarly, Extractive summarization involves choosing sentences directly from the source text to create a concise summarization.Functional Decomposition Diagram\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 2 Functional Decomposition Diagram of the system\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nArtifacts\r\n\r\nThe proposed artifacts outline the components and features for document to text summarization system.The project imposes the development of a web-based platform that encompasses a range of functionalities to simplify the summarization process including user registration, document upload, summary display.Based on the first phase the second phase starts with the basic visualization of the overall system through wireframing and creating the User Interface (UI) and User Experience (UX) of the system.Dealing with lengthy documents that require significant time and effort is a terrible task, the project will be able to minimize the time required and will prioritize important documents.NLP Subsystem\r\n\r\nAPI Based Summarizer\r\n\r\nThis functionality will integrate an external summarization API from hugging face or any reliable source which will allow summarizing any kind of documents.In the professional world, handling and extracting major key points from proposals and documents could be a terrible task for working individuals until there is a summarization tool that makes the task easier.Aims and Objectives\r\n\r\nAims\r\n\r\nTo develop a Natural Language Processing (NLP) based document summarization model.', 1, '101_2065697_proposaldocx-1', '2023-12-21 12:15:52', '2024-02-09 20:04:22'),
	(3, 2, 'Project Paribhasa.docx', 3776338, 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document', 'A Social Experience Project by\r\n\r\nProject Paribhasa\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nGroup Members\r\n\r\nRiwaz Joshi\r\n\r\nOscar Koirala\r\n\r\nAyusha Bhattarai\r\n\r\nMimisara Thapa \r\n\r\nAaryan Kuikel\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPrepared for:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAcknowledgement\r\n\r\nAs Bachelor of Business Administration students, this report was assigned to us as a compulsory project during our third year. We extend our sincere gratitude to Kathmandu University School of Management for incorporating this valuable social experience project into our academic curriculum. This initiative provided us with the opportunity to engage with underprivileged communities and carry out various activities for their well-being.\r\n\r\nWe would like to express our heartfelt appreciation to our dedicated coordinator, Mrs. Prabina Rajbhandari, whose unwavering support and guidance played a pivotal role in steering us through this project. Her expertise and willingness to address our queries and challenges significantly contributed to the success of our endeavor.\r\n\r\nWe are indebted to the Principal of Bhagwati Secondary School, Mr. Ramesh Neupane Sir, who graciously allowed us to undertake our SEP project within the school premises. His continuous support and encouragement were instrumental in the realization of our project goals.\r\n\r\nOur heartfelt thanks go out to our generous sponsors, namely Mahalaxmi Bikas Bank, Garima Bikas Bank, and Buddha Publications, whose financial assistance and provision of books were crucial in the successful execution of our project.\r\n\r\nLastly, we extend our deepest respect and gratitude to all the individuals who generously offered their time and support, contributing significantly to the completion of our SEP projects.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTable of Contents\r\n\r\n	Abstract	1\r\n\r\n	CHAPTER 1	2\r\n\r\n	1.1 Introduction to Organization	2\r\n\r\n	1.2 Reasons for Selection	2\r\n\r\n	CHAPTER 2	3\r\n\r\n	ACTIVITIES AND TASKS DONE DURING SEP	3\r\n\r\n	2.1 INTRODUCTION OF THE ACTIVITIES	3\r\n\r\n	ACTIVITIES PERFORMED:	3\r\n\r\n	2.2 PROCEDURES OF THE TASKS PERFORMED	5\r\n\r\n	CHAPTER 3	7\r\n\r\n	LEARNINGS, CHALLENGES, AND OUTCOMES	7\r\n\r\n	3.1 LEARNINGS	7\r\n\r\n	3.2 CHALLENGES	8\r\n\r\n	3.3 OUTCOMES	10\r\n\r\n	CONCLUSION	11\r\n\r\n	Appendix	12\r\n\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAbstract\r\n\r\nThe Social Experience Project, led by Bachelor of Business Administration students, sought to uplift Shree Bhagwati Secondary School in Gulmi, Nepal, addressing critical areas such as educational resources, menstrual hygiene awareness, inclusive education, sports facilities, and access to clean water. Despite challenges in planning, securing sponsorships, and logistical coordination, the project successfully executed its initiatives. Valuable lessons in effective planning, teamwork, and the importance of gratitude were gleaned from this experience. The outcomes were significant, including heightened awareness of menstrual hygiene, the establishment of a functional library, provision of extracurricular opportunities, improved student attendance, and the establishment of valuable partnerships with businesses. The project also significantly contributed to the CSR initiatives of the supporting organizations. Sponsors and partners including Mahalaxmi Bikas Bank, Garima Bikas Bank, and Buddha Publications played an indispensable role in the project\'s success, while the unwavering support of the school administration was instrumental in achieving the project\'s objectives.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, the Social Experience Project stands as a testament to the impact that dedicated students can have in underprivileged communities. Through a blend of determination, teamwork, and invaluable support from sponsors and the school administration, the project successfully addressed critical needs and left a lasting positive mark on Shree Bhagwati Secondary School and its students.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCHAPTER 1\r\n\r\n1.1 Introduction to Organization\r\n\r\nShree Bhagwati Secondary School, a government school nestled in the heart of Gulmi, Nepal. It is situated in Arbeni, Kaligandaki Gaupalika-02. The school was established in 2017 B.S.The school has a total of two hundred and eighteen students. The school is highly committed to improve itself with necessary actions with the main objective of improving the quality of education day by day. Through this project we are committed to assist the school in integrating some essential elements that will improve the quality of education.\r\n\r\n1.2 Reasons for Selection\r\n\r\nBy interacting with community leaders and local residents of Gulmi, Shree Bhagwati Secondary School came to our attention, as they are closely connected with the ground realities and are aware of the institutions that require aid.\r\n\r\nLack of Educational Resources\r\n\r\nAwareness of Menstrual Hygiene\r\n\r\nInclusive Approach to Education\r\n\r\nLimited Sports Infrastructure\r\n\r\nInadequate Clean Water Facilities\r\n\r\nIn summary, Shree Bhagwati Secondary School was selected due to its evident needs in various sectors like education, physical well-being and basic amenities. Project Paribhasa, through SEP, identified these gaps and tailored its activities to make a meaningful and lasting impact on the school\'s infrastructure and its students\' lives.\r\n\r\nCHAPTER 2\r\n\r\nACTIVITIES AND TASKS DONE DURING SEP\r\n\r\n2.1 INTRODUCTION OF THE ACTIVITIES\r\n\r\nThrough SEP, Project Paribhasa aimed to conduct various activities that were focused on the students of different grades at Shree Bhagwati Secondary School. Book donation and library setup, menstrual hygiene session along with pad donation to female students and to the school, donation of different types of sports materials to the school and lastly donation of a water tank and a purifier were some of the major events we performed there.\r\n\r\nACTIVITIES PERFORMED:\r\n\r\nBook Donations and Library Setup\r\n\r\nThrough this program, we donated books that were helpful for students from grade 1 to grade 12 for their betterment. Along with the donation of books we also helped the school set up the library as it really needed some change. We donated the books to the principal of the school. The main objective of this program was to help every student get access to good books and to equal knowledge and provide a clean and friendly space to learn and study.\r\n\r\nMenstrual Hygiene and Pad Donation\r\n\r\nThe main objective behind this session was to provide knowledge regarding why women menstruate, what they should do, how to take care of themselves and other general facts regarding menstruation. The participants in this session were the students of grade 8,9,10,11 and 12. \r\n\r\nWe started the session by discussing what menstruation is, why they happen, and then we started discussing sanitary pads, how to wear them, how to dispose of them properly and then the discussion went on regarding the myths and facts about menstruation. We also discussed the importance of nutrition, yoga while menstruating. In the session, male students were also present and were openly discussing and sharing their experiences and teachers were involved and quite supportive during the session. \r\n\r\nAt the end of the session, we distributed pads to every female student present there and then we donated the remaining pads to the school. And to the male participants of the session, we gave them copies to appreciate their presence and their participation.  In total, we donated 100 pads to the school so that the students could get access to clean and safe sanitary pads in the school itself. \r\n\r\nDonation of sports materials\r\n\r\n             When we had a conversation with the school representative, we got to know that the students did not have enough sports equipment to play in the school, thus we decided to donate various types of sports materials to the school. We donated chess boards, ludo, football, volleyball, badminton rackets. The materials were handed over to the schoolâ€™s vice principal. And after the donation, we asked the respective authority to allow the students to have a little play time where the students had a great time playing different types of games. We played games like musical balls and we gave the winners some copies and the rest were given to the school itself so that it could be provided to the needy students.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDonation of Water Tank and Purifier\r\n\r\n           The major program of Project Paribhasa was the donation of a water tank and a purifier because we were told that the school does not have a proper tap allocated for drinking water. And that it was one of the major requirements of the school. There was only a pipe for drinking water and the students were not satisfied with it. Therefore, with the motive of providing clean drinking water to the 215 students of Shree Bhagawati Secondary School, we donated a 1000 liter water tank and a water purifier to the school. This really made a positive impact on the students and the school.\r\n\r\n2.2 PROCEDURES OF THE TASKS PERFORMED\r\n\r\nThe entire process required and done for the completion of Project Paribhasaâ€™s programs can be classified into the following important steps:\r\n\r\nSelection of the school\r\n\r\n              The very first step of SEP was to find a school where some help and assistance was required. We were actually looking for a school where we could really make an impact and create a difference through our programs. Therefore, our search stopped when we got to know about Shree Bhagawati Secondary School located in Arbeni, Kaligandaki Gaupalika-2, Gulmi. \r\n\r\nCommunication\r\n\r\n            The next step after selecting the school was to set up objectives and goals that we had to achieve. But before that, we also had to know about the necessities of the children at the school. Therefore, Project Paribhasa was in constant contact with the school Principal to know about the student\'s requirements and in what ways we could be helpful. Through continuous communication, we were able to know about the lack of sports materials, and lack of access to clean drinking water.  Because of communication, we were able to complete our project as well as address the studentâ€™s needs in an effective way. And it turned out to be really helpful for both parties\r\n\r\nSponsorship\r\n\r\n             After learning about the requirements at the school, we started to search for sponsors who were willing to help us complete our project and help the students in Gulmi. For this, we started contacting the potential sponsors via email, calls, and personal contacts. We did not receive the anticipated responses yet we were supported by our three sponsors to whom we are really grateful. Garima Bikas Bank, Mahalaxmi Bikas Bank and Buddha Publication were our finalized sponsors who supported our project and helped make impacts in the lives of the 215 students of Shree Bhagwati Secondary School.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe above mentioned were the major procedures for the completion of the tasks performed during our SEP. After the materials were collected and bought, we headed towards our destination, and then we started to work as per mentioned in 2.1. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCHAPTER 3\r\n\r\nLEARNINGS, CHALLENGES, AND OUTCOMES\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n3.1 LEARNINGS\r\n\r\nThe Social Experience Project has been one of the most fruitful projects of our educational life where we got the opportunity to lively interact with people from rural areas, to know about their culture and traditions, their way of life and many more. There are a lot of learnings that can be listed but we would like to list the major ones which are elaborated under:\r\n\r\na. Proper planning and organization\r\n\r\nb. Team work\r\n\r\nc. Sponsorships\r\n\r\nd. Taking care of your belongings\r\n\r\ne. Managerial skills\r\n\r\nf. Compassion is really important\r\n\r\ng. Gratefulness in what we have\r\n\r\nWithin the duration of this project, the time spent at Shree Bhagwati Secondary School was beyond any imagination and expectations. This project has taught us that planning is not important in just theories that we\'ve learned but in practical life too. To manage and organize a set of activities need a proper planning and well scheduled timeline as we did from deciding in advance which organization should we choose to work on to companies to approach for sponsorships and delegating tasks to each member. Related to planning, the program has also given the opportunity to excel and practice our managerial skills. We interacted with the Red Cross Society members, school principal, village head, teachers, staff and most importantly the children there in the class. Similarly, it gave us a platform to lead the topics we delivered to the children. \r\n\r\nBy far the most important lesson that we learned during the entire Social Experience\r\n\r\nProject is â€˜Teamworkâ€™. We worked together from planning to execution and controlling the entire\r\n\r\nset of activities we did. It taught us a valuable lesson that success cannot be achieved in isolation.\r\n\r\nComparing the lives that we live here in Kathmandu valley as a student of KUSOM and\r\n\r\nthe life they lived there as the locals of Gulmi were drastically different from each other which taught us the importance of being grateful for what we have and to be compassionate with everyone. The bumpy roads, however beautiful the experience, subsistence food but tasty, poor accommodation but warm bonding among the Red Cross Society members were the unforgettable experience we had. These experiences also come up with a bundle of learnings that are not just applicable in our professional life but play an equal role in personal life and being a responsible citizen of the country.\r\n\r\n3.2 CHALLENGES\r\n\r\nThere are challenges in every step of our lives and overcoming them and moving forward is what makes the journey precious and memorable. We also faced several challenges while executing the Social Experience Program which we have explained below:\r\n\r\nPlanning and Coordinating: Although there were no issues with and among our team, the only problem was that we were not able to sit together and start planning and coordinating for the project because of our final examination of Semester 4. As this project was something we had never done before, coming up with a perfect plan to execute this project and make it successful was also very challenging.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFinding Sponsors: The objective of our project was not only to provide literacy and\r\n\r\nawareness sessions to the students, but it was also to help them with some stationery and\r\n\r\nExtracurricular Activities (ECA)  items and books for the library at the school, which would not be possible without the management of funds for which we had to find the sponsors. We also came across various challenges while communicating with sponsors and managing the required letters.\r\n\r\nComing up with the Content: It was difficult for us to come up with appropriate content for the awareness program part of our project due to the cultural differences. Menstrual hygiene awareness program, however, was a very successful program, more successful than we had thought.\r\n\r\nManaging Accommodation and Transportation: One of the biggest challenges for us was finding a suitable place for us to stay during the execution of the project. Since we were not familiar with the place that we were visiting for the project, we didnâ€™t have any idea about where we would be staying. We also had a huge challenge of taking all the donation items (stationery items, ECA items, books, sanitary pads, etc.) with us because there were too many items along with our luggage and managing the vehicle was very important. In fact, the group had to walk for about an hour and a half every day to go to the school and return to the place of the accommodation. \r\n\r\nMaking Sessions Productive: The main aim of our project was to give insightful and useful sessions related to menstrual hygiene. But just delivering the contents of the sessions would not be productive. We had to make sure that the students were actually understanding every content that we were delivering. However, the students turned out to be very shy at first which made the initial part of the sessions less interactive. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAccommodation and Food: The traditional home that we stayed in lacked modern comforts, basic sanitation, and easy access to clean drinking water. The food variety was also restricted to local produce, and the absence of cooking facilities created logistical issues.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDespite all these challenges present while conducting our SEP, we thoroughly\r\n\r\nenjoyed every bit of it while working together as a team and finding out ways to resolve and\r\n\r\novercome them.\r\n\r\n3.3 OUTCOMES\r\n\r\nSome of the outcomes from this project are listed as follows;\r\n\r\nStudents, even the boys, got an in-depth overview of menstrual hygiene.\r\n\r\nLibrary setup to make sure that the students will not have to limit their knowledge.\r\n\r\nSetting up Extra Curricular time, for students to engage in activities beyond studies.\r\n\r\nIncreased motivation of students to come to the schools, due to the availability of the\r\n\r\nsports items, donated by Team Paribhasa leading to lesser number of absentees.\r\n\r\nBegining of discussion on sensitive topics like safe menstrual hygiene.\r\n\r\nFacilitating students of the rural part of Nepal to participate in events which were being held in urban schools of Kathmandu Valley.\r\n\r\nFurthering the relationship between KUSOM and different business houses through\r\n\r\nsuccessful sponsorship collaborations.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION\r\n\r\n                Project Paribhasa would not have been able to help the school and its students if not for the sponsors who assisted and supported us and made it so much easier for us. We would like to extend a hearty thanks and appreciation  to our sponsors: Garima Bikas Bank, Mahalaxmi Bikas Bank and Buddha Publications. With your generous support we were able to complete our project successfully and bring smiles to the faces of 215 students of Shree Bhagwati Secondary School. It would have been almost impossible to complete SEP without their assistance. Thus, we are very much grateful towards our generous sponsors.\r\n\r\n                Along with our sponsors we also want to extend our heartfelt thanks and appreciation to the school and to the school administration who were kind enough to help us and cooperate with us which made our tasks so much easier. Without their support, we would not have been able to fulfill the student\'s needs and be as impactful as we were able to with their full support. We are also grateful to the school for making us feel so welcomed and comfortable. We will never forget their kindness and warm gestures towards us.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAppendix\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2', 'Table of Contents\r\n\r\n	Abstract	1\r\n\r\n	CHAPTER 1	2\r\n\r\n	1.1 Introduction to Organization	2\r\n\r\n	1.2 Reasons for Selection	2\r\n\r\n	CHAPTER 2	3\r\n\r\n	ACTIVITIES AND TASKS DONE DURING SEP	3\r\n\r\n	2.1 INTRODUCTION OF THE ACTIVITIES	3\r\n\r\n	ACTIVITIES PERFORMED:	3\r\n\r\n	2.2 PROCEDURES OF THE TASKS PERFORMED	5\r\n\r\n	CHAPTER 3	7\r\n\r\n	LEARNINGS, CHALLENGES, AND OUTCOMES	7\r\n\r\n	3.1 LEARNINGS	7\r\n\r\n	3.2 CHALLENGES	8\r\n\r\n	3.3 OUTCOMES	10\r\n\r\n	CONCLUSION	11\r\n\r\n	Appendix	12\r\n\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAbstract\r\n\r\nThe Social Experience Project, led by Bachelor of Business Administration students, sought to uplift Shree Bhagwati Secondary School in Gulmi, Nepal, addressing critical areas such as educational resources, menstrual hygiene awareness, inclusive education, sports facilities, and access to clean water.Book donation and library setup, menstrual hygiene session along with pad donation to female students and to the school, donation of different types of sports materials to the school and lastly donation of a water tank and a purifier were some of the major events we performed there.Donation of sports materials\r\n\r\n             When we had a conversation with the school representative, we got to know that the students did not have enough sports equipment to play in the school, thus we decided to donate various types of sports materials to the school.Finding Sponsors: The objective of our project was not only to provide literacy and\r\n\r\nawareness sessions to the students, but it was also to help them with some stationery and\r\n\r\nExtracurricular Activities (ECA)  items and books for the library at the school, which would not be possible without the management of funds for which we had to find the sponsors.Along with our sponsors we also want to extend our heartfelt thanks and appreciation to the school and to the school administration who were kind enough to help us and cooperate with us which made our tasks so much easier.CONCLUSION\r\n\r\n                Project Paribhasa would not have been able to help the school and its students if not for the sponsors who assisted and supported us and made it so much easier for us.Through a blend of determination, teamwork, and invaluable support from sponsors and the school administration, the project successfully addressed critical needs and left a lasting positive mark on Shree Bhagwati Secondary School and its students.And it turned out to be really helpful for both parties\r\n\r\nSponsorship\r\n\r\n             After learning about the requirements at the school, we started to search for sponsors who were willing to help us complete our project and help the students in Gulmi.Therefore, with the motive of providing clean drinking water to the 215 students of Shree Bhagawati Secondary School, we donated a 1000 liter water tank and a water purifier to the school.2.2 PROCEDURES OF THE TASKS PERFORMED\r\n\r\nThe entire process required and done for the completion of Project Paribhasaâ€™s programs can be classified into the following important steps:\r\n\r\nSelection of the school\r\n\r\n              The very first step of SEP was to find a school where some help and assistance was required.In total, we donated 100 pads to the school so that the students could get access to clean and safe sanitary pads in the school itself.A Social Experience Project by\r\n\r\nProject Paribhasa\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nGroup Members\r\n\r\nRiwaz Joshi\r\n\r\nOscar Koirala\r\n\r\nAyusha Bhattarai\r\n\r\nMimisara Thapa \r\n\r\nAaryan Kuikel\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPrepared for:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAcknowledgement\r\n\r\nAs Bachelor of Business Administration students, this report was assigned to us as a compulsory project during our third year.', 0, 'project-paribhasadocx', '2023-12-21 12:18:01', '2024-02-09 19:58:54'),
	(4, 1, 'Fractured Memories Script.docx', 14904, 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document', 'Fractured Memories\r\n\r\nScene 1: Family Vacation â€“ Packing and Loading Luggage \r\n\r\nQuotation Box: â€œThey are going for a trip on a yacht on a vacation, the scene starts with them quickly moving from the house and filling the cargo area of the van with the luggage. Thet are happy to go for the vacation.â€\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDescription:\r\n\r\nPictorial Representation (Maybe)\r\n\r\nPrompt for Generating Image: A scene of suburban house, surrounded by a vibrant garden. The sun is shining, and the atmosphere is filled with excitement. The family, consisting of a father, a mother, a son and a daughter, hustles around the front yard, packing suitcases into the back of spacious van.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nScene 2: The Storm â€“ Yacht Journey\r\n\r\n[Black Screen with Narrator Text]\r\n\r\nNarrator: â€œThey are at the yacht port excited and happy heading to get seated in the yacht. They had a nice breakfast, and the children were playing in the open space of the yacht. The wife and husband with wine were celebrating the quality time they were spending with the family.â€\r\n\r\nThe serene scene transitions to a sudden change in weather. Dark clouds gather ominously as the yacht moves forward and the waves tosses. The thunder roars, and lightning illuminates the chaos. IN a desperate attempt to survive, the family scrambles into a small lifeboat.\r\n\r\nIn another story, a storm separates the family while they were rescuing themselves in a small lifeboat. The father got lost in a single lifeboat and ended up on an island.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nScene 3: Arrival on the island â€“ A lone survivor\r\n\r\nDescription:\r\n\r\nThe father, battered and exhausted, washes ashore on an isolated island. The beach is surrounded by dense, mysterious and the sound of unfamiliar wildlife echoes in the background. The camera follows the father as he walks onto the sandy beach, disoriented and alone. The yacht, now a distant memory, is nowhere in sight.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nScene 4: Survival Challenges â€“ Crafting a New Life\r\n\r\n[Gameplay begins with the player controlling the character]\r\n\r\nDescription:\r\n\r\nThe game introduces players to survival mechanics. The father navigates the lush environment, scavenging for food, crafting tools, and searching for shelter. The island poses various challenges, from gathering resources to fending off wildlife. The immersive gameplay showcases the fatherâ€™s adaptation to his newfound environment, setting the stage for the adventure that lies ahead.\r\n\r\nThe father explores the island, stumbles upon a clearing where the native wild humans reside, These inhabitants, connected to the island glowing stone like element, use them for energy. The father observes their rituals and interactions, realizing the significance of these glowing stones in the native culture.\r\n\r\nThis scene hints the father to collect the resource as a source of energy. [Might Change this concept]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFractured Memories â€“ Reminiscing the Past\r\n\r\nDriven in loneliness and a yearning for his lost family, the father sues the glowing stones and collected items to craft makeshift representation of his wife, son and daughter. The scene is poignant as the father arranges these objects, reflecting his desperate attempt to hold onto memories.\r\n\r\nFlashbacks of the joyful moments with his real family intertwine with the present, highlighting the fractured nature of his recollections. The scene evokes a sense of nostalgia and loss as the father grapples with the reality of his situation.', 'The game introduces players to survival mechanics. The father navigates the lush environment, scavenging for food, crafting tools, and searching for shelter. The immersive gameplay showcases the fatherâ€™s adaptation to his newfound environment, setting the stage for the adventure that lies ahead.', 0, 'fractured-memories-scriptdocx', '2023-12-21 22:11:55', '2024-02-09 19:58:54'),
	(5, 2, '2116279_ManojKarki_FYP_Proposal.docx', 81689, 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document', 'Project and Professionalism\r\n\r\n(6CS007)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nProject Proposal \r\n\r\nThe Game â€œFractured Memoriesâ€\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nProject and Professionalism\r\n\r\n(6CS007)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nProject Proposal \r\n\r\nThe Game â€œFractured Memoriesâ€\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nUniversity ID		: 2116279\r\n\r\nStudent Name		: Manoj Karki\r\n\r\nGroup			: L6CG1\r\n\r\nSupervisor			: Mr. Yamu Poudel\r\n\r\nReader			: Mr. Akash Adhikari\r\n\r\nSubmitted on		: \r\n\r\nUniversity ID		: 2116279\r\n\r\nStudent Name		: Manoj Karki\r\n\r\nGroup			: L6CG1\r\n\r\nSupervisor			: Mr. Yamu Poudel\r\n\r\nReader			: Mr. Akash Adhikari\r\n\r\nSubmitted on		: \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAbstract\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAcknowledgement\r\n\r\nI extend my sincere gratitude to the University of Wolverhampton and Herald College Kathmandu, for providing us with this opportunity of an individual project for FYP with no limitation in choosing the project. \r\n\r\nI extend my sincere thanks to our module leader Mr. Biraj Dulal for kickstarting our project through his first session on introduction to the project. I am deeply thankful to our supervisor Mr. Yamu Poudel for appreciating my project idea and guiding me with his advice and suggestions. Finally, I would like to extend my appreciation to our Reader Mr. Akash Adhikari for his active feedback and guidance. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTable of Contents\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n	Abstract	2\r\n\r\n	Acknowledgement	3\r\n\r\n	Table of Contents	4\r\n\r\n	Introduction	1\r\n\r\n	Aims and Objectives	1\r\n\r\n	Aims	1\r\n\r\n	Objective	2\r\n\r\n	Problem Statement	2\r\n\r\n	Project as Solution	2\r\n\r\n	Scope and Limitations	3\r\n\r\n	Scope	3\r\n\r\n	Limitations	3\r\n\r\n	Literature Review	4\r\n\r\n	The Development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe Food and Water in Borneo Forest (Kurniawan, et al., 2020)	4\r\n\r\n	Software Development Methodology	5\r\n\r\n	Tools and Technologies	6\r\n\r\n	Unity	6\r\n\r\n	Blender	6\r\n\r\n	Photoshop	6\r\n\r\n	VS Code	6\r\n\r\n	C#	6\r\n\r\n	Conclusion	7\r\n\r\n	Bibliography	8\r\n\r\n	Bibliography	8\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\n\r\nThis project is game development which is related to open-world gameplay. It aims to create a 3D platform open-world game named â€œFractured Memoriesâ€. This open-world adventure game re-unities the mission of the family, the characters will have to survive in the wild with some skills and their available resources. This project focuses on a dynamic environment. The game has a realistic feature of change in time and weather of the game environment. The narrative will evolve alongside the changing time and weather. Within this game the player will be able to interact and collect the resources available. The game will consist of Non-Pedestrian Characters (NPCs) making the game more realistic. \r\n\r\nThe targeted audience for this game primarily consists of individuals who have a keen interest in open-world gaming experiences, particularly within the survival game genre. The game will cater to a sense of freedom and exploration, allowing players to interact with the dynamic and unpredictable virtual world. This is the proposed overview of the game where the players can also gather things available, and based on different tactics the player needs to survive.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAims and Objectives\r\n\r\nAims\r\n\r\nThe player can feel nature and enjoy the gameplay without any restrictions.\r\n\r\nThis game will help the player to know the survival and crafting skills which can be related in the real world.\r\n\r\nThis game also has some quests and missions which will help to increase the general knowledge and IQ of the player.\r\n\r\nThe game can help in releasing stress and improve self-satisfaction on winning different stages of the game.\r\n\r\nThe game will help players to live a life inside an environment where they can experience a world they would enjoy. \r\n\r\nObjective\r\n\r\nTo provide the player with the opportunity to play the game with their own choices whether they want to continue the mission or explore the world.\r\n\r\nTo develop a 3D open world game using Unity and Blender.\r\n\r\nTo implement a realistic environment where the player can experience day, night, and season change.\r\n\r\nTo implement survival tactics and character growth in the game while playing and experiencing it.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nProblem Statement\r\n\r\nGame enthusiasts face device compatibility issues since different platforms may have different specifications which can lead to difficulties in making games work consistently across different platforms. The gamers do want to experience a game that can help boost their mood and help them to tackle stress, loneliness, and depression. The game that has been proposed will help players to interact in an open world. Players do enjoy a game where they are free to do anything. This gives them a sense of freedom and joy in exploration. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nProject as Solution\r\n\r\nAs the character progresses through the story, the skills and ability of the character will develop, providing players feel like they made progress and achieved something in the real-world. This game will motivate the player to explore the expansive world of the game, discovering hidden locations and exciting encounters. Lastly, this game will deliver some feelings of importance, loss, love, and happiness to the player.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nScope and Limitations\r\n\r\nScope\r\n\r\nThis is an open-world game, the player will have freedom to make significant decisions that will impact the gameplay and can explore the world without any restrictions.\r\n\r\nA game for gamers with low specifications computer interested in open world games.\r\n\r\nDuring the gameplay, the player might get stuck at some point if the character is unable to solve the quests which may decrease the interest of continuing the game. Also, some unidentified bugs may also ruin the gameplay.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nLimitations\r\n\r\nAlthough this is an offline story-based game, we can still face the optimization issues for the less powerful system of the player.\r\n\r\nBudget constraints may affect the ability to acquire assets like trees, cars, and other environmental elements in the developmental phase.\r\n\r\nAs an individual developer, challenges in debugging, identifying the bugs and glitches can be time consuming and complex.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nLiterature Review\r\n\r\nThe Development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe Food and Water in Borneo Forest (Kurniawan, et al., 2020)\r\n\r\nTraditional methods of teaching survival skills, especially the ability to identify safe food and water in challenging environments often rely on verbal approaches, which may not properly convey practical information to students. Researchers have investigated the use of games as an alternative and useful learning medium to address this restriction, particularly simulation games. This literature review aims to examine the development and effectiveness of a 3D survival simulation game designed to teach players how to identify safe food and water in the Borneo Forest.\r\n\r\nThe concept of this game was developed based on the learning material, teaching method, gameplay, setting, and plot. The main scenario of this game is Borneo Island, known for rich flora and natural beauty, making it an ideal location for adventure. The research aimed to address this issue by using a simulation game to help players distinguish between edible and toxic substances. \r\n\r\nThe game involves four missions, each increasing in complexity and difficulty. These missions teach players different techniques for identifying safe food and water, such as recognizing plant characteristics and performing irritation testing. In the material collection stage, the researchers collected images, 3D objects with textures, 3D characters, audio, and animations needed for the game. Most 3D assets were obtained from Unity Assets Store, and any necessary modifications were made using Blender. The assembly stage involved the actual game development using Unity game engine and Visual Studio as a source code editor. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nArtifacts\r\n\r\n3D Assets\r\n\r\n3D assets include the characters, vehicles, buildings, objects, trees, and other visible game objects that the player will be able to see while playing the game.\r\n\r\nUI/ UX\r\n\r\nThis will help in the interaction of the player character model with the 3D assets that are available in the environment.\r\n\r\nAudio Assets\r\n\r\nThe audio effects such as in game interaction sound, realistic player movement sound, the sound of vehicles and background music will be the artifacts. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSoftware Development Methodology\r\n\r\nSoftware development methodology is a structured and organized process of developing high-quality software quickly and efficiently. The development phase consists of different stages from problem identification, planning, designing, building/ developing, testing, and then deploying the final product. The whole process in software development methodology is called Software Development Life Cycle. SDLC aims to avoid common mistakes in the development phase. The common SDLC models are waterfall method, spiral method, agile method (Alexandra, 2023). \r\n\r\nTo seamlessly track and manage this project, Kanban methodology for software development will be followed. Kanban is a term from the Japan that means billboard or signboard. The kanban methodology signifies its meaning as the major principle of Kanban is to visualize the work status and progress using the boards. Instead of dividing the work in teams, the stakeholder can add request to the backlogs. Kanban and Scrum are two agile approaches where Kanban doesnâ€™t define roles focusing on cycle whereas scrum has fixed length sprints, specific roles (Mijacobs, et al., 2022).  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTools and Technologies\r\n\r\nUnity\r\n\r\nUnity is a powerful tool used by many game developers to create and enhance their games. It is a game engine that provides tools for creating the core functionality of games and serves as an integrated development environment (IDE), helping in coding, designing, and managing the game elements. Some of the games made with Unity are Temple Run, Monument Valley, Ori and the Blind Forest and many more (Sinicki, 2021).\r\n\r\nBlender \r\n\r\nBlender is a free and opensource software that helps in creating 2D and 3D elements, characters and many other objects that require 2D or 3D modeling. Blender is mostly used in video, filmmaking, game development, architecture. Blender will be used to animate the characters and design the models and assets of the game environment.\r\n\r\nPhotoshop\r\n\r\nAdobe Photoshop is a software that is mostly used for editing, manipulating the photos and graphical contents. It is used by designers, photographers, artists, and other creative background individuals. In this project, photoshop will be used to create the buttons and images used in the game. \r\n\r\nVS Code\r\n\r\nVS Code is a code editor software developed by Microsoft. This is a good choice to interpret codes due to tis extensibility, flexibility, and many features that help coding seamlessly.\r\n\r\nC#\r\n\r\nC# programming language will be used as the fundamental game development language helping in implementing game logic with high efficiency. It can be utilized in the Unity Game Engine for scripting, offering the ability to implement game logic, physics, user interaction, and more (Kamau, 2021). \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, the proposed project aims to create an engaging open-world 3D platform game that immerses players in dynamic and unpredictable virtual worlds. By offering freedom of choice and exploration, the game seeks to cater to diverse audiences, impact survival and crafting skills, and enhance players critical thinking ability.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBibliography\r\n\r\nA., 2023. What Is SDLC? Understand the Software Development Life Cycle. [Online] \r\nAvailable at: https://stackify.com/what-is-sdlc/\r\n[Accessed 08 August 2023].\r\n\r\nKamau, V., 2021. C# or C++ for Game Development?. [Online] \r\nAvailable at: https://www.section.io/engineering-education/c-sharp-or-c++-for-game-development/\r\n[Accessed 12 August 2023].\r\n\r\nM., E., V.-t. & A., 2022. What is Kanban?. [Online] \r\nAvailable at: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/devops/plan/what-is-kanban\r\n[Accessed 12 August 2023].\r\n\r\nSinicki, A., 2021. What is Unity? Everything you need to know. [Online] \r\nAvailable at: https://www.androidauthority.com/what-is-unity-1131558/\r\n[Accessed 12 August 2023].\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKurniawan, Y. F., Isnanda, R. G. & A., 2020. The Development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe Food and Water in Borneo Forest. Emerging Information Science and Technology, Volume 1, pp. 1-7.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n		2 | Page\r\n\r\n		\r\n\r\n		1 | Page', 'Project is development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe Food and Water in Borneo Forest (Kurniawan, et al., 2020) The game has a realistic feature of change in time and weather. It aims to create 3D platform open-world game named â€œFractured Memoriesâ€', 1, '2116279_manojkarki_fyp_proposaldocx-1', '2024-01-04 22:14:33', '2024-02-10 08:33:31'),
	(6, 2, 'Project Paribhasa.pdf', 2704255, 'application/pdf', 'A Social Experience Project by  \r\nProject Paribhasa  \r\n \r\nGroup Members  \r\nRiwaz Joshi  \r\nOscar Koirala  \r\nAyusha Bhattarai  \r\nMimisara Thapa  \r\nAaryan Kuikel  \r\n \r\nPrepared for:  \r\n \r\n \r\n  \r\n \r\n Acknowledgement  \r\nAs Bachelor of Business Administration students, this report was assigned to us as a \r\ncompulsory project during our third year. We extend our sincere gratitude to Kathmandu \r\nUniversity School of Management for incorporating this valuable social experience pr oject into \r\nour academic curriculum. This initiative provided us with the opportunity to engage with \r\nunderprivileged communities and carry out various activities for their well -being.  \r\nWe would like to express our heartfelt appreciation to our dedicated coordinator, Mrs. \r\nPrabina Rajbhandari, whose unwavering support and guidance played a pivotal role in steering us \r\nthrough this project. Her expertise and willingness to address our querie s and challenges \r\nsignificantly contributed to the success of our endeavor.  \r\nWe are indebted to the Principal of Bhagwati Secondary School, Mr. Ramesh Neupane Sir, \r\nwho graciously allowed us to undertake our SEP project within the school premises. His \r\ncontinuous support and encouragement were instrumental in the realization of our p roject goals.  \r\nOur heartfelt thanks go out to our generous sponsors, namely Mahalaxmi Bikas Bank, \r\nGarima Bikas Bank,  and Buddha Publications, whose financial assistance and provision of books \r\nwere crucial in the successful execution of our project.  \r\nLastly, we extend our deepest respect and gratitude to all the individuals who generously \r\noffered their time and support, contributing significantly to the completion of our SEP projects.  \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n  \r\n Table of Contents  \r\nAbstract  ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ ...........  1 \r\nCHAPTER 1  ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ ... 2 \r\n1.1 Introduction to Organization  ................................ ................................ ................................ ..... 2 \r\n1.2 Reasons for Selection  ................................ ................................ ................................ ................  2 \r\nCHAPTER 2  ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ ... 3 \r\nACTIVITIES AND TASKS DONE DURING SEP  ................................ ................................ ....... 3 \r\n2.1 INTRODUCTION OF THE ACTIVITIES  ................................ ................................ ..............  3 \r\nACTIVITIES PERFORMED:  ................................ ................................ ................................ ........  3 \r\n2.2 PROCEDURES OF THE TASKS PERFORMED  ................................ ................................ ... 5 \r\nCHAPTER 3  ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ ... 7 \r\nLEARNINGS, CHALLENGES, AND OUTCOMES  ................................ ................................ .... 7 \r\n3.1 LEARNINGS  ................................ ................................ ................................ ............................  7 \r\n3.2 CHALLENGES  ................................ ................................ ................................ ........................  8 \r\n3.3 OUTCOMES ................................ ................................ ................................ ...........................  10 \r\nCONCLUSION  ................................ ................................ ................................ .............................  11 \r\nAppendix  ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ ....... 12 \r\n \r\n  1 \r\n Abstract  \r\nThe Social Experience Project, led by Bachelor of Business Administration students, \r\nsought to uplift Shree Bhagwati Secondary School in Gulmi, Nepal, addressing critical areas such \r\nas educational resources, menstrual hygiene awareness, inclusive education, sports facilities, and \r\naccess to clean water. Despite challenges in planning, securing sponsorships, and logistical \r\ncoordination, the project successfully executed its initiatives. Valuable lessons in effective \r\nplanning, teamwork, and the importance of gra titude were gleaned from this experience. The \r\noutcomes were significant, including heightened awareness of menstrual hygiene, the \r\nestablishment of a functional library, provision of extracurricular opportunities, improved student \r\nattendance, and the establ ishment of valuable partnerships with businesses. The project also \r\nsignificantly contributed to the CSR initiatives of the supporting organizations. Sponsors and \r\npartners including Mahalaxmi Bikas Bank, Garima Bikas Bank, and Buddha Publications played \r\nan indispensable role in the project\'s success, while the unwavering support of the school \r\nadministration was instrumental in achieving the project\'s objectives.  \r\n \r\nIn conclusion, the Social Experience Project stands as a testament to the impact that \r\ndedicated students can have in underprivileged communities. Through a blend of determination, \r\nteamwork, and invaluable support from sponsors and the school administration , the project \r\nsuccessfully addressed critical needs and left a lasting positive mark on Shree Bhagwati Secondary \r\nSchool and its students.  \r\n \r\n 2 \r\n CHAPTER 1  \r\n1.1 Introduction to Organization  \r\nShree Bhagwati Secondary School, a government school nestled in \r\nthe heart of Gulmi, Nepal. It is situated in Arbeni, Kaligandaki Gaupalika -\r\n02. The school was established in 2017 B.S.The school has a total of two \r\nhundred and eighteen students. The school is  highly committed to improve \r\nitself with necessary actions with the main objective of improving the quality of education day by \r\nday. Through this project we are committed to assist the school in integrating some essential \r\nelements that will improve the qua lity of education.  \r\n1.2 Reasons for Selection  \r\nBy interacting with community leaders and local residents of Gulmi, Shree Bhagwati \r\nSecondary School came to our attention, as they are closely connected with the ground realities \r\nand are aware of the institutions that require aid.  \r\nâ— Lack of Educational Resources  \r\nâ— Awareness of Menstrual Hygiene  \r\nâ— Inclusive Approach to Education  \r\nâ— Limited Sports Infrastructure  \r\nâ— Inadequate Clean Water Facilities  \r\nIn summary, Shree Bhagwati Secondary School was selected due to its evident needs in \r\nvarious sectors like education, physical well -being and basic amenities. Project Paribhasa, through \r\nSEP, identified these gaps and tailored its activities to make a meanin gful and lasting impact on \r\nthe school\'s infrastructure and its students\' lives.  \r\n3 \r\n CHAPTER 2  \r\nACTIVITIES AND TASKS DONE DURING SEP  \r\n2.1 INTRODUCTION OF THE ACTIVITIES  \r\nThrough SEP, Project Paribhasa aimed to conduct various activities that were focused on \r\nthe students of different grades at Shree Bhagwati Secondary School. Book donation and library \r\nsetup, menstrual hygiene session along with pad donation to female student s and to the school, \r\ndonation of different types of sports materials to the school and lastly donation of a water tank and \r\na purifier were some of the major events we performed there.  \r\nACTIVITIES PERFORMED:  \r\n1. Book Donations and Library Setup  \r\nThrough this  program, we donated books that were helpful for students from grade 1 \r\nto grade 12 for their betterment. Along with the donation of books we also helped the school \r\nset up  the library as it really needed some change. We donated the books to the principal of the \r\nschool. The main objective of this program was to help every student get access to good books \r\nand to equal knowledge and provide a clean and friendly space to learn and study.  \r\n2. Menstrual Hygiene and Pad Donation  \r\nThe main objective behind this session was to provide knowledge regarding why \r\nwomen menstruate, what they should do, how to take care of themselves and other general \r\nfacts regarding menstruation. The participants in this session were the students of grade \r\n8,9,10,11 and 12.  \r\nWe started the session by discussing what menstruation is, why they happen, and then \r\nwe started discussing sanitary pads, how to wear them, how to dispose of them properly and 4 \r\n then the discussion went on regarding the myths and facts about menstruation. We also \r\ndiscussed the importance of nutrition, yoga while menstruating. In the session, male students \r\nwere also present and were openly discussing and sharing their experiences a nd teachers were \r\ninvolved and quite supportive during the session.  \r\nAt the end of the session, we distributed pads to every female student present there \r\nand then we donated the remaining pads to the school. And to the male participants of the \r\nsession, we gave them copies to appreciate their presence and their participation .  In total, we \r\ndonated 100 pads to the school so that the students could get access to clean and safe sanitary \r\npads in the school itself.  \r\n3. Donation of sports materials  \r\n             When we had a conversation with the school representative, we got to know that \r\nthe students did not have enough sports equipment to play in the school, thus we decided \r\nto donate various types of sports materials to the school. We donated chess  boards, ludo, \r\nfootball, volleyball, badminton rackets. The materials were handed over to the schoolâ€™s \r\nvice principal. And after the donation, we asked the respective authority to allow the \r\nstudents to have a little play time where the students had a great  time playing different \r\ntypes of games. We played games like musical balls and we gave the winners some \r\ncopies and the rest were given to the school itself so that it could be provided to the needy \r\nstudents.  \r\n \r\n4. Donation of Water Tank and Purifier  \r\n           The major program of Project Paribhasa was the donation of a water tank and a \r\npurifier because we were told that the school does not have a proper tap allocated for 5 \r\n drinking water. And that it was one of the major requirements of the school. There was \r\nonly a pipe for drinking water and the students were not satisfied with it. Therefore, with \r\nthe motive of providing clean drinking water to the 215 students of Shree Bha gawati \r\nSecondary School, we donated a 1000 liter water tank and a water purifier to the school. \r\nThis really made a positive impact on the students and the school.  \r\n2.2 PROCEDURES OF THE TASKS PERFORMED  \r\nThe entire process required and done for the completion of Project Paribhasaâ€™s programs \r\ncan be classified into the following important steps:  \r\n1. Selection of the school  \r\n              The very first step of SEP was to find a school where some help and assistance \r\nwas required. We were actually looking for a school where we could really make an impact \r\nand create a difference through our programs. Therefore, our search stoppe d when we got \r\nto know about Shree Bhagawati Secondary School located in Arbeni, Kaligandaki \r\nGaupalika -2, Gulmi.  \r\n2. Communication  \r\n            The next step after selecting the school was to set up objectives and goals that we \r\nhad to achieve. But before that, we also had to know about the necessities of the children \r\nat the school. Therefore, Project Paribhasa was in constant contact w ith the school Principal \r\nto know about the student\'s requirements and in what ways we could be helpful. Through \r\ncontinuous communication, we were able to know about the lack of sports materials, and \r\nlack of access to clean drinking water.  Because of commu nication, we were able to \r\ncomplete our project as well as address the studentâ€™s needs in an effective way. And it \r\nturned out to be really helpful for both parties  6 \r\n 3. Sponsorship  \r\n             After learning about the requirements at the school, we started to search for \r\nsponsors who were willing to help us complete our project and help the students in Gulmi. \r\nFor this, we started contacting the potential sponsors via email, calls, an d personal contacts. \r\nWe did not receive the anticipated responses yet we were supported by our three sponsors \r\nto whom we are really grateful. Garima Bikas Bank, Mahalaxmi Bikas Bank and Buddha \r\nPublication were our finalized sponsors who supported our proje ct and helped make \r\nimpacts in the lives of the 215 students of Shree Bhagwati Secondary School.  \r\n \r\nThe above mentioned were the major procedures for the completion of the tasks performed \r\nduring our SEP. After the materials were collected and bought, we headed towards our destination, \r\nand then we started to work as per mentioned in 2.1.  \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n 7 \r\n CHAPTER 3  \r\nLEARNINGS, CHALLENGES, AND OUTCOMES  \r\n \r\n3.1 LEARNINGS  \r\nThe Social Experience Project has been one of the most fruitful projects of our educational \r\nlife where we got the opportunity to lively interact with people from rural areas, to know about \r\ntheir culture and traditions, their way of life and many more. There  are a lot of learnings that can \r\nbe listed but we would like to list the major ones which are elaborated under:  \r\na. Proper planning and organization  \r\nb. Team work  \r\nc. Sponsorships  \r\nd. Taking care of your belongings  \r\ne. Managerial skills  \r\nf. Compassion is really important  \r\ng. Gratefulness in what we have  \r\nWithin the duration of this project, the time spent at Shree Bhagwati Secondary School was \r\nbeyond any imagination and expectations. This project has taught us that planning is not important \r\nin just theories that we\'ve learned but in practical life too. To manage and organize a set of activities \r\nneed a proper planning and well scheduled timeline as we did from deciding in advance which \r\norganization should we choose to work on to companies to approach for sponsorships and \r\ndelegating tasks to each member. Rela ted to planning, the program has also given the opportunity \r\nto excel and practice our managerial skills. We interacted with the Red Cross Society members, 8 \r\n school principal, village head, teachers, staff and most  importantly the children there in the class. \r\nSimilarly, it gave us a platform to lead the topics we  delivered to the children.  \r\nBy far the most important lesson that we learned during the entire Social Experience  \r\nProject is â€˜Teamworkâ€™. We worked together from planning to execution and controlling the entire  \r\nset of activities we did. It taught us a valuable lesson that success cannot be achieved in isolation.  \r\nComparing the lives that we live here in Kathmandu valley as a student of KUSOM and  \r\nthe life they lived there as the locals of Gulmi were drastically different from each other which \r\ntaught us the importance of being grateful for what we have and to be compassionate with \r\neveryone. The bumpy roads, however beautiful the experience, subsiste nce food but tasty, poor \r\naccommodation but warm bonding among the Red Cross Society members were the unforgettable \r\nexperience we had. These experiences also come up with a bundle of learnings that are not just \r\napplicable in our professional life but play a n equal role in personal life and being a responsible \r\ncitizen of the country.  \r\n3.2 CHALLENGES  \r\nThere are challenges in every step of our lives and overcoming them and moving forward \r\nis what makes the journey precious and memorable. We also faced several challenges while \r\nexecuting the Social Experience Program which we have explained below:  \r\n1. Planning and Coordinating:  Although there were no issues with and among our team, \r\nthe only problem was that we were not able to sit together and start planning and \r\ncoordinating for the project because of our final examination of Semester 4. As this project \r\nwas something we had neve r done before, coming up with a perfect plan to execute this \r\nproject and make it successful was also very challenging.  \r\n 9 \r\n 2. Finding Sponsors:  The objective of our project was not only to provide literacy and  \r\nawareness sessions to the students, but it was also to help them with some stationery and  \r\nExtracurricular Activities (ECA)  items and books for the library at the school, which \r\nwould not be possible without the management of funds for which we had to find the \r\nsponsors. We also came across various challenges while communicating with sponsors and \r\nmanaging the required letters.  \r\n3. Coming up with the Content:  It was difficult for us to come up with appropriate content \r\nfor the awareness program part of our project due to the cultural differences. Menstrual \r\nhygiene awareness program, however, was a very successful program, more successful \r\nthan we had thought.  \r\n4. Managing Accommodation and Transportation:  One of the biggest challenges for us \r\nwas finding a suitable place for us to stay during the execution of the project. Since we \r\nwere not familiar with the place that we were visiting for the project, we didnâ€™t have any \r\nidea about where we would be staying.  We also had a huge challenge of taking all the \r\ndonation items (stationery items, ECA items, books, sanitary pads, etc.) with us because \r\nthere were too many items along with our luggage and managing the vehicle was very \r\nimportant. In fact, the group had to  walk for about an hour and a half every day to go to the \r\nschool and return to the place of the accommodation.  \r\n5. Making Sessions Productive:  The main aim of our project was to give insightful and \r\nuseful sessions related to menstrual hygiene. But just delivering the contents of the sessions \r\nwould not be productive. We had to make sure that the students were actually \r\nunderstanding every content that we were delivering. However, the students turned out to \r\nbe very shy at first which made the initial part of the sessions less interactive.  10 \r\n  \r\n6. Accommodation and Food:  The traditional home that we stayed in lacked modern \r\ncomforts, basic sanitation, and easy access to clean drinking water. The food variety was \r\nalso restricted to local produce, and the absence of cooking facilities created logistical \r\nissues.  \r\n \r\nDespite all these challenges present while conducting our SEP, we thoroughly  \r\nenjoyed every bit of it while working together as a team and finding out ways to resolve and  \r\novercome them.  \r\n3.3 OUTCOMES  \r\nSome of the outcomes from this project are listed as follows;  \r\n- Students, even the boys, got an in -depth overview of menstrual hygiene.  \r\n- Library setup to make sure that the students will not have to limit their knowledge.  \r\n- Setting up Extra Curricular time, for students to engage in activities beyond studies.  \r\n- Increased motivation of students to come to the schools, due to the availability of the  \r\nsports items, donated by Team Paribhasa leading to lesser number of absentees.  \r\n- Begining of discussion on sensitive topics like safe menstrual hygiene.  \r\n- Facilitating students of the rural part of Nepal to participate in events which were being \r\nheld in urban schools of Kathmandu Valley.  \r\n- Furthering the relationship between KUSOM and different business houses through  \r\nsuccessful sponsorship collaborations.  \r\n 11 \r\n CONCLUSION  \r\n                Project Paribhasa would not have been able to help the school and its students if not for \r\nthe sponsors who assisted and supported us and made it so much easier for us. We would like to \r\nextend a hearty thanks and appreciation  to our sponsors : Garima Bikas Bank, Mahalaxmi Bikas \r\nBank and Buddha Publications. With your generous support we were able to complete our project \r\nsuccessfully and bring smiles to the faces of 215 students of Shree Bhagwati Secondary School. It \r\nwould have been almost impo ssible to complete SEP without their assistance. Thus, we are very \r\nmuch grateful towards our generous sponsors.  \r\n                Along with our sponsors we also want to extend our heartfelt thanks and appreciation to \r\nthe school and to the school administration who were kind enough to help us and cooperate with \r\nus which made our tasks so much easier. Without their sup port, we would not have been able to \r\nfulfill the student\'s needs and be as impactful as we were able to with their full support. We are \r\nalso grateful to the school for making us feel so welcomed and comfortable. We will never forget \r\ntheir kindness and warm  gestures towards us.  \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n 12 \r\n \r\nAppendix  \r\n \r\n \r\n 13 \r\n \r\n14 \r\n \r\n15 \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n16 \r\n \r\n17 \r\n  \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n18 \r\n  \r\n', 'The Social Experience Project, led by Bachelor of Business Administration students,  sought to uplift Shree Bhagwati Secondary School in Gulmi, Nepal. The project addressed critical areas such as educational resources, menstrual hygiene awareness, inclusive education, sports facilities, and clean water. Valuable lessons were gleaned from this experience.', 0, 'project-paribhasapdf', '2024-01-05 09:50:22', '2024-02-09 19:58:54'),
