	(8, 2, 'Complex System Report.docx', 84847, 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document', '6CS014\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nComplex Systems\r\n\r\n(6CS014)\r\n\r\nA Review on Target Customer Segmentation and Ad Prediction using Machine Learning\r\n\r\nComplex Systems\r\n\r\n(6CS014)\r\n\r\nA Review on Target Customer Segmentation and Ad Prediction using Machine Learning\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nStudent Id			: 2065697\r\n\r\nStudent Name		: Dhiraj Kumar Sah Kanu\r\n\r\nGroup				: L6CG14\r\n\r\nModule Leader    		: Mr. Deepson Shrestha\r\n\r\nInstructor			: Mr. Shiv Kumar Yadav\r\n\r\nWord Count		       : 2313\r\n\r\nSubmitted on		       : 30 December, 2023\r\n\r\nStudent Id			: 2065697\r\n\r\nStudent Name		: Dhiraj Kumar Sah Kanu\r\n\r\nGroup				: L6CG14\r\n\r\nModule Leader    		: Mr. Deepson Shrestha\r\n\r\nInstructor			: Mr. Shiv Kumar Yadav\r\n\r\nWord Count		       : 2313\r\n\r\nSubmitted on		       : 30 December, 2023\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTable of Contents\r\n\r\n1. Ad Prediction using Click Through Rate and Machine Learning with Reinforcement	1\r\n\r\n2. Ad Click Prediction in Sequence with Long Short-Term Memory Networks: An Eternality-aware Model	2\r\n\r\n3. Deep User Segment Interest Network Modeling for Click-Through Rate Prediction of Online Advertising	3\r\n\r\n4. Customer Segmentation using Machine Learning	4\r\n\r\n5. Analysis of Unsupervised Machine Learning Techniques for an Efficient Customer Segmentation using Clustering Ensemble and Spectral Clustering	5\r\n\r\n6. K-Means and K-Medoids Clustering Methods for Customer Segmentation in Online Retail Datasets	6\r\n\r\n7. AdRobot: A Smart Segmentation Application for Automated & Personalized Marketing Campaigns	7\r\n\r\nReferences	8\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n1. Ad Prediction using Click Through Rate and Machine Learning with Reinforcement\r\n\r\nThis conference paper focuses on Upper Confidence Bound (UCB) and Thompson Sampling, represents a significant stride in the domain of online advertising optimization. The paper begins by addressing the steps of dataset collection, utilizing the Ads_CTR_Optimizsation dataset from Kaggle, consisting of information on 10 advertisements and 10,000 user clicks. The dataset choice, while providing a foundation for experimentation, raises concerns about the generalizability of findings to diverse advertising scenarios. The exploration of the dataset reveals a binary nature (0 and 1) representing user clicks on advertisements, forming the basics for the reinforcement learning models. Introduction of reinforcement learning as a field within machine learning sets the stage for the subsequent application of UCB and Thomspon Sampling. Reinforcement learning, with its focus on maximizing rewards, is appropriately framed within the context of online advertising, where the algorithm learns from its experiences rather than relying on predefined answers. The methodology section elaborates the use of UCB algorithm and the Thompson Samling algorithm. UCB algorithm involves calculating average rewards and confidence intervals for each advertisement, while Thompson Sampling relies on randomly generated beliefs to select ads. The subsequent application of these algorithms to the dataset yields insightful results. The experimentation phase, spanning 1000 rounds, highlights the efficiency of the algorithms. Random Selection surprisingly identifies Ad-9 as the best-performing ad among the 10 ads, laying the foundation for comparison with the more sophisticated UCB and Thompson Samling algorithms. UCB, when applied for different rounds, exhibits varying performances, with Ad-5 and Ad-8 emerging as top-performing ads in different scenarios. Thompson Sampling consistently prioritizes Ad-5 across all rounds, outperforming UCB in predictive accuracy. Potential challenges related to algorithm sensitivity, assumption of stationarity in user behavior, and the impact of feature representation are some of the limitations which could be a topic of discussion. Despite these constraints, it provides valuable insights into the practical application of reinforcement learning for ad prediction, with Thomspon Sampling consistently demonstrating superior performance, exploring alternative machine learning approaches for insights into online advertising optimization (Lakshmanarao, et al., 2021). \r\n\r\n2. Ad Click Prediction in Sequence with Long Short-Term Memory Networks: An Eternality-aware Model\r\n\r\nThis paper explains the significant evolution of online advertising, with ad click prediction addressing the critical task of the ad click prediction in sponsored search systems. It addresses the problem related to click-though rate (CTR) in sponsored ads, where the accuracy of the click prediction significantly impacts the user search experience and business revenue. The proposed approach/ methodology utilizes Recurrent Neural Networks (RNN) with Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) cells for sequential click prediction. The LSTM-RNN architecture is detailed, involving the sequential feeding of ads from ML1 to ML4, where ML1 is the first ad displayed in mainline, considering the information from previous ads. Authors have conducted analysis of externalities, demonstrating the impact of the CTR of the first ad (ML1) on the CTR of the second ad (ML2). The performance of the proposed model is evaluated using standard metrics such as Area under Receiver Operating Characteristics Curve (AUC) and Relative Information Gain (RIG), showcasing the improvements over a baseline Deep Neural Network (DNN) model. Acknowledging certain limitations and challenges, the primary concern covered is the high computational cost associated with the LSTM-RNN model, which may hinder its real-time applicability in dynamic advertising environments. To address this, a simplified version is proposed, reducing computation costs while maintaining a substantial portion of the accuracy gains. The analysis of externalities reveals that the quality of the first ad impacts the CTR of subsequent ads, establishing the influence of ad quality on sequential CTR. The LSTM-RNN model outperforms the baseline DNN model, demonstrating improvements in AUC and RIG across various ad positions. To address computation cost, a simplified version with a new externality feature is proposed, achieving significant gains with reduced complexity. Statistical significance tests support the meaningfulness of the observed performance differences (Deng, et al., 2018).\r\n\r\n3. Deep User Segment Interest Network Modeling for Click-Through Rate Prediction of Online Advertising \r\n\r\nUse of a novel Deep User Segment Interest Network (DUSIN) model for predicting click-through rates (CTR) in online advertising is introduced. The model architecture comprises key layers, including an Embedding Layer transforming user behavior sequences, an Individual Interest Extractor Layer utilizing a Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) for extracting individual user interests, a Segment Interest Activating Layer updating segment interests based on the last hidden vector, and a Segment Interest Activating Layer inspired by Deep Interest Network (DIN). Employing the Tobacco dataset, researchers undertake preprocessing steps like under sampling for class imbalance and defines user segments based on features related to age and gender. Baseline algorithms such as MLP, PNN, DeepFM and DIN are compared using evaluation metrics like AUC and log loss. Insights from segment interest are gained by visualizing differences using Euclidean distances, providing valuable perspectives on user preferences within the predefined segments. The model performance comparison demonstrates the superiority of DUSIN, with notable AUC gains over baseline models. Specifically, DUSIN achieved an AUC gain of 0.0017 over MLP and a further gain of 0.0029 with a sequence length of 100. The analysis of different behavior sequence lengths emphasizes the significance of historical user behavior, indicating optimal performance with longer sequence for DUSIN. Concluding with a focus on the importance of segment interests and the effectiveness of DUSIN, authors are suggesting future research directions involving automatic segmentation methods and ensemble approaches. The findings offer valuable insights into user segment dynamics, emphasizing the practical relevance of DUSIN in real-time advertising systems. The ability of model to outperform baseline algorithms underscores its potential for enhancing CTR prediction accuracy. The consideration of different behavior sequence lengths provides nuanced perspectives on the temporal aspects of user behavior. While the research proposed provides valuable contributions, it also acknowledges certain limitations, including the reliance on predefined user segments and the potential of dataset high dimensional spare features. Addressing these limitations could further enhance applicability of model across diverse online advertising contexts (Kim, et al., 2021).\r\n\r\n4. Customer Segmentation using Machine Learning\r\n\r\nIn recent years, the integration of machine learning algorithms in customer segmentations has become pivotal for businesses aiming to enhance customer satisfaction, retention, and overall profitability. The methodologies and models employed, provides insights into the evolving era of customer relationship management (CRM) and its intersection with cutting-edge clustering algorithms. The research focused on customer segmentation introduces diverse methodologies of clustering models, including the widely utilized K-means algorithm known for its computational efficiency, the hierarchical clustering approach that builds a hierarchy of data points, the density-based clustering represented by DBSCAN, and the Affinity Propagation Algorithm, which stands out for its ability to identify clusters without a predefined number. The methodology underscores the significance of CRM in modern marketing, emphasizing its role in customer value analysis and the development of persistent customer-company relationships. Customer segmentation emerges as a crucial aspect, involving the division of the market into distinct buyer groups based on behaviors and characteristics. The use of clustering algorithms becomes evident as a powerful tool in predicting consumption trends and refining marketing strategies. The comparative analysis of these clustering algorithms reveals valuable insights into their performance across dimensions such as computation speed, adaptability to dataset characteristics, and overall efficiency. K-Means, for instance, exhibits high computational efficiency. K-Means, exhibits high computational efficiency bur grapples with the challenge of dependency on the initial number of clusters. Hierarchical clustering, although versatile in cluster formation, faces limitations in computational speed, making it more suitable for smaller datasets. The finding shows the importance of choosing the appropriate clustering algorithm based on specific dataset characteristics and analytical goals. Moreover, it acknowledges the limitations associated with interpreting cluster meanings and suggests a potential enhancement by addressing these challenges. However, the review suggests a need for real-world case studies to illustrate the practical application of clustering algorithms in diverse business scenarios, bridging the gap between theoretical insights and practical implications (Patel, et al., 2020).\r\n\r\n5. Analysis of Unsupervised Machine Learning Techniques for an Efficient Customer Segmentation using Clustering Ensemble and Spectral Clustering\r\n\r\nThe article presents an insightful analysis of unsupervised machine learning techniques for efficient customer segmentation using a novel clustering ensemble and spectral clustering approach. The models employed include DBSCAN, K-Means, Mini Batch K-Means, Mean Shift, and Spectral Clustering. Data is collected from Moroccan residents through a questionnaire, resulting in a dataset of 1357 individuals with eight distinguishing traits. The methodology involves applying individual clustering models to the dataset and combining their results using clustering ensemble and spectral clustering. The proposed model is then applied to a real dataset, showcasing its effectiveness in clustering diverse populations. Performance evaluation using metrics such as Adjusted Rand Index (ARI), Normalized Mutual Information (NMI), Silhouette Coefficient (SC), and Davies-Bouldin Index (DI), demonstrating the superiority of model over traditional clustering approaches is performed. The findings showcase the distinct clusters based on demographics and socioeconomic attributes. Cluster 3 comprises educated, high income, non-single females in large cities, while Cluster 4 consists of single men with higher incomes in urban centers. Median age comparisons highlight variations across clusters, with Cluster 2 and 3 showing younger ages (28.5 and 29), and Clusters 1 and 4 exhibiting notably older ages (36 and 37). Application to a real dataset identifies five clusters, with Cluster 0 representing middle class single men and Cluster 4 comprising married women with high income and education. The proposed model outperforms traditional models in performance metrics, with ARI, NMI, SC, and DI values of 0.7014, 0.7175, 0.7289, and 0.7515, respectively, indicating its efficacy in capturing complex patterns within datasets. However, the study has limitations. It primarily relies on traditional clustering models, and the exploration of advanced techniques like deep learning could enhance clustering capabilities. Generalizing may be limited to the specific characteristics of the Moroccan residents surveyed, necessitating validation across diverse datasets and populations. Lastly, the explicit discussions on potential biases in data collection and ethical considerations lacks, raising concerns about the fairness of clustering outcomes (Karim & Hicham, 2022). \r\n\r\n6. K-Means and K-Medoids Clustering Methods for Customer Segmentation in Online Retail Datasets\r\n\r\nIn this study conducted in 2022, the authors focuses on the application of K-Means and K-Medoids clustering methods for customer segmentation in online retail datasets. The research employed a methodology encompassing various stages. Data collection involved the utilization of online retail customer data obtained from Kaggle, comprising parameters such as invoice, stock code, description, invoice data, price, customer ID, and country. The subsequent data preprocessing steps included handling missing values, conducting regency, frequency, and monetary (RFM) analysis, addressing outliers using the Interquartile Range (IQR), and normalizing the data. The clustering methods applied were K-Means and K-Medoids, each requiring the determination of the optimal number of cluster (K). The elbow method was employed for this purpose. For K-Means, the study identified the optimal K value as 4, resulting in four distinct clusters with specific characteristics related to customer behavior. K-Medoids, with an optimal K value of 6, formed six clusters, offering a more detailed segmentation based on RFM analysis. The results analysis involved an examination and interpretation of the characteristics of each cluster obtained from both clustering methods. Making the importance of preprocessing steps and highlighting the implications for businesses in tailoring their strategies based on the identified customer clusters, findings are explained properly. The generalization of the findings maybe be constrained due to the specific characteristics of the dataset and focus on clustering techniques neglects the exploration of other potential factors influencing customer behavior. The reliance on the elbow method for determining the optimal number of clusters may not be universally applicable, and analysis with alternative clustering algorithms is absent. The implication of study has become evident that the identified clusters provide valuable insights for businesses in enhancing their marketing and operational strategies. The research contributes to the understanding of customer behavior in online retail, emphasizing the need for addressing outliers and providing actionable insights for businesses seeking to optimize their online retail strategies (Mufarroha, et al., 2022).\r\n\r\n7. AdRobot: A Smart Segmentation Application for Automated & Personalized Marketing Campaigns\r\n\r\nThis paper addresses a critical challenge in contemporary marketing connecting the right promotional campaign with the right audience in the digital area. The authors present AdRobot as a solution, harnessing the power of artificial intelligence to automate and personalize the marketing strategies. The proposed algorithm investigates profiling and conversational data, employing AI heuristics to adeptly match audiences with tailored promotional campaigns. The methodology comprises two key data collection approaches. Firstly, conversational constraints are automatically gathered from interactions with the Chatfuel chatbot, encompassing details such as age, field of work, martial status, and interests. Secondly, customer responses to marketing agent posts on social media platforms, including likes, dislikes, ratings, and comments, are collected. Distance correlation, Levenshtein distance, and Euclidean distance to match customers with the most suitable promotional campaigns based on characteristics like departure place, arrival place, departure date, ticket type and price are utilization for the research. The integration of Chatfuel chatbot and DialogFlow is pivotal to the process. Chatfuel facilitates user interactions, while DialogFlow contributes to natural language understanding, aiding in the determination of customer intents during conversations. The overall process involves the initiation of conversation, data collection through forms or predefined questions, and the generation of targets for customized advertising campaigns. The results showcase the effectiveness of the algorithm, with a positive user response indicating a 70% satisfaction rate regarding the accuracy of matched offers. However, the paper acknowledges certain limitations. Notably, the reliance on data exclusively from Facebook interactions raises concerns about the generalization of findings across diverse social media platforms. The researchers have primarily focused on a specific industry potentially limiting its applicability to other domains. This innovation emerges as a solution for automated and personalized marketing campaigns, leveraging AI and advanced algorithms to enhance audience targeting. The finding suggests the potential of automated marketing strategies, in personalized and targeted advertising (Hafaiedh, et al., 2020).\r\n\r\nReferences\r\n\r\nDeng, W. et al., 2018. Ad Click Prediction in Sequence with Long Short-Term Memory. Ann Arbor, MI, USA,, The 41st International ACM SIGIR Conference on Research & Development in Information Retrieval, pp. 1065-1068.\r\n\r\nHafaiedh, K. et al., 2020. AdRobot: A smart segmentation application for automated & personalized marketing campaigns. Tunisia, DTUC \'20: Proceedings of the 2nd International Conference on Digital Tools & Uses Congress, pp. 1-6.\r\n\r\nKarim, S. & Hicham, N., 2022. Analysis of Unsupervised Machine Learning Techniques for an Efficient Customer Segmentation using Clustering Ensemble and Spectral Clustering. (IJACSA) International Journal of Advanced Computer Science and Applications, Volume 13, p. 10.\r\n\r\nKim, K., Kwon, E. & Park, J., 2021. Deep User Segment Interest Network Modeling for Click-Through Rate Prediction of Online Advertising. IEEE Access, Volume 9, pp. 9812-9821.\r\n\r\nLakshmanarao, A., Ushanag, S. & Leela, B. S., 2021. Ad Prediction using Click Through Rate and Machine Learning with Reinforcement Learning. Endore, India, 2021 Fourth International Conference on Electrical, Computer and Communication Technologies (ICECCT).\r\n\r\nMufarroha, F. A. et al., 2022. K-Means and K-Medoids Clustering Methods for Cusomer Segmentation in Online Retail Datasets. Surabaya, Indonesia, 2022 IEEE 8th Information Technology International Seminar (ITIS).\r\n\r\nPatel, M. et al., 2020. Customer Segmentation using Machine Learning. International Journal for Research in Applied Science & Engineering Technology (IJRASET), 8(VI), pp. 2104-2108.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n		\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2', 'This conference paper focuses on Upper Confidence Bound (UCB) and Thompson Sampling, represents a significant stride in the domain of online advertising optimization. Introduction of reinforcement learning as a field within machine learning sets the stage for the subsequent application of UCB and Thomspon Sampling. AdRobot: A Smart Segmentation Application for Automated & Personalized Marketing Campaigns.', 0, 'complex-system-reportdocx', '2024-01-16 13:36:18', '2024-02-09 19:58:54'),
