ments  .....................  61 \nFigure 40 Response of participants in use of Summarization tool  ............................  62 \nFigure 41Scenarios where document summarization can be used by participants  .. 62 \n \n \n 6CS007  \n1 \n 1. Introduction  \n1.1. Project Briefing  \nThe project  chosen  is a document to text summarization web application that will help \nthe user summarize content of documents, making it easier for the users to extract \nnecessary and important information without having to read the entire document. Due \nto the large amount o f data, individuals and organizations face the challenges of \nmanaging vast amounts of textual data, including lengthy documents, research \npapers, and articles. Extracting essential insights from these documents is a time \nconsuming and resource intensive ta sk. The proposed document summarization tool \naims to address the problem by leveraging NLP and machine learning techniques.  \n1.2. Aims and Objectives  \n1.2.1.  Aims  \nI. To d evelop a Natural Language Processing (NLP) based document \nsummarization model.  \nII. To create a tool for summarizing lengthy documents, research papers, and \narticles.  \nIII. To p rovide the users with concise summaries for improved content \ncomprehension.  \nIV. To improve efficiency in learning and reading contents.  \nV. To save time and increase interest  in reading document -based  contents.  \n1.2.2.  Objectives  \nI. A web application will be created that will allow users to input documents \nand get summaries generated.  \nII. Natural Language Toolkit (NLTK) or spaCy technology will be used to \nhandle document parsing and processing for various formats.  \nIII. A suitable Natural Language Processing (NLP) summarization model will be \nchosen . \nIV. The summarized set of documents will then be stored in the database from \nthe documents.  \n \n 6CS007  \n2 \n 1.3. Artefact  \nThe proposed artifacts outline the components and features for document to text \nsummarization system. The system comprises different subsystems, each with \nspecific functionalities.  \n \nFigure 1 Functional Decomposition Diagram (FDD)  \n  \n1.3.1.  Frontend System  \n1.3.1.1.  User Registration  \nThis will be the first user interaction, which will allow the user to register by creating a \nuser account and login with their credentials. Here, the user needs to provide their \nbasic information to access the system.  \n1.3.1.2.  Document Upload  \nUsers can interact with the system by uploading documents they wish to summarize. \nThis feature provides users to input the documents into the system.  \n6CS007  \n3 \n 1.3.1.3.  Summary Display  \nAfter the document is uploaded, this feature will play an important role in displaying \nthe summarized data to the user.  \n1.3.2.  NLP Subsystem  \n1.3.2.1. API Based Summarizer  \nThis functionality will integrate an external summarization API from hugging face or \nany reliable source which will allow summarizing any kind of documents.  \n1.3.2.2. NLP Summarizer  \nThis system will be trained with data especially for a specific kind of text -based file \nsuch as a book  and will summarize the contents based on its specific feature.  \n1.3.3. Backend Subsystem  \n1.3.3.1. Database Management  \nThe system will use MariaDB to manage data storage and will be storing user \ninformation, uploaded documents and generated summaries allowing the users to \naccess and review the summaries of their uploaded documents whenever they need.  \n1.3.3.2. API Management  \nThis functionality will be involved in managing the data fetched from the API and will \nbe helping in allowing the external summarization API.  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 6CS007  \n4 \n 1.4. Academic Question  \nI. How does the tool address the problem of information and time -consuming \ncontent review?  \nII. What are the potential benefits of using NLP and machine learning \nalgorithms in the summarization process?  \nIII. What existing NLP algorithms and approaches will be used to automate the \ntext summarization?  \nIV. What techniques will be used to handle document parsing and processing \nfor document format (e.g., PDF)?  \n1.5. Scope and Limitations  \n1.5.1.  Scope  \nI. The major scope of this application is that it can summarize pdf -based \ndocuments including research papers, articles, and textual content.  \nII. It will be able to identify key points, findings, and contextual information from \nlengthy documents.  \n1.5.2.  Limitations  \nI. Summarization algorithms may not capture the complete context of a \ndocument.  \nII. The tool will be limited to cross -language summarization feature.  \nIII. The tool focuses on text -based documents and may not be able to \neffectively handle images, charts, and videos.  \nIV. The summarizer might be limited to certain word count.  \n1.5.3.  Problem Statement  \nDue to the expansion in digital information, a challenge of information overloading has \nbeen seen . Dealing with lengthy documents and research materials becomes time \nconsuming, hindering the ability to extract crucial information quickly.  A study \npublished in Nature Communication reveals that our collective attention span is \nnarrowing. This is not just on social media but also in different domains , that people \nare losing their attention span  (Lorenz -Spreen, et al., 2019) . Due to the low attention \nspan, most individuals are not likely to read journals, books, and other documented \nfiles. The rise of audio -visual content has also impacted the consumption of text -based \ninformation. These days the way of consuming information ha s changed which is a 6CS007  \n5 \n positive thing but in context of a person with academic background in performing \nresearch based on text -based documents,  one of the pain -points I have been facing  \nis analyzing and curating the contents from lengthy documents . In the professional  \nworld, handling and extracting major key points  from proposals  and documents could \nbe a terrible task for working individuals until there is a summarization tool that makes \nthe task easier.  \n1.5.4.  Project as Solution  \nProfessionals, researchers, and students face challenges of extracting content from \nresearch papers and journals. This summarization tool will extract important insights \nfrom a paper to make informed decisions quickly.  Dealing with lengthy documents that \nrequire significant time and effort is a terrible task, the project will be able to minimize \nthe time required and will prioritize important documents. This  tool will help streamline \nthe process of summarizing and aggregating information from multiple sourc es and \nwill store it for further usage of the user.  People will be able to access necessary \ncontent  in a short format,  saving time.  It will encourage continuous learning by allowing \nusers to explore a broader range of topics within a shorter time frame.  \n2. Initial Research  \n2.1. Hugging Face  \nHugging Face is a platform for data science and machine learning which was initially \ndeveloped in 2017 as a chatbot app for teenagers but has expanded its domain from \njust a chatbot app. This platform has a range of functionalities from creating, hosting, \nand managing their own AI models to engaging in discussions and collaborations \nwithin the platform. Hugging face also holds a substantial collection of models and \ndatasets created by the collaborators and users. This platform encompasses a range \nof AI appl ications like computer vision, audio analysis, and natural language \nprocessing (Rebelo, 2023) . \n2.2. Natural Language Processing (NLP)  \nNatural Language Processing (NLP) is a division of AI that aims to make computers \ncomprehend, analyze, and produce human language. NLP plays and significant role \nin extracting the most meaningful information. NLP encompasses various techniques \nand methods to process and understand human language. The division of NLP 6CS007  \n6 \n approaches extractive and abstractive summarization, along with other categories \nsuch as single -document, multi -document, and query -based summarization.  \n2.2.1.  Abstractive Summarization  \nAbstractive summarization is a method where the generated summary doesnâ€™t \nnecessarily consist of sentences present in the original text, instead it creates new \nsentences that capture the key concepts. This is a approach where the new texts are \ngenerated on ly after abstracting and understanding the semantic meaning of the text \nwhile capturing the key concepts of the original content.  \n2.2.2.  Extractive Summarization  \nSimilarly, Extractive summarization involves choosing sentences directly from the \nsource text to create a concise summarization. Then the chosen text based content is \ntypically chosen based on its importance and relevance. This method aims to retain \nthe or iginal wording from the text, making it more conservative approach to \nsummarization (Adhikari, et al., 2020) .  \n3. Literature Review  \n3.1. NLP Based Text Summarization Using Semantic Analysis  \n3.1.1.  Introduction  \nText Summarization is a supervised learning method, that heavily relies on Natural \nLanguage Processing (NLP), which helps in generating concise and comprehensive \nsummaries from massive number of text -based inputs.  \nThis literature review focuses on the research paper titled â€œNLP Based Text \nSummarization Using Sematic Analysisâ€ which introduces an innovative approach for \nspecific text summarization. To save manual effort in information processing, the study \ndiscusses the challenges of summarizing large texts and highlights the use of \nautomatic summarization tools. The author offers a method based on Semantic \nAnalysis, a subset of Natural Language Processing (NLP), which helps in extracting \nrepresentative sentences and generates meaningful summaries.  \n 6CS007  \n7 \n 3.1.2.  Methodology  \nThe proposed methodology in this research paper leverages a technique based on \nLatent Semantic Analysis (LSA) for text summarization. LSA is used to extract \nsemantically important sentences and generate a summary of the input text. First, the \ninput documen t undergoes data preprocessing method, where irrelevant words such \nas stop, words are removed to enhance the quality of the summary. A matrix of word \ncounts is constructed from preprocessed text, representing the occurrence of words \nacross sentences. The s entence matrix undergoes Singular Value Decomposition \n(SVD) to reduce dimensionality and identify the latent semantic structure of the text. \nThis helps in identifying the most noticeable feature of the document, enabling \nextraction of meaningful sentences for summary. Based on latent semantic structure, \nthe system identifies the most relevant sentence and arranges them in a coherent \nmanner to generate the final summary.  \n \nFigure 2  Proposed System (Moiyadi, et al., 2016)  \nLatent Semantic Analysis (LSA) is a dimensionality reduction technique used for \nidentifying the most important sentences in a text document. Below is the \nmathematical equation for the LSA method.  \nSingular Value Decomposition (SVD)  \nSVD is used to factorize the term -document matrix into three matrices: u, âˆ‘, and v  \nu, s, v = svds (matrix, k= num_concepts)  \n6CS007  \n8 \n Saliency Vector Calculation  \nThe saliency of each sentence is calculated as the dot product of the squared values \nin u and v.  \nsaliency_vec = np.dot (np.square(u), np.square(v))  \nTopic Filtering  \nSingular values below a certain threshold controlled by topic_sigma_threshold are set \nto zero to filter out less significant topics.  \nu [u < sigma_threshold] = 0  \nTop Sentence Selection  \nThe top sentences are selected based on their saliency scores.  \ntop_sentences = saliency_vec.argsort() [ -length:] [:: -1] \nHere, the code implements Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) to perform text \nsummarization. First the input text is preprocessed, and a term -document matrix is \ngenerated. Then SVD is applied to identify the important topics and sentences and at \nlast the salien t sentences are selected to create a summary.  \n3.1.3.  Discussion  \nThe authors applied LSA -based summarization technique to a diverse set of texts and \nevaluated the performance of generated summaries. They measured the quality of the \nsummaries using various metrics, including ROUGE scores, F1 -score, and precision -\nrecall c urves. The study indicates that LSA approach performed better than existing \nsummarization techniques (Moiyadi, et al., 2016) .  \n \n \n \n \n \n 6CS007  \n9 \n 3.2. Survey on NLP based automatic extractive text  \nsummarization using Spacy  \n3.2.1.  Introduction  \nThis article provides a general overview of the area of NLP -based automated text \nsummarization. It seeks to discuss and evaluate frequently used summarizing \ntechniques by the researchers with an emphasis on useful and successful tactics with \nan insight int o the evolution of summarization. The major key points that the article \ndiscusses are the difficulties of numerically evaluating the quality of summary and the \ndistinctions between extractive and abstractive summarization.  \nThe article offers a comprehensive examination of text summarization, tracing its \nevolution from early IBM research in 1950s to modern methods. The authors delve \ninto the fundamental ideas behind extractive summarizing techniques, putting special \nemphasis on the importance of elements like key phrase recognition and sentence \npositioning during the summarization procedure. These methods are considered as \nthe pillars that support the development of contemporary extractive summarization \napproaches.  \n3.2.2.  NLP and Ambiguity  \nText summarization and other applications, such as language translation and \nchatbots, rely heavily on NLP, which emphasizes its importance in comprehending \nand interpreting human language. NLP is complicated because natural language is \noften unclear and un certain. There are different types of uncertainties in language: \nLexical ambiguity; that occurs when a single word has multiple meanings. Syntactic \nambiguity: this occurs from the way words are structured in sentences. For instance, \nthe phrase â€œVisiting re latives can be tediousâ€ can have two different interpretations. \nLastly, semantic ambiguity: this occurs when the meaning of words themselves are \nunclear.  \n \n3.2.3.  Phases of Natural Language Processing  \nThe article claims that the phases of NLP including lexical analysis, syntactic analysis, \nsemantic analysis, discourse integration and pragmatic analysis help in analyzing \nambiguities. Lexical analysis is the first step where the sentences are divided into  6CS007  \n10 \n tokens. For the second step, syntactic analysis or parsing is performed, where the \nword order is studied then in semantic analysis meaning and word order is analyzed. \nAfter performing discourse integration, pragmatic analysis is performed which is the \nlast stage, where real impact of text is gained.  \n \n \nFigure 3 Phases of Natural Language Processing (Prakash, et al., 2022) . \n3.2.4.  Preprocessing  \nTo retrieve valid information, pre -processing steps in text summarization are depicted \nin the article including sentence separation, stop words removal, stemming, part -of \nspeech tagging and keyword extraction.  \n3.2.5.  Conclusion  \nThe authors make recommendations for potential future text summarizing research. \nThey draw attention to the fact that it can be difficult to reach consensus between \nmultiple annotators and that we need more effective tools to automatically verify text \nsumm aries. This demonstrates how the industry is developing and working towards \nmore effective automatic text summarization systems (Prakash, et al., 2022) . \n \n \n \n6CS007  \n11 \n 3.3. Implementation of NLP based on automatic text \nsummarization using spacy  \nSummarization of large texts has become a pivotal task in natural language processing \n(NLP) and has garnered significant attention in both academic research and \ncommercial applications. In recent years, the field of text summarization has witnessed \nsignifi cant advancements, driven by the integration of deep learning models and NLP \ntechniques. This article explores the state of the art in automatic text summarization, \nwith a focus on summarization techniques, challenges, and the role of libraires like \nSpaCy.  With the two different methods of summarization i.e., extractive, and \nabstractive summarization. A method utilizing K -Means clustering for sentence \nselection in extractive method was introduced which involves in preprocessing the \ninput text by removing th e stop words, hyphens, and extra spaces followed by n -grams \nto select the features and applying clustering techniques.  \n3.3.1.  Summarization Techniques  \nAn unsupervised framework called SummCoder for extractive summarization was \nintroduced that employs a scoring system, considering sentence content relevance, \nsentence novelty, and sentence position relevance, to select sentences for the \nsummary. A graph -based extraction system was introduced in the paper that utilizes \nthe nouns as nodes and non -nouns words as edge. This approach considers the \nrelationship between nouns and selects the sentences based on prominence of nouns, \nachieving effective sentence extr action.  \nThe paper also suggests that abstractive summarization methods are more \nchallenging but hold the promise of creating more human -like summaries. Zheng and \nLapata proposed PacSumm, which employs a graph -based rank algorithm and utilizes \nBERT (Bidirectional E ncoder Representation from Transformers) for representation \nmapping which leverages transformer -based model to create abstractive summaries \nby considering the relationships between sentences.  \n3.3.2.  Spacy in Text Summarization  \nThe automatic text summarization with the above techniques faced challenges \nparticularly with abstractive summarization. However, the recent advancements in \ndeep learning have improved. SpaCy is an open -source NLP library in Python, that \nplays a significan t role in text summarization and sentence extraction. It offers a range 6CS007  \n12 \n of NLP functionalities, including tokenization, part -of-speech tagging, parsing, and \nnamed entity recognition. These features are essential for the preprocessing and \nunderstanding the structure of the input text. It supports deep learning workflows with \nmodels compatible with PyTorch and TensoFlow. It provides accurate parsing, \nsentence boundary detection and access to the word vectors making it a valuable tool \nfor researchers and developers working on text summarization projects.  \n3.3.3.  Discussion  \nThe text summarization process in this article follows several key steps. The initial \nphase involves preparing the input text for the summarization. This addresses the \nissues commonly found in unstructured text, such as line breaks, special characters, \nunwanted spaces, and punctuation. Then, the stop words are removed which are the \nwords which contribute little meaning are eliminated. After the removal of stop words, \ntokenization is performed which splits the sentences into individual words, forming \ntokens.  Then the selection and extraction of significant sentences from the \npreprocessed text is performed. This step involves frequency analysis, weight \ncalculation of each word determined by dividing frequency by maximum frequency. \nKey phrases in the input text  are reviewed and sentences are scored by summing \nweighted frequencies of word then the token list is sorted in descending order based \non scores. The sentences with the highest score are selected for inclusion in the final \nsummary. This method is further i ntegrated with NLP frameworks using libraries like \nSpaCy which enables efficient extraction of informative summaries (Nayana, et al., \n2022) . \n \nFigure 4 Architecture for text summarization using SpaCy (Nayana, et al., 2022)  \n6CS007  \n13 \n 3.4. Automatic Text Summarization Using Gensim Word2Vec \nand K -Means Clustering Algorithm  \n3.4.1.  Introduction  \nThis paper gives us two necessary approaches for text summarization which are \nextractive and abstractive summarization. Extractive involves choosing relevant \nsentences, paragraphs, or phrases directly from the source and then summarizing it. \nOn the other h and, abstractive creates new sentences by rephrasing the original text \nusing words that are not in the source document. The primary objective of this research \nis to summarize single documents using a sentence -based model with clustering. The \nstudy leverage s Gensim Word2Vec for feature extraction, aiming to identify the main \nconcept across the sentences.  \nThe model proposed by this paper is primarily a sentence -based clustering approach \nfor summarizing news articles. The BBC news article dataset consisting of 2,225 news \narticles were categorized into five groups (business, entertainment, politics, sport, an d \ntech) which were used for the research. To prepare the data for analysis, sentences \nwere first tokenized where text was divided into sentences using NLTK library. \nUnnecessary characters were removed, commonly occurring stop words were \neliminated, duplica te words within each sentence were removed retaining only one \ninstance and then words in the text were lemmatized to obtain their root forms.  \n3.4.2.  Word2Vec  \nWord2Vec, a widely used word embedding technique in neural networks, was \nemployed. Word2Vec method involves two terms: Skip Gram and Common Bag of \nWords (CBOW). For the implementation method, Skip Gram was chosen due to its \neffectiveness with small data am ounts and uncommon words. CBOW takes meaning \nof each word from the file and tires to predict the target word using single context input. \nThis technique generated vector representations for each word, with similar words \nhaving closer spatial positions (Karani, 2018) .  \nsin(ð‘‹,ð‘Œ)= cos(ðœƒ)=(ð‘‹.ð‘Œ)\n||ð‘‹|| ||ð‘Œ|| \n 6CS007  \n14 \n 3.4.3.  Gensim Word2Vec  \nAnother open -source library for unsupervised learning is Gensim, which uses \nWord2Vec to create word vectors from tokenized word lists based on Latent Dirichlet \nAllocation (LDA).  \n3.4.4.  K-Means Clustering  \nData points with comparable characteristics were grouped into groups using K -Means \nclustering. K -Means seeks to reduce the squared distance between each data point \nand the cluster center. Below is an algorithmic representation of K -Means.  \nLet M = {m1, m2, m3,â€¦.,mn} be collection of data points and V = {v1, v2, v3,..., vc} \nare the centers.  \n1. A cluster of the center named c was chosen at random.  \n2. The distinction between a cluster center and a single data point is established.  \n3. Cluster center datapoints are assigned to cluster centers within the shortest travel \ntime.  \n4. The following factors are used to identify the new center of cluster:  \nð‘£ð‘–=(1)\n(ð‘ð‘–)âˆ‘ð‘šð‘–ð‘ð‘–\nð‘—=1 \n1. New cluster centers are found by recalculating the distance between each data \npoint.  \n2. If there is no reallocated data point, step 3 is repeated. (Ortega, et al., 2009) . \n3.4.5.  Elbow Method to find k  \nThe ideal value of k, which stands for the number of clusters used in the model, was \nfound using the elbow approach. The final step involved generating the summary. The \ncluster with the highest number of sentences, indicating the most valuable sentences, \nwas selected.  \nThe steps to follow elbow method.  \n1. The range of K is 1 to 9.  \n2. Here, the value of k is  Increased  by 1.  6CS007  \n15 \n Third, calculate the distortion.  \n4. The point at which the distortion starts to linearly decrease.   \n \nFigure 5 The elbow with k =2 in business_doc_465 (Haider, et al., 2020)  \n3.4.6.  Evaluation  \nThe Word2Vec model was used to calculate the mean similarity of the sentences \ninside the cluster while taking noun and number content into account. The sentences \nwere chosen to produce a summary of the original text that was one -third as long. Two \ntexts ha ve been compared using the BELU score. The score for each category of the \nnews article in the image below, from lowest to highest, is calculated using BELU. The \nmodel for the business article outperformed the others. For business items, the highest \nBELU sc ore was 0.894 (Haider, et al., 2020) .  \n \nFigure 6 BELU Score for business article (Haider, et al., 2020)  \n6CS007  \n16 \n  \nFigure 7 Summary score comparison between news article categories (Haider, et al., 2020)  \n  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n6CS007  \n17 \n 3.5. Speed Reading Tool Powered by Artificial Intelligence for \nStudents with ADHD, Dyslexia, or Short Attention Span  \nThe paper reveals that the development of AI -based solutions to improve reading \ncomprehension and speed among the people with ADHD (Attention Deficit \nHyperactivity Disorder) or dyslexia has represented great advancement in the sector \nof education and acces sibility. Although there have been traditional speed -reading \nmethods, they frequently need substantial training and practice. However, many \nresearches and developments in the field of Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Natural \nLanguage Processing (NLP) have paved a way for the development of AI powered \nspeed -reading tools that can automatically summarize the texts facilitating efficient \ninformation intake.  \n3.5.1.  T5 Model  \nThe proposed model discussed in this paper uses a pre -trained model to generate \nsummaries of the input text. The tool includes features such as custom bolding feature, \nhighlighting the important information and feature to adjust the line, word and characte r \nspacing in the tool for custom reading preference. The pretrained model used by this \ntool is T5 (Text -to-Text Transfer Transformer) provided by Transformers library, a \nmodel from Hugging Face. The model was further fine -tuned to allow generate \naccurate a nd personalized summaries (Raffel, et al., 2020) .  \n3.5.2.  Transformer Architecture  \nThe transformer architecture was introduced by Vaswani and their colleague in their \ngroundbreaking paper named â€œAttention is All You Needâ€ in 2017 that has \nrevolutionized use of Natural Language Processing (NLP) and its tasks (Vaswani, et \nal., 2017) . The core concept of this architecture lies in self -attention, often referred to \nas scaled dot -product attention, enabling the model to weigh the importance of the \ndifferent words in a sequence when processing specific words.  \n3.5.3.  Feedforward Neural Networks (FFNNs)  \nThe transformer architecture is incorporated with Feedforward Neural Networks that \nplays a pivotal role in the processing and generating expressive representations. The \nencoder and decoder layers of the Transformer compute the attention score for each \ntoken in the data entered which is the input sequence. The outputs from the self -\nattention layer are channeled through FFNNs which consists of two linear 6CS007  \n18 \n transformations, which is often followed by a non -linear activation function such as \nRectified Linear Unit (ReLU), introducing non -linearity and enabling complex pattern \nand relationship learning within the data.  \n3.5.4.  Tool Implementation  \nIn implementing AI -based speed -reading tool, T5 tokenizer is set to â€œt5 -baseâ€ which \nhandles the sequences with a maximum of 512 tokens and T5 model is loaded with \nâ€œt5-baseâ€ for summarization. To manage long paragraphs, the text is divided into \nsmaller 512 -token chunks, ensuring the summarization process retains important \ninformation. The system uses Flask as the development framework, which is a \nlightweight web server framework to handle user input, process the text and apply the \nalgorithms from the python script. For the interface the proposed tool uses HTML, \nCSS, and JavaScript to display the summarized information. The below figure is a \nscreenshot of the user interface of the summarizing too l (Kamarozaman, et al., 2023).   \n \nFigure 8 Summarizing user interface (Kamarozaman, et al., 2023)  \n \n \n \n \n \n6CS007  \n19 \n 3.6. Hybrid Long Document Summarization using C2F -FAR and \nChatGPT: A Practical Study  \nLong Document summarization has drawn a lot of attention nowadays in the field of \ninformation retrieval. The development of cutting -edge language models like C2F -FAR \nand ChatGPT has created new opportunities for exploring the real -world uses of hybrid \nsumm arization pipelines. This paper gives significant research initiatives and \nadvancements in lengthy document summarization and focuses on the advantages \nand difficulties of the hybrid approaches used in this paper.  \nDue to the extensive amount of information and the need for consistency and integrity \nin the summaries, long documents have issues while summarizing because of large \namount of information and the need of coherence summaries. Traditional extractive \nmethods tend to struggle with generating coherent and concise summaries. Large \nlanguage models like ChatGPT enable abstractive approaches addressing the \nchallenges but also have problems with content hallucination and stylistic \ninconsistencies.  \n3.6.1.  C2F-FAR \nIn this paper, C2F -FAR (Content -to-flow Extractive Facilitated Abstractive \nsummarization) was introduced that offers an extractive summarization approach for \nlong documents. It relies on sentence extraction to identify key information, aiming to \nenhance th e summaries. The study shows that C2F -FAR can generate summaries \nwith competitive automated metrics, indicating its potential as a basis for hybrid \nsummarization. It can automatically select sentences from a document by considering \nthe semantics similarity  between blocks of text and between different sentences. The \nbelow figure illustrates the application of default C2F -FAR settings to 20 cleaned \narticles, demonstrating that the number of blocks partitions generally increases with \nthe number of sentences in  an article which shows that the model can automatically \ncapture semantic blocks in text.  6CS007  \n20 \n  \nFigure 9 Testing C2F -FAR default settings on 20 articles (Lu, et al., 2023).  \n \n3.6.2.  ChatGPT  \nThe research also focused on utilizing ChatGPT for summarization, specifically in the \ncontext of extractive summaries generated by C2F -FAR with a particular emphasis on \nlong documents. The summarization process involved in the two -step prompting \nmethod gen erally yielded satisfactory summary length compared to human written \nsummaries. However, repeated requests for additional details led to irrelevancy. \nThese summarizations were performed based on GPT -3.5, except for the final test \nusing GPT -4 for summarizin g the entire book.  \n3.6.3.  Evaluation  \nFor the evaluation, automated metrics such as ROGUE and BERT Score were used \nwhich suggested that machine -generated summaries are equivalent with the human \nwritten ones. The evaluation of summarization pipeline involved both human and \nautomated metrics. Hu man evaluations reveal critical issues related to coherence, \nfaithfulness, and style. The below figure shows the paraphrasing ability of ChatGPT \nagainst C2F -FAR extracted sentences using 20 cleaned articles.  \n \nFigure 10 Evaluation of article summarizes with various metrics (Lu, et al., 2023).  \n6CS007  \n21 \n In the figure above, when ChatGPT paraphrases sentences extracted by C2F -FAR, it \nleads to slightly lower ROGUE -1 and BALANC scores, but a slightly higher BERT \nScore compared to C2F -FAR generated summaries. ROGUE -2 and ROGUE -L scores \nremain largely unchange d. However, paraphrasing introduces new words to convey \nthe same meaning resulting in higher ESTIME alarms and lower ESTIME soft values \ncompared to C2F -FAR generated summaries. Despite this, ChatGPTâ€™s ESTIME \nalarms value remains lower than human written su mmaries and ESTIME soft value \nremains higher. In conclusion, ChatGPT demonstrates the ability to rewrite text to \nsome extent while maintaining overall summary quality (Lu, et al., 2023).  \n4. Project Methodology  \n4.1. Work Breakdown Structure (WBS)  \n \nFigure 11 Work breakdown structure  \n \n4.2. Software Development Methodology  \nTo organize the software development cycle, Kanban Methodology will be used. \nKanban is a method used to manage and optimize workflows in project management \nby emphasizing visual work, limiting work in progress, and promoting continuous \nimprovement. Choosin g Kanban for individual software development offers distinct \nadvantages over other SDLC methodologies. Kanban allows high flexibility as it deals \nwith prioritizing tasks based on their importance and urgency since solo developers \noften face quick change in  priority. It encourages a constant flow of deliverables \n6CS007  \n22 \n leading to quicker feedback. It allows individual developers to manage their work in a \nway that suits their own pace and style, as it does not have a predefined iteration like \nScrum, allowing them not to spend time on detailed planning sessions or assignin g \ntasks (Raut, 2015).  \n \n \n \nFigure 12 Glimpse to Trello  \nTrello will be utilized to follow the Kanban method, utilizing its visual card -based \nsystem for effective task and project management. Trello was launched in 2011, \nattributed to user friendly design and adaptability which helped it in gaining popularity. \nIn Trello, the tasks are visualized as cards or sticky notes on a visual board which is \nkanban and, usually divided into columns that represent different stages of the \nworkflow, such as â€˜To Doâ€™, â€˜In Progressâ€™ and â€˜Doneâ€™. These cards are movable across \nthe c olumns to reflect the progress of the work (Johnson, 2021) .  \n4.3. Evidence of Project Management  \n4.3.1.  Project Milestones Achieved  \nThe project Document to Text Summarization using AI has made substantial progress \nin delivering a functional system. Since the whole project was divided into several \nsystems, which includes User Management System, Document Management System, \nSummarization System, and Database System. It was easier to work on each \nfunctional system. The project initiated with the implementation of Kanban \nmethodology using Trello proved to be a highly effective approach for managing this \n6CS007  \n23 \n project. Trello provided me with the visual organization of the project, and with the help \nof automation, I was able to organize tasks, track progress and adapt to changing \npriorities seamlessly.  \n4.3.2.  Sprint Planning  \n4.3.2.1.  Initial Phase  \nThe project was initiated with the research and design phase. In the research phase, \nindividual research, literature reviews, survey forms and reviewing other systems \nhelped me picturize the system. With the initial requirement and research, I was able \nto design a basic wireframe and then give a brand theme and identity to my Lo -Fi \ndesign where I improved my wireframes and prepared Hi -Fi UI designs with a theme \nthat followed the color, typography, and basic layout of the system. While surveying \nthe system, I was able to gather the challenges and scenarios where this system can \nbe useful.  \n \nFigure 13 Sample survey 1  \n \nFigure 14 Sample survey 2  \n6CS007  \n24 \n 4.3.2.2.  Development Phase  \nThe development phase was initiated with the use of GitHub from August 20, 2023, \nhere I was able to work with the Django framework for the system development where \nwith the assigned tasks in Trello for Sprint 1, related to User Management followed by \nthe d evelopment on login, signup and logout were performed. Along with user \nmanagement, Document Management System and Database Management System \nwere successfully established. Here, authentication features for users, profile \nfunctionalities, uploading and stor ing documents were developed. The work on API \nbased summarization was done from implementing the summarization in Notebook to \nintegrating it to the system. At the end of Sprint 1, initiation of research and \ndevelopment on Summarization System was done. The  progress on the development \nis demonstrated below with the help of GitHub insights.  \n \nFigure 15 Work insight in GitHub  for contributions  \nFor Sprint 2, major updates in the development done in Sprint 1 were performed where \nfirstly, forgotten password authentication, popup modal, upgrading the frontend, use \nof messages and other tasks were performed. The issues in implementing API were \nconcerned.  \nTo track every task is going seamlessly as planned in the Gantt Chart, proper \noptimization and use of GitHub, Trello Board and Meeting Minutes were done.  \n6CS007  \n25 \n  \nFigure 16 Commits track in GitHub  \n \n5. Different Technologies and Tools Used  \n5.1. HTML/ CSS/ JS  \nHTML, CSS and JavaScript are used for front -end development for this system, where \nHTML helps in structuring the content where CSS helps in defining the visual \nrepresentation of the HTML elements, ensuring a consistent and attractive design. \nSimilarly, JavaScript helps in adding interactivity, enabling dynamic content updates \nand enhancing the user engagement.  \n5.2. Django Framework  \nDjango Framework was chosen for backend due to my familiarity with Python \nlanguage. Django is known for its effectiveness in handling web applications. It is a \nfree and open -source web framework for Python that accelerates the development of \nweb applicatio ns. It offers a more effective method to build and develop web programs \nthat initiating from scratch because it removes the need to build the backend, APIs, \nJavaScript (IBM, 2023) .  \n5.3. MariaDB  \nTo store the data, MariaDB will