to extract necessary and important information without having to read the entire document. Due to the large amount of data, individuals and organizations face the challenges of managing vast amounts of textual data, including lengthy documents, research papers, and articles. Extracting essential insights from these documents is a time consuming and resource intensive task. The proposed document summarization tool aims to address the problem by leveraging NLP and machine learning techniques. \r\n\r\nAims and Objectives\r\n\r\nAims\r\n\r\nTo develop a Natural Language Processing (NLP) based document summarization model.\r\n\r\nTo create a tool for summarizing lengthy documents, research papers, and articles.\r\n\r\nTo provide the users with concise summaries for improved content comprehension.\r\n\r\nTo improve efficiency in learning and reading contents.\r\n\r\nTo save time and increase interest in reading document-based contents.\r\n\r\nObjectives\r\n\r\nA web application will be created that will allow users to input documents and get summaries generated.\r\n\r\nNatural Language Toolkit (NLTK) or spaCy technology will be used to handle document parsing and processing for various formats.\r\n\r\nA suitable Natural Language Processing (NLP) summarization model will be chosen.\r\n\r\nThe summarized set of documents will then be stored in the database from the documents.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nArtefact\r\n\r\nThe proposed artifacts outline the components and features for document to text summarization system. The system comprises different subsystems, each with specific functionalities.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 1 Functional Decomposition Diagram (FDD)\r\n\r\n		\r\n\r\nFrontend System\r\n\r\nUser Registration\r\n\r\nThis will be the first user interaction, which will allow the user to register by creating a user account and login with their credentials. Here, the user needs to provide their basic information to access the system.\r\n\r\nDocument Upload\r\n\r\nUsers can interact with the system by uploading documents they wish to summarize. This feature provides users to input the documents into the system.\r\n\r\nSummary Display\r\n\r\nAfter the document is uploaded, this feature will play an important role in displaying the summarized data to the user.\r\n\r\n1.3.2. NLP Subsystem\r\n\r\n1.3.2.1. API Based Summarizer\r\n\r\nThis functionality will integrate an external summarization API from hugging face or any reliable source which will allow summarizing any kind of documents.\r\n\r\n1.3.2.2. NLP Summarizer\r\n\r\nThis system will be trained with data especially for a specific kind of text-based file such as a book and will summarize the contents based on its specific feature.\r\n\r\n1.3.3. Backend Subsystem\r\n\r\n1.3.3.1. Database Management\r\n\r\nThe system will use MariaDB to manage data storage and will be storing user information, uploaded documents and generated summaries allowing the users to access and review the summaries of their uploaded documents whenever they need.\r\n\r\n1.3.3.2. API Management \r\n\r\nThis functionality will be involved in managing the data fetched from the API and will be helping in allowing the external summarization API.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAcademic Question\r\n\r\nHow does the tool address the problem of information and time-consuming content review?\r\n\r\nWhat are the potential benefits of using NLP and machine learning algorithms in the summarization process?\r\n\r\nWhat existing NLP algorithms and approaches will be used to automate the text summarization?\r\n\r\nWhat techniques will be used to handle document parsing and processing for document format (e.g., PDF)?\r\n\r\nScope and Limitations\r\n\r\nScope \r\n\r\nThe major scope of this application is that it can summarize pdf-based documents including research papers, articles, and textual content. \r\n\r\nIt will be able to identify key points, findings, and contextual information from lengthy documents.\r\n\r\nLimitations\r\n\r\nSummarization algorithms may not capture the complete context of a document.\r\n\r\nThe tool will be limited to cross-language summarization feature.\r\n\r\nThe tool focuses on text-based documents and may not be able to effectively handle images, charts, and videos.\r\n\r\nThe summarizer might be limited to certain word count.\r\n\r\nProblem Statement\r\n\r\nDue to the expansion in digital information, a challenge of information overloading has been seen. Dealing with lengthy documents and research materials becomes time consuming, hindering the ability to extract crucial information quickly. A study published in Nature Communication reveals that our collective attention span is narrowing. This is not just on social media but also in different domains, that people are losing their attention span (Lorenz-Spreen, et al., 2019). Due to the low attention span, most individuals are not likely to read journals, books, and other documented files. The rise of audio-visual content has also impacted the consumption of text-based information. These days the way of consuming information has changed which is a positive thing but in context of a person with academic background in performing research based on text-based documents, one of the pain-points I have been facing is analyzing and curating the contents from lengthy documents. In the professional world, handling and extracting major key points from proposals and documents could be a terrible task for working individuals until there is a summarization tool that makes the task easier.\r\n\r\nProject as Solution\r\n\r\nProfessionals, researchers, and students face challenges of extracting content from research papers and journals. This summarization tool will extract important insights from a paper to make informed decisions quickly. Dealing with lengthy documents that require significant time and effort is a terrible task, the project will be able to minimize the time required and will prioritize important documents. This tool will help streamline the process of summarizing and aggregating information from multiple sources and will store it for further usage of the user. People will be able to access necessary content in a short format, saving time. It will encourage continuous learning by allowing users to explore a broader range of topics within a shorter time frame.\r\n\r\nInitial Research\r\n\r\nHugging Face\r\n\r\nHugging Face is a platform for data science and machine learning which was initially developed in 2017 as a chatbot app for teenagers but has expanded its domain from just a chatbot app. This platform has a range of functionalities from creating, hosting, and managing their own AI models to engaging in discussions and collaborations within the platform. Hugging face also holds a substantial collection of models and datasets created by the collaborators and users. This platform encompasses a range of AI applications like computer vision, audio analysis, and natural language processing (Rebelo, 2023).\r\n\r\nNatural Language Processing (NLP)\r\n\r\nNatural Language Processing (NLP) is a division of AI that aims to make computers comprehend, analyze, and produce human language. NLP plays and significant role in extracting the most meaningful information. NLP encompasses various techniques and methods to process and understand human language. The division of NLP approaches extractive and abstractive summarization, along with other categories such as single-document, multi-document, and query-based summarization.\r\n\r\nAbstractive Summarization\r\n\r\nAbstractive summarization is a method where the generated summary doesnâ€™t necessarily consist of sentences present in the original text, instead it creates new sentences that capture the key concepts. This is a approach where the new texts are generated only after abstracting and understanding the semantic meaning of the text while capturing the key concepts of the original content.\r\n\r\nExtractive Summarization \r\n\r\nSimilarly, Extractive summarization involves choosing sentences directly from the source text to create a concise summarization. Then the chosen text based content is typically chosen based on its importance and relevance. This method aims to retain the original wording from the text, making it more conservative approach to summarization (Adhikari, et al., 2020). \r\n\r\nLiterature Review\r\n\r\nNLP Based Text Summarization Using Semantic Analysis\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\n\r\nText Summarization is a supervised learning method, that heavily relies on Natural Language Processing (NLP), which helps in generating concise and comprehensive summaries from massive number of text-based inputs. \r\n\r\nThis literature review focuses on the research paper titled â€œNLP Based Text Summarization Using Sematic Analysisâ€ which introduces an innovative approach for specific text summarization. To save manual effort in information processing, the study discusses the challenges of summarizing large texts and highlights the use of automatic summarization tools. The author offers a method based on Semantic Analysis, a subset of Natural Language Processing (NLP), which helps in extracting representative sentences and generates meaningful summaries.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\n\r\nThe proposed methodology in this research paper leverages a technique based on Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) for text summarization. LSA is used to extract semantically important sentences and generate a summary of the input text. First, the input document undergoes data preprocessing method, where irrelevant words such as stop, words are removed to enhance the quality of the summary. A matrix of word counts is constructed from preprocessed text, representing the occurrence of words across sentences. The sentence matrix undergoes Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) to reduce dimensionality and identify the latent semantic structure of the text. This helps in identifying the most noticeable feature of the document, enabling extraction of meaningful sentences for summary. Based on latent semantic structure, the system identifies the most relevant sentence and arranges them in a coherent manner to generate the final summary.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 2  Proposed System (Moiyadi, et al., 2016)\r\n\r\nLatent Semantic Analysis (LSA) is a dimensionality reduction technique used for identifying the most important sentences in a text document. Below is the mathematical equation for the LSA method. \r\n\r\nSingular Value Decomposition (SVD)\r\n\r\nSVD is used to factorize the term-document matrix into three matrices: u, âˆ‘, and v\r\n\r\nu, s, v = svds (matrix, k= num_concepts)\r\n\r\nSaliency Vector Calculation\r\n\r\nThe saliency of each sentence is calculated as the dot product of the squared values in u and v.\r\n\r\nsaliency_vec = np.dot (np.square(u), np.square(v))\r\n\r\nTopic Filtering \r\n\r\nSingular values below a certain threshold controlled by topic_sigma_threshold are set to zero to filter out less significant topics.\r\n\r\nu [u < sigma_threshold] = 0\r\n\r\nTop Sentence Selection \r\n\r\nThe top sentences are selected based on their saliency scores.\r\n\r\ntop_sentences = saliency_vec.argsort() [-length:] [:: -1]\r\n\r\nHere, the code implements Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) to perform text summarization. First the input text is preprocessed, and a term-document matrix is generated. Then SVD is applied to identify the important topics and sentences and at last the salient sentences are selected to create a summary.\r\n\r\nDiscussion\r\n\r\nThe authors applied LSA-based summarization technique to a diverse set of texts and evaluated the performance of generated summaries. They measured the quality of the summaries using various metrics, including ROUGE scores, F1-score, and precision-recall curves. The study indicates that LSA approach performed better than existing summarization techniques (Moiyadi, et al., 2016). \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSurvey on NLP based automatic extractive text summarization using Spacy\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\n\r\nThis article provides a general overview of the area of NLP-based automated text summarization. It seeks to discuss and evaluate frequently used summarizing techniques by the researchers with an emphasis on useful and successful tactics with an insight into the evolution of summarization. The major key points that the article discusses are the difficulties of numerically evaluating the quality of summary and the distinctions between extractive and abstractive summarization.\r\n\r\nThe article offers a comprehensive examination of text summarization, tracing its evolution from early IBM research in 1950s to modern methods. The authors delve into the fundamental ideas behind extractive summarizing techniques, putting special emphasis on the importance of elements like key phrase recognition and sentence positioning during the summarization procedure. These methods are considered as the pillars that support the development of contemporary extractive summarization approaches.\r\n\r\nNLP and Ambiguity \r\n\r\nText summarization and other applications, such as language translation and chatbots, rely heavily on NLP, which emphasizes its importance in comprehending and interpreting human language. NLP is complicated because natural language is often unclear and uncertain. There are different types of uncertainties in language: Lexical ambiguity; that occurs when a single word has multiple meanings. Syntactic ambiguity: this occurs from the way words are structured in sentences. For instance, the phrase â€œVisiting relatives can be tediousâ€ can have two different interpretations. Lastly, semantic ambiguity: this occurs when the meaning of words themselves are unclear.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPhases of Natural Language Processing \r\n\r\nThe article claims that the phases of NLP including lexical analysis, syntactic analysis, semantic analysis, discourse integration and pragmatic analysis help in analyzing ambiguities. Lexical analysis is the first step where the sentences are divided into tokens. For the second step, syntactic analysis or parsing is performed, where the word order is studied then in semantic analysis meaning and word order is analyzed. After performing discourse integration, pragmatic analysis is performed which is the last stage, where real impact of text is gained. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 3 Phases of Natural Language Processing (Prakash, et al., 2022).\r\n\r\nPreprocessing\r\n\r\nTo retrieve valid information, pre-processing steps in text summarization are depicted in the article including sentence separation, stop words removal, stemming, part-of speech tagging and keyword extraction. \r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nThe authors make recommendations for potential future text summarizing research. They draw attention to the fact that it can be difficult to reach consensus between multiple annotators and that we need more effective tools to automatically verify text summaries. This demonstrates how the industry is developing and working towards more effective automatic text summarization systems (Prakash, et al., 2022).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nImplementation of NLP based on automatic text summarization using spacy\r\n\r\nSummarization of large texts has become a pivotal task in natural language processing (NLP) and has garnered significant attention in both academic research and commercial applications. In recent years, the field of text summarization has witnessed significant advancements, driven by the integration of deep learning models and NLP techniques. This article explores the state of the art in automatic text summarization, with a focus on summarization techniques, challenges, and the role of libraires like SpaCy. With the two different methods of summarization i.e., extractive, and abstractive summarization. A method utilizing K-Means clustering for sentence selection in extractive method was introduced which involves in preprocessing the input text by removing the stop words, hyphens, and extra spaces followed by n-grams to select the features and applying clustering techniques. \r\n\r\nSummarization Techniques\r\n\r\nAn unsupervised framework called SummCoder for extractive summarization was introduced that employs a scoring system, considering sentence content relevance, sentence novelty, and sentence position relevance, to select sentences for the summary. A graph-based extraction system was introduced in the paper that utilizes the nouns as nodes and non-nouns words as edge. This approach considers the relationship between nouns and selects the sentences based on prominence of nouns, achieving effective sentence extraction. \r\n\r\nThe paper also suggests that abstractive summarization methods are more challenging but hold the promise of creating more human-like summaries. Zheng and Lapata proposed PacSumm, which employs a graph-based rank algorithm and utilizes BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representation from Transformers) for representation mapping which leverages transformer-based model to create abstractive summaries by considering the relationships between sentences.\r\n\r\nSpacy in Text Summarization\r\n\r\nThe automatic text summarization with the above techniques faced challenges particularly with abstractive summarization. However, the recent advancements in deep learning have improved. SpaCy is an open-source NLP library in Python, that plays a significant role in text summarization and sentence extraction. It offers a range of NLP functionalities, including tokenization, part-of-speech tagging, parsing, and named entity recognition. These features are essential for the preprocessing and understanding the structure of the input text. It supports deep learning workflows with models compatible with PyTorch and TensoFlow. It provides accurate parsing, sentence boundary detection and access to the word vectors making it a valuable tool for researchers and developers working on text summarization projects. \r\n\r\nDiscussion\r\n\r\nThe text summarization process in this article follows several key steps. The initial phase involves preparing the input text for the summarization. This addresses the issues commonly found in unstructured text, such as line breaks, special characters, unwanted spaces, and punctuation. Then, the stop words are removed which are the words which contribute little meaning are eliminated. After the removal of stop words, tokenization is performed which splits the sentences into individual words, forming tokens. Then the selection and extraction of significant sentences from the preprocessed text is performed. This step involves frequency analysis, weight calculation of each word determined by dividing frequency by maximum frequency. Key phrases in the input text are reviewed and sentences are scored by summing weighted frequencies of word then the token list is sorted in descending order based on scores. The sentences with the highest score are selected for inclusion in the final summary. This method is further integrated with NLP frameworks using libraries like SpaCy which enables efficient extraction of informative summaries (Nayana, et al., 2022).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 4 Architecture for text summarization using SpaCy (Nayana, et al., 2022)\r\n\r\nAutomatic Text Summarization Using Gensim Word2Vec and K-Means Clustering Algorithm\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\n\r\nThis paper gives us two necessary approaches for text summarization which are extractive and abstractive summarization. Extractive involves choosing relevant sentences, paragraphs, or phrases directly from the source and then summarizing it. On the other hand, abstractive creates new sentences by rephrasing the original text using words that are not in the source document. The primary objective of this research is to summarize single documents using a sentence-based model with clustering. The study leverages Gensim Word2Vec for feature extraction, aiming to identify the main concept across the sentences.\r\n\r\nThe model proposed by this paper is primarily a sentence-based clustering approach for summarizing news articles. The BBC news article dataset consisting of 2,225 news articles were categorized into five groups (business, entertainment, politics, sport, and tech) which were used for the research. To prepare the data for analysis, sentences were first tokenized where text was divided into sentences using NLTK library. Unnecessary characters were removed, commonly occurring stop words were eliminated, duplicate words within each sentence were removed retaining only one instance and then words in the text were lemmatized to obtain their root forms.\r\n\r\nWord2Vec\r\n\r\nWord2Vec, a widely used word embedding technique in neural networks, was employed. Word2Vec method involves two terms: Skip Gram and Common Bag of Words (CBOW). For the implementation method, Skip Gram was chosen due to its effectiveness with small data amounts and uncommon words. CBOW takes meaning of each word from the file and tires to predict the target word using single context input. This technique generated vector representations for each word, with similar words having closer spatial positions (Karani, 2018). \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nGensim Word2Vec\r\n\r\nAnother open-source library for unsupervised learning is Gensim, which uses Word2Vec to create word vectors from tokenized word lists based on Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA).\r\n\r\nK-Means Clustering\r\n\r\nData points with comparable characteristics were grouped into groups using K-Means clustering. K-Means seeks to reduce the squared distance between each data point and the cluster center. Below is an algorithmic representation of K-Means.\r\n\r\nLet M = {m1, m2, m3,â€¦.,mn} be collection of data points and V = {v1, v2, v3,..., vc} are the centers. \r\n\r\n1. A cluster of the center named c was chosen at random.\r\n\r\n2. The distinction between a cluster center and a single data point is established.\r\n\r\n3. Cluster center datapoints are assigned to cluster centers within the shortest travel time.\r\n\r\n4. The following factors are used to identify the new center of cluster:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNew cluster centers are found by recalculating the distance between each data point.\r\n\r\nIf there is no reallocated data point, step 3 is repeated. (Ortega, et al., 2009).\r\n\r\nElbow Method to find k\r\n\r\nThe ideal value of k, which stands for the number of clusters used in the model, was found using the elbow approach. The final step involved generating the summary. The cluster with the highest number of sentences, indicating the most valuable sentences, was selected. \r\n\r\nThe steps to follow elbow method.\r\n\r\n1. The range of K is 1 to 9.\r\n\r\n2. Here, the value of k isÂ IncreasedÂ by 1.\r\n\r\nThird, calculate the distortion. \r\n\r\n4. The point at which the distortion starts to linearly decrease. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 5 The elbow with k =2 in business_doc_465 (Haider, et al., 2020)\r\n\r\nEvaluation\r\n\r\nThe Word2Vec model was used to calculate the mean similarity of the sentences inside the cluster while taking noun and number content into account. The sentences were chosen to produce a summary of the original text that was one-third as long. Two texts have been compared using the BELU score. The score for each category of the news article in the image below, from lowest to highest, is calculated using BELU. The model for the business article outperformed the others. For business items, the highest BELU score was 0.894 (Haider, et al., 2020). \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 6 BELU Score for business article (Haider, et al., 2020)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 7 Summary score comparison between news article categories (Haider, et al., 2020)\r\n\r\n		\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSpeed Reading Tool Powered by Artificial Intelligence for Students with ADHD, Dyslexia, or Short Attention Span \r\n\r\nThe paper reveals that the development of AI-based solutions to improve reading comprehension and speed among the people with ADHD (Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder) or dyslexia has represented great advancement in the sector of education and accessibility. Although there have been traditional speed-reading methods, they frequently need substantial training and practice. However, many researches and developments in the field of Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Natural Language Processing (NLP) have paved a way for the development of AI powered speed-reading tools that can automatically summarize the texts facilitating efficient information intake. \r\n\r\nT5 Model\r\n\r\nThe proposed model discussed in this paper uses a pre-trained model to generate summaries of the input text. The tool includes features such as custom bolding feature, highlighting the important information and feature to adjust the line, word and character spacing in the tool for custom reading preference. The pretrained model used by this tool is T5 (Text-to-Text Transfer Transformer) provided by Transformers library, a model from Hugging Face. The model was further fine-tuned to allow generate accurate and personalized summaries (Raffel, et al., 2020). \r\n\r\nTransformer Architecture \r\n\r\nThe transformer architecture was introduced by Vaswani and their colleague in their groundbreaking paper named â€œAttention is All You Needâ€ in 2017 that has revolutionized use of Natural Language Processing (NLP) and its tasks (Vaswani, et al., 2017). The core concept of this architecture lies in self-attention, often referred to as scaled dot-product attention, enabling the model to weigh the importance of the different words in a sequence when processing specific words. \r\n\r\nFeedforward Neural Networks (FFNNs)\r\n\r\nThe transformer architecture is incorporated with Feedforward Neural Networks that plays a pivotal role in the processing and generating expressive representations. The encoder and decoder layers of the Transformer compute the attention score for each token in the data entered which is the input sequence. The outputs from the self-attention layer are channeled through FFNNs which consists of two linear transformations, which is often followed by a non-linear activation function such as Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU), introducing non-linearity and enabling complex pattern and relationship learning within the data.\r\n\r\nTool Implementation\r\n\r\nIn implementing AI-based speed-reading tool, T5 tokenizer is set to â€œt5-baseâ€ which handles the sequences with a maximum of 512 tokens and T5 model is loaded with â€œt5-baseâ€ for summarization. To manage long paragraphs, the text is divided into smaller 512-token chunks, ensuring the summarization process retains important information. The system uses Flask as the development framework, which is a lightweight web server framework to handle user input, process the text and apply the algorithms from the python script. For the interface the proposed tool uses HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to display the summarized information. The below figure is a screenshot of the user interface of the summarizing tool (Kamarozaman, et al., 2023). \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 8 Summarizing user interface (Kamarozaman, et al., 2023)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nHybrid Long Document Summarization using C2F-FAR and ChatGPT: A Practical Study \r\n\r\nLong Document summarization has drawn a lot of attention nowadays in the field of information retrieval. The development of cutting-edge language models like C2F-FAR and ChatGPT has created new opportunities for exploring the real-world uses of hybrid summarization pipelines. This paper gives significant research initiatives and advancements in lengthy document summarization and focuses on the advantages and difficulties of the hybrid approaches used in this paper.\r\n\r\nDue to the extensive amount of information and the need for consistency and integrity in the summaries, long documents have issues while summarizing because of large amount of information and the need of coherence summaries. Traditional extractive methods tend to struggle with generating coherent and concise summaries. Large language models like ChatGPT enable abstractive approaches addressing the challenges but also have problems with content hallucination and stylistic inconsistencies.\r\n\r\nC2F-FAR\r\n\r\nIn this paper, C2F-FAR (Content-to-flow Extractive Facilitated Abstractive summarization) was introduced that offers an extractive summarization approach for long documents. It relies on sentence extraction to identify key information, aiming to enhance the summaries. The study shows that C2F-FAR can generate summaries with competitive automated metrics, indicating its potential as a basis for hybrid summarization. It can automatically select sentences from a document by considering the semantics similarity between blocks of text and between different sentences. The below figure illustrates the application of default C2F-FAR settings to 20 cleaned articles, demonstrating that the number of blocks partitions generally increases with the number of sentences in an article which shows that the model can automatically capture semantic blocks in text.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 9 Testing C2F-FAR default settings on 20 articles (Lu, et al., 2023).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nChatGPT\r\n\r\nThe research also focused on utilizing ChatGPT for summarization, specifically in the context of extractive summaries generated by C2F-FAR with a particular emphasis on long documents. The summarization process involved in the two-step prompting method generally yielded satisfactory summary length compared to human written summaries. However, repeated requests for additional details led to irrelevancy. These summarizations were performed based on GPT-3.5, except for the final test using GPT-4 for summarizing the entire book. \r\n\r\nEvaluation \r\n\r\nFor the evaluation, automated metrics such as ROGUE and BERT Score were used which suggested that machine-generated summaries are equivalent with the human written ones. The evaluation of summarization pipeline involved both human and automated metrics. Human evaluations reveal critical issues related to coherence, faithfulness, and style. The below figure shows the paraphrasing ability of ChatGPT against C2F-FAR extracted sentences using 20 cleaned articles. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 10 Evaluation of article summarizes with various metrics (Lu, et al., 2023).\r\n\r\nIn the figure above, when ChatGPT paraphrases sentences extracted by C2F-FAR, it leads to slightly lower ROGUE-1 and BALANC scores, but a slightly higher BERT Score compared to C2F-FAR generated summaries. ROGUE-2 and ROGUE-L scores remain largely unchanged. However, paraphrasing introduces new words to convey the same meaning resulting in higher ESTIME alarms and lower ESTIME soft values compared to C2F-FAR generated summaries. Despite this, ChatGPTâ€™s ESTIME alarms value remains lower than human written summaries and ESTIME soft value remains higher. In conclusion, ChatGPT demonstrates the ability to rewrite text to some extent while maintaining overall summary quality (Lu, et al., 2023).\r\n\r\nProject Methodology\r\n\r\nWork Breakdown Structure (WBS)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 11 Work breakdown structure\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSoftware Development Methodology \r\n\r\nTo organize the software development cycle, Kanban Methodology will be used. Kanban is a method used to manage and optimize workflows in project management by emphasizing visual work, limiting work in progress, and promoting continuous improvement. Choosing Kanban for individual software development offers distinct advantages over other SDLC methodologies. Kanban allows high flexibility as it deals with prioritizing tasks based on their importance and urgency since solo developers often face quick change in priority. It encourages a constant flow of deliverables leading to quicker feedback. It allows individual developers to manage their work in a way that suits their own pace and style, as it does not have a predefined iteration like Scrum, allowing them not to spend time on detailed planning sessions or assigning tasks (Raut, 2015). \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 12 Glimpse to Trello\r\n\r\nTrello will be utilized to follow the Kanban method, utilizing its visual card-based system for effective task and project management. Trello was launched in 2011, attributed to user friendly design and adaptability which helped it in gaining popularity. In Trello, the tasks are visualized as cards or sticky notes on a visual board which is kanban and, usually divided into columns that represent different stages of the workflow, such as â€˜To Doâ€™, â€˜In Progressâ€™ and â€˜Doneâ€™. These cards are movable across the columns to reflect the progress of the work (Johnson, 2021). \r\n\r\nEvidence of Project Management\r\n\r\nProject Milestones Achieved \r\n\r\nThe project Document to Text Summarization using AI has made substantial progress in delivering a functional system. Since the whole project was divided into several systems, which includes User Management System, Document Management System, Summarization System, and Database System. It was easier to work on each functional system. The project initiated with the implementation of Kanban methodology using Trello proved to be a highly effective approach for managing this project. Trello provided me with the visual organization of the project, and with the help of automation, I was able to organize tasks, track progress and adapt to changing priorities seamlessly. \r\n\r\nSprint Planning\r\n\r\nInitial Phase\r\n\r\nThe project was initiated with the research and design phase. In the research phase, individual research, literature reviews, survey forms and reviewing other systems helped me picturize the system. With the initial requirement and research, I was able to design a basic wireframe and then give a brand theme and identity to my Lo-Fi design where I improved my wireframes and prepared Hi-Fi UI designs with a theme that followed the color, typography, and basic layout of the system. While surveying the system, I was able to gather the challenges and scenarios where this system can be useful.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 13 Sample survey 1\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 14 Sample survey 2\r\n\r\nDevelopment Phase \r\n\r\nThe development phase was initiated with the use of GitHub from August 20, 2023, here I was able to work with the Django framework for the system development where with the assigned tasks in Trello for Sprint 1, related to User Management followed by the development on login, signup and logout were performed. Along with user management, Document Management System and Database Management System were successfully established. Here, authentication features for users, profile functionalities, uploading and storing documents were developed. The work on API based summarization was done from implementing the summarization in Notebook to integrating it to the system. At the end of Sprint 1, initiation of research and development on Summarization System was done. The progress on the development is demonstrated below with the help of GitHub insights.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 15 Work insight in GitHub for contributions\r\n\r\nFor Sprint 2, major updates in the development done in Sprint 1 were performed where firstly, forgotten password authentication, popup modal, upgrading the frontend, use of messages and other tasks were performed. The issues in implementing API were concerned.\r\n\r\nTo track every task is going seamlessly as planned in the Gantt Chart, proper optimization and use of GitHub, Trello Board and Meeting Minutes were done. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 16 Commits track in GitHub\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDifferent Technologies and Tools Used\r\n\r\nHTML/ CSS/ JS \r\n\r\nHTML, CSS and JavaScript are used for front-end development for this system, where HTML helps in structuring the content where CSS helps in defining the visual representation of the HTML elements, ensuring a consistent and attractive design. Similarly, JavaScript helps in adding interactivity, enabling dynamic content updates and enhancing the user engagement.\r\n\r\nDjango Framework \r\n\r\nDjango Framework was chosen for backend due to my familiarity with Python language. Django is known for its effectiveness in handling web applications. It is a free and open-source web framework for Python that accelerates the development of web applications. It offers a more effective method to build and develop web programs that initiating from scratch because it removes the need to build the backend, APIs, JavaScript (IBM, 2023). \r\n\r\nMariaDB \r\n\r\nTo store the data, MariaDB will be used due to its user-friendly interface simplifies database management, making it an excellent choice for an uncomplicated database solution. \r\n\r\nNLP Model \r\n\r\nNLP model is the proposed model that will be used for the machine learning aspect of the system. TextRank is one of the algorithms that extracts important sentences from a document. Similarly for the proposed system, transformer-based models such as BERT and BART could be used for abstractive summarization (Pietro, 2022).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nArtefact Designs\r\n\r\nLegend\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nUM-F-1.0\r\n\r\nSub systems\r\n\r\nUM	: User Management System\r\n\r\nDM	: Document Management System\r\n\r\nSM	: Summarization System\r\n\r\nDMS	: Database Management System\r\n\r\nNM	: Notification Management System\r\n\r\nTypes of Requirements\r\n\r\nF	: Functional Requirements\r\n\r\nNF	: Non-Functional Requirements\r\n\r\nUR	: Usability Requirements\r\n\r\nNumbering\r\n\r\nUM-F-1.0\r\n\r\nSub systems\r\n\r\nUM	: User Management System\r\n\r\nDM	: Document Management System\r\n\r\nSM	: Summarization System\r\n\r\nDMS	: Database Management System\r\n\r\nNM	: Notification Management System\r\n