..... .. 78 \r\nFigure 69: Log Sheet 9  ................................ ................................ ................................ .. 79 \r\nFigure 70: Log Sheet 10  ................................ ................................ ................................  80 \r\nFigure 71: Enter Patient Detail Page  ................................ ................................ .............  84 \r\nFigure 72: Enter Patient Detail Page with Error  ................................ .............................  85 \r\nFigure 73: Crop image Page  ................................ ................................ .........................  85 \r\nFigure 74: Confirm Information Page  ................................ ................................ ............  86 \r\nFigure 75: Predicting Page  ................................ ................................ ............................  86 \r\nFigure 76: Output Page with heatmap  ................................ ................................ ...........  87 \r\nFigure 77: Output Page with overlayed heatmap  ................................ ..........................  87 \r\nFigure 78: All Results Page  ................................ ................................ ...........................  88 \r\nFigure 79: Delete Confirmation Page  ................................ ................................ ............  88 \r\n  1 | P a g e  \r\n 1. Introduction  \r\n1.1. Project Briefing  \r\n1.1.1 Project Introduction  \r\nIn this revolutionary age of technology, the amount of data produced daily has increased \r\nexponentially. Machine Learning concepts can be used to leverage the power of these \r\nraw data. Compute r vision is a field of machine learning which allows computers to \r\nprocess visual data to produce a meaningful output. The use of computer vision has been \r\nemployed in tasks like disease detection (Ouhami, 2021) , self -driving car s (Janai, et al., \r\n2020) , sports (Thomas, et al., 2017) , and so on. With the growing use of machine learning \r\nin every field possible, it only makes sense to harness its power in the field of medical \r\nscience.  \r\nThis project focuses on the use of computer vision in the field of digestive capsule \r\nendoscopy. Capsule -endoscopy is a medical procedure where the patient swallows a \r\nwireless camera which after passing through their entire digestive tract provides v isual \r\ninformation about their gastrointestinal tract. Each frame of the video is then manually \r\nanalyzed by endoscopists to detect any anomalies in the digestive tract (Hwang, et al., \r\n2021) . This process tends to be cumbersome an d requires high attention. With the help \r\nof a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN), the detection process can be automated. First, \r\nthe CNN model is trained on the publicly available dataset with augmentation, and after \r\nit has achieved a good validation accur acy, it can be deployed in a web service to be \r\nused by doctors.  \r\n \r\n1.1.2. Problem Statement  \r\nThe analysis of endoscopy videos is a time -consuming and tedious process for \r\nendoscopists. They need to check every frame of the video with great precision to check \r\nfor the presen ce of different kind s of anomalies such as ulcers, bleeding, inflammation, \r\nand tumors. The videos can be very long which makes  the process of reviewing the videos \r\ntake several hours or even days.  This long process of evaluation of videos can c ause \r\nstress to the endoscopists resulting in improper diagnosis which may even lead to fatality. 2 | P a g e  \r\n The slow diagnosis can also be anxiety -inducing to the patients themselves  (Kugler, \r\n2022) . \r\n1.1.3. The Project as a Solution  \r\nThis project aims to automate the tedious process of analyzing the output video of \r\ndigestive endoscopy. Machine learning can be used to train a computer to be able to \r\nrecognize diseases in an image. This machine -learning model can then be deployed  \r\nonline to be used by endoscopists and researchers alike. The web application will be able \r\nto take in an image or a video, process it, and provide information about the input data. \r\nThis automated pipeline will make the process of detecting anomalies in dig estive \r\nendoscopy more streamlined.  \r\nFaster  diagnosis can also help alleviate stress for both endoscopists and patients alike. \r\nThe localization of diseases in the endoscopic images can be helpful to beginner \r\nendoscopists by aiding in their diagnosis.  \r\n1.1.4. Aspects of AI  \r\nComputer Vision  \r\nComputer vision is a field of artificial intelligence that focuses on enabling machines to \r\ninterpret and understand visual data from the world around them. It involves the use of \r\nalgorithms and mathematical models to analyze and extract information from images and \r\nvideos. Computer vision has applications in various industries, including healthcare, \r\nautomotive, and security, and is becoming increasingly important in areas such as \r\nrobotics and autonomous systems. Some of the key  techniques used in computer vision \r\ninclude image processing, object recognition, and machine learning. One of the most \r\npowerful tools in computer vision is the convolutional neural network (CNN), a type of \r\ndeep learning algorithm that is designed to recog nize patterns and features within images.  \r\nConvolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)  \r\nConvolutional Neural Network is a type of machine learning technique that extracts high -\r\nlevel spatial features from an image by convolving a kernel/filter through an image. The \r\nextracted feature is then fed to a Multi -layered Perceptron (MLP) to find a com plex relation 3 | P a g e  \r\n between those features and provided classes.\r\n \r\nFigure 1: Convolutional Neural Network  (Saha, 2022)  \r\nA CNN model usually consists of a convolutional layer, a pooling layer, and a fully \r\nconnec ted layer . \r\n \r\n1. Convolutional Layer : It is the main component of a CNN. In a convolutional layer, \r\na filter (square matrix with learnable parameters) is slid through the entire  \r\ninput image to form a high -level feature that preserves spatial information. \r\n \r\nFigure 2: Convolutional Operation (European Space Agency, 2022)  \r\n2. Pooling Layer : A pooling layer is used to reduce the dimens ions of the extracted \r\nfeatures. It down -samples the feature matrix while preserving information. Usually, \r\ntwo types of pooling are employed: average pooling and max pooling. Average \r\n4 | P a g e  \r\n pooling outputs the average of data points over the kernel size whereas ma x \r\npolling returns the largest value among the kernels.  \r\n \r\n3. Fully Connected Layer : This part of the CNN consists of most of the learnable \r\nparameters of the network. It is a connection of a dense layer that usually collapses \r\ninto a SoftMax layer at the end. Th e SoftMax layer outputs the probability that an \r\nitem belongs to a specific class. The output of the convolutional layers is flattened \r\nand fed to this connection of dense layers.  \r\n \r\n1.2. Aims  \r\nTo detect diseases in the digestive tract automatically  and provide  its localizations . \r\nUsing labeled data, computer -vision models such as CNN can be developed to find \r\npatterns in the data to be able to recognize different types of diseases. This capability of \r\nCNNs can be used to automatically detect diseases in the digest ive tract with out the need \r\nfor human intervention. This allows for fast diagnosis resulting in faster treatment which \r\nin most case s is a matter of life and death  (Aljarad & Mobayed, 2021) . GradCAM is the \r\nmethod of representation of learned weights from the filters of a convolutional model in \r\nthe input image (Selvaraju, et al., 2017) . Grad -CAM is used to represent how a CNN \r\nmodel makes its decision. This localizat ion provided by Grad -CAM can be used to find \r\nnew ways of identifying diseases. The u se of Grad -CAM makes the more transparent and \r\ntrustworthy.  \r\n1.3. Objectives  \r\n1. To create a model which takes in image s or video of digestive endoscopy and provides \r\nan accurate classification of diseases.  \r\n2. To create a model capable of visualizing localizations of detected diseases  \r\n3. To streamline the diagnostic process of Capsule Digestive Endoscopy resulting in \r\nfaster treatment and recovery.  5 | P a g e  \r\n 4. To design and develop a web-based application that can be used by endoscopists to \r\nautomatically detect diseases.  \r\n \r\n1.4. Artefacts  \r\n1.4.1. Functional Decomposition Diagram (FDD)  \r\n \r\nFigure 3: Functional Decomposition Diagram  \r\n1.4.2. System Design  \r\nThe system has  been divided into four sub -systems  with each having its responsibility. \r\nThe systems are briefly explained below:  \r\nUser Interaction System  \r\nA user interaction system is a fundamental part of any modern software application or \r\nsystem. It is essentially the front -end interface that enables users to interact with the \r\nsystem, input data, and retrieve results . In this context, a user interaction system is a \r\nweb-based interface that allows doctors to input patient information and endoscopic \r\ndata. This data is then passed on to other subsystems within the larger system that will \r\nanalyze and process the data to generate meaningful results. Once the analysis is \r\ncomplete, the results are displayed back to the doctor via the same web interface.  This \r\ninterface can also be used by doctors to view past records and results of patients.  \r\n6 | P a g e  \r\n Data Preprocessing Network  \r\nMachine Learning models are constrained by the fact that they can only take data in the \r\nformat that they have been trained on. This sub -system is re sponsible for converting all \r\ndata sent by the user to the format that can be used by the machine learning model. The \r\nfirst take of this network is to convert video data into images. The images are then resized \r\nto pixel values corresponding to the modelâ€™s i nput size. The pixel value s are the n \r\nnormalized and converted to a special datatype called Tensors.  \r\nImage Classification Network  \r\nThe Image Classification Network is a crucial subsystem of the user interaction system, \r\nresponsible for analyzing and classifyi ng the images generated from the endoscopic data \r\nprovided by the doctors. It is the heart of the system, as it plays a vital role in generating \r\nmeaningful results that can aid doctors in diagnosing and treating their patients. In \r\nessence, the Image Classif ication Network is a Machine Learning model that has been \r\ntrained on a vast dataset of endoscopic images. The model learns to identify and classify \r\nspecific features within the images that are indicative of certain conditions or diseases.  \r\nImage Localizati on Network  \r\nThe Image Localization Network is a complimentary part of the Image Classification \r\nNetwork as it takes data output by that sub -system. This system is used to identify and \r\nlocate specific areas of interest within an image. In this case, this netw ork will locate \r\nregions in the endoscopic images responsible for the classification.  \r\nStorage and Data Management  \r\nStorage and Data Management is responsible  for handling all processes  related to storing \r\nand retrieving data from databases . All data coming f rom the User  Interaction System \r\nshould be saved in the database and after classification and localization ha ve been \r\ncompleted, this system is responsible for providing data related to the results. This system  \r\nis also responsible for converting all image an d video datatype to URL format while \r\nsending a response using an API.  7 | P a g e  \r\n 1.5. Academic Questions  \r\n1. Can the process of diagnosis of diseases in digestive endoscopy be automated with \r\nhigh accuracy and speed?  \r\n2. Can the automatic diagnosis provided be explained further using localized heatmaps?  \r\n1.6. Scopes  \r\n1. This application can be used by endoscopists in hospitals for fast and streamlined \r\nprocessing of digestive endoscopy data to detect anomalies.  \r\n2. It can also be used by researchers to compare their model s for accuracy evaluation.  \r\n1.7. Limitations  \r\n1. Less availability of data hampers the model\'s accuracy because of its inability to \r\ngeneralize to all kinds of data.  \r\n2. Literature Review  \r\n2.1. Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition  \r\nImage recognition tasks are often handled by Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs). \r\nCNN models can generate features from an image and make predictions using those \r\nfeatures. The ongoing trend in image classification was to create deeper networks for \r\nharder tasks. But this trend suffered from the complication of vanishing/exploding \r\ngradients. When the gradients are passed backward during backpropagation, gradients \r\nwith values less than 1 get vanished and gradients with values more than 0 explode. To \r\nsolve thi s issue, the authors of this paper introduce the concept of skip connections (He, 8 | P a g e  \r\n et al., 2016) , which allows information to bypass one or more layers directly. \r\n \r\nFigure 4: Skip Connection (He, et al., 2016)  \r\nThis skip connection makes the deeper model more immune to the problem of \r\nvanishing/exploding gradients. Because of the skip connection, the deeper layers are at \r\nleast able to learn the identity to maintain the same accur acy with the same model having \r\nlesser layers  (He, et al., 2016) . Because of the skip connection, the model is able to learn \r\nmore than the identity when needed. To evaluate the advantage of skip connections in \r\ndeeper networks, t he ImageNet dataset, which contains 1.4 million photos of 10,000 \r\nclasses , was first used to train the model . The d ataset containing images of different sizes \r\nwas randomly cropped into 224x224 pixels with color augmentation. After each \r\nconvolutional layer, Batch Normalization (BN) was applied for faster convergence and to \r\nprevent overfitting. Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) was used for learning  in the model \r\nand the learning rate was gradually reduced over the course of 600,000 iterations. The \r\nmini-batch s ize was set to 256.  \r\n9 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 5: Evaluation of ResNet models with other models (He, et al., 2016)  \r\nDifferent ResNet (Residual Networks) models were trained with a different number of \r\nlayers. The B and C i n the table above indicate a different type of skip connection. As \r\nevident from the table above, the ResNet model with 34 layers performs significantly \r\nbetter than both the VGGNet with 41 layers and GoogleNet with 44 layers. The top -5 \r\nerrors also drop for the ResNet models with the increase in layers which was not the case \r\nfor other networks.  \r\nFindings  \r\nAs the classification task at hand gets more complex, it is important to generate many \r\nhigh-level features from that image using deeper convolutions. Deeper networks suffer \r\nfrom the problem of vanishing/exploding gradients which can be solved using skip \r\nconnections. This fluidity provided by ResNet models allows us to develop very deep \r\nnetworks that can generate high -quality features requi red for the classification task.  \r\n2.2. Learning Deep Features for Discriminative Localization  \r\nConvolutional Neural Networks have been shrouded by the fact that the decision behind \r\ntheir prediction is often a mystery. (Zhou, et al., 2016)  aims to solve this issue by \r\ngenerating a localization map for the input image which is responsible for making the \r\nprediction. This process has been described as Class Activation Mapping (CAM).  \r\n10 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 6: Class Activation Mapping (Zhou, et al., 2016)  \r\nCNN models usually consist of two parts: convolutional layers and a fully connected layer. \r\nThe convolutional part of the model is responsible for generat ing features and the fully \r\nconnected layer is responsible for learning a complex relation between those features \r\nand labels. The complex relationship generated by the fully connected layer hides the \r\nreasoning behind the generation of those features. CAM re moves the use of fully \r\nconnected layers. Instead, it uses Global Average Pooling (GAP) (Lin, et al., 2013)  for \r\neach of the feature maps generated by the convolutional layer and multiplies it by a \r\nlearnable weight. The score gener ated is passed through a SoftMax layer to generate \r\npredictions. For an image, let ð‘“ð‘˜(ð‘¥,ð‘¦) be the output of an activation function of unit k in \r\nthe last convolution layer at the spatial region (ð‘¥,ð‘¦). The resulting output of GAP, ð¹ð‘˜ is \r\nâˆ‘ð‘“ð‘˜(ð‘¥,ð‘¦)ð‘¥,ð‘¦ . The input to the SoftMax for class c is ð‘†ð‘=âˆ‘ð‘¤ð‘˜ð‘\r\nð‘˜ð¹ð‘˜ where ð‘¤ð‘˜ð‘ is the weight \r\ncorresponding to class c for unit k. The output of the SoftMax for class c is given by,  \r\nð‘ƒð‘=exp(Sc)\r\nâˆ‘exp(Sc)c \r\nBy replacing the value of ð¹ð‘˜ into the class score ð‘†ð‘, we get  \r\nð‘†ð‘=âˆ‘ð‘¤ð‘˜ð‘âˆ‘ð‘“ð‘˜(ð‘¥,ð‘¦)\r\nð‘¥,ð‘¦ ð‘˜=âˆ‘âˆ‘kwkc\r\nx,yfk(x,y) \r\n11 | P a g e  \r\n The class activation map for class c, denoted as ð‘€ð‘, is a spatial representation where \r\neach element is determined by \r\nð‘€ð‘(ð‘¥,ð‘¦)=âˆ‘ð‘¤ð‘˜ð‘\r\nð‘˜ð‘“ð‘˜(ð‘¥,ð‘¦) \r\n(Zhou, et al., 2016)  \r\nThe process of up-sampling allows for the identification of image regions that are \r\nresponsible for the prediction by scaling the mapping back up to the size of the original \r\nimage.  \r\nGAP is prioritized over Global Max Pooling (GMP) because the authors believe that GAP \r\nfocus es on the entire spatial region whereas GMP focuses on only one part of the spatial \r\nregion. The generalization of GAP helps to generate a better mapping. Three prominent \r\nnetworks; AlexNet, VGGNet, and GoogLeNet were used for the evaluation of the \r\nalgorithm . For each network, the fully connected layers were replaced with a GAP \r\nfollowed by a SoftMax layer. Alongside removing the fully connected layers, a \r\nconvolutional layer of size 3 x 3, stride 1, and pad 1 with 1024 units w ere added. ImageNet \r\ndataset was us ed to train the model.  \r\nThe same error metric (top -1, top -5) were used for classification evaluation like in ILSVRC. \r\nThere was not much significant drop in performance regardless of removing millions of \r\nparameters (from the fully connected layer). There was  only a difference of 1 -2% \r\nclassification accuracy while using CAM. It is necessary for models to have good \r\nclassification accuracy to obtain a good class activation mapping.  12 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 7: Classification Error of CNN models with CAM (Zhou, et al., 2016)  \r\nA bounding box was generated around the localization using simple thresholding in order \r\nto evaluate its accuracy . The GoogLeNet -GAP achieved the lowest localization error of \r\n43% on top -5 which is a very goo d result considering that the model was not trained on \r\na single annotated image.  \r\n \r\nFigure 8: Localization Error of CNN models with CAM (Zhou, et al., 2016)  \r\n  \r\nFindings  \r\nThis paper presents a way of visualizing the reasoning behind the prediction of a CNN \r\nmodel using CAM. CAM can be used to generate accurate representations of the \r\nlocalizations without the need for annotated data. This trait is especially useful in the fie ld \r\nof medical AI where annotated data is less available. In the case of endoscopy, annotating \r\n13 | P a g e  \r\n data is very tedious so this advantage of CAM can be leveraged to generate localizations \r\nof diseases.  \r\n \r\n2.3. Grad -CAM: Why did you say that?  \r\nCNN models are often presented as a black box because the decision behind their \r\nprediction is not well known. Although it is known that the initial layers of CNN models \r\nextract low -level features like edges and shapes, the deeper layer extracts very complex \r\nhigh-level features  not comprehendible by us. Gradient Based Class Activation Mapping \r\n(Grad -CAM) localizes the area responsible for making that decision  (Selvaraju, et al., \r\n2017) . Grad -CAM adds to the idea of Class Activation Mapping (CAM).  \r\n \r\nFigure 9: Guided Grad -CAM (Selvaraju, et al., 2017)  \r\nTo generate the Grad -CAM visualization, the following steps are taken:  \r\n1. Forward pass: The input image is passed through CNN , and the output prediction \r\nis obtained. For this example, let\'s say CNN predicts that the image is a cat.  \r\n2. Backward pass: The gradients of the final fully connected layer with respect to the \r\npredicted clas s (cat) are calculated using backpropagation. These gradients represent \r\nthe importance of each node in the final fully connected layer for the prediction.  \r\n14 | P a g e  \r\n 3. Weighted sum: The gradients from step 2 are used to weight the activations of the \r\nfinal convolutional  layer. This is done by multiplying the gradients by the activations and \r\nsumming over the two nodes in the final fully connected layer. The resulting weighted \r\nactivations are a single value for each channel in the final convolutional layer.  \r\n4. Upsampling : The  weighted activations from step 3 are up-sampled  to the original \r\nresolution of the input image.  \r\n5. Overlay: The up -sampled activations from step 4 are overlaid . \r\nFindings  \r\nLike CAM, Grad -CAM can be used in the field of analyzing medical imagery because of \r\nits ability to localize entities without the need for annotated data. It offers greater flexibility \r\nand applicability compared to CAM, as it can be used with any CNN architecture and \r\ndoes not require any modifications to the network or training process. Grad -CAM also \r\nprovides a more direct and intuitive explanation of the network\'s decision -making process, \r\nas it uses the gradients of the final convolutional layer with respect to the predicted class \r\nto weigh the activations.  \r\n \r\n2.4. Improved classification and loca lization approach to small bowel \r\ncapsule endoscopy using convolutional neural network  \r\nThis journal article  (Hwang, et al., 2021)  has worked on a similar problem of detecting \r\nanomalies in pictures of digestive endoscopy. The mai n task at hand for this literature \r\nwas to classify images into three categories: Negative, Hemorrhagic, and Ulcerative. The \r\ndataset was extracted from 526 Small Bowel Capsule Endoscopy videos from a hospital \r\nwhich was manually labeled by expert endoscopist s. The final dataset contained about \r\n30,000 images after augmentation.  15 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 10: The m odel architecture of (Hwang, et al., 2021)  \r\nThe architecture proposed by this paper is a modification of a VGGNet. The network \r\nconsisted of 14 convolutional layers, followed by a max pooling layer after each two \r\nconvolutional layers. The modifications can be seen in section (a) of the image above. \r\nThe working of Grad -CAM can be seen in section (b). A total of t hree models were trained \r\nin this paper:  \r\n \r\n1. Combined Model:  \r\n16 | P a g e  \r\n Two binary classification models were trained separately, and the results were \r\ncombined to create this model.  \r\na. NH Model: Responsible for only classifying Hemorrhagic images and Negative \r\nimages.  \r\nb. NU Mod el: Responsible for only classifying Ulcerative images and Negative \r\nimages.  \r\n2. Binary Model: This model was trained to detect whether  the image contained any \r\nkind of anomalies (either Hemorrhagic or Ulcerative) or not.  \r\nThese two models were evaluated on metri cs such as Accuracy, Sensitivity, Specificity, \r\nNegative Predictive Value (NPV), and Positive Predictive Value (PPV). Both models were \r\nable to achieve good results in all the metrics.  \r\n \r\nFigure 11: Evaluation of Combined and Binary model of (Hwang, et al., 2021)  \r\n \r\nFindings  \r\nThis paper has proposed a new architecture for multi -class classification models. In the \r\ncase of anomalies in digestive endoscopy, there can be differe nt types of anomalies. \r\nThose anomalies can be further grouped  into specific categories (Hemorrhagic and \r\nUlcerative in this case). This grouping helps the model achieve a better score in the case \r\nof fewer data. The problem of few data can also be solved usi ng data augmentation as \r\ndone in the paper. The main takeaway of this paper can be to experiment with the use of \r\nan ensemble of single -class classification models instead of a multi -class classification \r\nmodel.  \r\n17 | P a g e  \r\n 2.5. Detecting early gastric cancer: Comparison  between the diagnostic \r\nability of convolutional neural networks and endoscopists  \r\nGlobally, gastric cancer ranks fourth among men\'s cancers and seventh among women\'s \r\ncancers, respectively.  Early diagnosis of gastric cancer can prevent death. The authors \r\nof this article compare the predictability power of an AI to the diagnosis capability of \r\nendoscopists. 13,000 images of endoscopy were collected from standard endoscopes \r\nand standard endoscopic video systems. A deep learning architecture, Single Shot \r\nMultiBo x Detector (SSD) was used to train the model  (Ikenoyama, et al., 2021) . The deep \r\nCNN models consisted of 16 layers and were built using the Caffe framework. SGD with \r\na fixed learning rate of 0.0001 was used to train the model. The model was evaluated \r\nusing similar evaluation metrics as mentioned in the paper above. To compare the \r\ndiagnosis prowess of the AI model, a total of 67 endoscopists were divided into two \r\ngroups: certified and non -certified. The inference was of th e CNN model was significantly \r\nhigher than the endoscopists. The sensitivity of the model was also very high as \r\ncompared to results by endoscopists. PPV and Specificity scores on the other hand seem \r\nto be lagging on the AI side.  \r\n \r\n 18 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 12: Comparison of CNN model with endoscopists (Ikenoyama, et al., 2021)  \r\nFindings  \r\nEndoscopy images are very difficult to diagnose on an image -by-image basis. Even \r\nthough endoscopists with greater training and experience can perform better than AI \r\nmodels, the use of AI in digestive endoscopy seems inevitable. CNN models can be used \r\nto aid lower -level endoscopists in making their diagnoses. The AI model in this case has \r\nhigher sensitivity, which means it can correctly class ify more anomalies. Because of this \r\nreason, AI models can serve as a mediator between the images and the endoscopists. \r\nInstead of shifting through the whole image, the endoscopists can only look at images \r\nthat have been flagged by the AI.  \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n19 | P a g e  \r\n 3. Project Me thodology  \r\nBefore undertaking any project of a decent size, proper planning is required. Proper plans \r\nand methodology should be set in stone before starting the project.  It is important for \r\nstakeholders to select a project methodology that suits their inter ests. Selecting the right \r\nmethodology is crucial to ensure that the project runs efficiently and that the final project \r\nmeets the needs of the stakeholder. For this project, I have chosen Extreme Programming \r\n(XP) as the project development methodology.  \r\nExtreme Programming (XP) is an agile software development paradigm that seeks to \r\ndeliver software of a better caliber while also improving the team\'s quality of life  (Agile \r\nAlliance, 2023) . Of the agile frameworks, XP is the most explicit in terms of the proper \r\nengineering techniques for software development.  It is excellent for any project which \r\nrequires a high level of flexibility and adaptability, which is true in our case. Any machine \r\nlearning project requires a high level of f lexibility. XP also focused on continuous  testing \r\nand integration. For any machine learning model to be deployed continuous testing is \r\nrequired both on the testing data and the real word data. If the model does not perform \r\nwell, it needs to be replaced  with a newer model.  XP also puts emphasis on frequent \r\nreleases and feedback. The feedback from stakeholders and domain professionals can \r\nbe taken into consideration for making changes to the modelâ€™s architecture.  \r\n4. Tools and Technologies  \r\n4.1. Software  \r\n4.1.1. Python  \r\nPython is an open -source programming language  commonly used in the field of machine \r\nlearning and data science. Python contains a large number  of frameworks and libraries \r\nlike TensorFlow, PyTorch, and OpenCV which are suitable for working with images and \r\nmachine learning models. Python codes are also easy to read and manage and can be \r\nscaled.  \r\n 20 | P a g e  \r\n 4.1.2. Django  \r\nDjango is a Python framework which can  be used to create web applications. Django, by \r\ndefault, provides a lot of web security features without needing to write code. This makes \r\nit suitable for projects involving sensitive data. Django can also be used to create REST \r\nAPIs that are scalable.  \r\n \r\n4.1.3. PyTorch  \r\n PyTorch i s an open -source Machine Learning framework used to develop and train deep \r\nneural networks. PyTorch provides a dynamic computational graph that allows for efficient \r\ncomputation of gradients during the backpropagation of CNNs. PyTorch  also has \r\nintegrated with CUDA which allows us to train machine learning models in the GPU. \r\nTraining in the GPU is a lot faster than training in CPU because of the number  of cores \r\nwe have in GPU. PyTorch also provides an easy API to create very complex mod els and \r\nallows us to use models that have  already been built by other engineers.  \r\n \r\n4.1.4. React and Tailwind CSS  \r\nReact is a popular JavaScript library for building user interfaces that provides a \r\ncomponent -based approach . It is an excellent choice for the f ront-end of this project \r\nbecause it helps to  create a modular, responsive, and interactive user interface that can \r\nhandle the image and video data. Because of the dynamic nature of my project and usage \r\nof multiple REST APIs, React was a better choice for t his project than vanilla JavaScript. \r\nTailwind CSS is a CSS library that allows us to style our webpage without explicitly writing \r\nCSS code. Using Tailwind, different class names can be added to component to style it. \r\nThis results in less code and less mess y file structure . \r\n \r\n4.1.5 . Visual Studio Code  \r\nVisual Studio Code in an Integrated Development Environment (IDE) developed by \r\nMicrosoft. Since it provides multiple useful extensions like Error Lens, Git Lens, Jupyter 21 | P a g e  \r\n Notebook, VS Code has been my primary IDE  for development of the web application \r\nand training of the model.  \r\n \r\n4.1.6. Git and GitHub  \r\nGit is a version control system that can be used to manage and track changes in codes. \r\nGitHub is a code -hosting service that integrates with Git. Keeping track of cha nges in \r\ncode knowing you can revert back to previous versions if things do not work out is the \r\nmain advantage of using Git.  \r\n \r\n4.2. Hardware  \r\n4.2.1 Nvidia Geforce RTX 3060 6GB  \r\nThe model for this project was trained on a laptop with Nvidia Geforce RTX 3060 car d \r\nwith 6 GB of VRAM. In some cases, where 6GB of RAM was not enough, the model was \r\ntrained on Google Collab which offers 12GB of RAM but with less computational power.  \r\n \r\n5. Artefact Designs  \r\nLegend  \r\nSub Systems:  \r\nâ€¢ UIS: User Interaction System  \r\nâ€¢ DPS: Data Pre-processing Network  \r\nâ€¢ ICS: Image Classification Network  \r\nâ€¢ ILN: Image Localization Network  \r\nâ€¢ SDM: Storage and Data Management  \r\nTypes of R