personal medical data is not easy. Luckily, there was a public dataset named \r\nHyperKvasir dataset (Borgli, et al., 2020) . The dataset contained about 44,000 images \r\nand 43 videos of length s ranging from 10 minutes to 30 m inutes. Since the videos were \r\nunlabeled, they were discarded for training. They were later manually clipped for testing. \r\nThe 4 8,000 images consisted of 14 classes:  \r\n- Normal Mucosa  \r\n- Pylorus  \r\n- Ileocecal Valve  \r\n- Ampulla of Vater  \r\n- Reduced Mucosal View  \r\n44 | P a g e  \r\n - Ulcer  \r\n- Polyp  \r\n- Foreign Bodies  \r\n- Erythematous  \r\n- Erosion  \r\n- Blood - Fresh  \r\n- Blood - Hematin  \r\n- Angiectasia  \r\n- Lymphangiectasia  \r\n \r\n6.2. Data Balancing  \r\nWith the help of Dr. Sagun Karki, I classified these 14 classes into two general classes: \r\nNormal and Pathological.  \r\n  \r\nClass Type  Class Name  Count  \r\nNormal  Normal Mucosa  34338  \r\nNormal  Pylorus  1529  \r\nNormal  Ileocecal Valve  4189  \r\nNormal  Ampulla of Vater  10 \r\nNormal  Reduced Mucosal View  2906  \r\nPathological  Ulcer  854 \r\nPathological  Polyp  55 45 | P a g e  \r\n Pathological  Foreign Bodies  776 \r\nPathological  Erythematous  159 \r\nPathological  Erosion  506 \r\nPathological  Blood - Fresh  446 \r\nPathological  Blood - Hematin  12 \r\nPathological  Angiectasia  866 \r\nPathological  Lymphangiectasia  592 \r\n \r\nThis was done for two reasons. First, to balance out the data since it is highly imbalanced , \r\nand second for clarity purpose s. For a layman, these two classes make much more sense \r\nthan specialized terms.  \r\nAs mentioned, the dataset was highly imbalanced with over 43000 images belonging to \r\nthe normal class  and only 5000 images belon ging to the pathological class. Four out of \r\nthe five normal classes had very large amo unt of images, so I wanted to sample them. \r\nTo get the number of images to sample from each class, I divided the number of images \r\nrequired by 4  which was 1212.  The samplin g method I chose was uniform sampling since \r\nthe images near each other were very similar.  46 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 34: Data Under sampling using Uniform Sampling  \r\nAfter sampling there w as an equal number  of images in the two general classes; Normal  \r\nand Pathological.  \r\n \r\n6.4. In -memory Data Augmentation  \r\nThe problem with many machine learning models is their inability to generalize to real -\r\nworld data. The distribution of data used for training may not always be representative of \r\nthe distribution of real -world data. For example, if we only have data that ha ve blood \r\npresent in the bottom -right part of the image, the model might not be able to recognize \r\nblood in other parts  of the image if it is in another shape or form. To solve this, we can \r\nuse the in-memory data augmentation feature which is provided by both PyTorch and \r\nTensor Flow. During training, a n image i s augmented to a different form as specified by \r\nthe user. The advantage of in -memory data augmentation over disk -based data \r\naugmentation is tha t it consumes less storage capacity and is faster.  \r\n47 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 35: In-memory data augmentation  \r\nFor all models mentioned below, the following data augmentations have been used:  \r\nâ€¢ Random Horizontal Flip with a 50% probability  \r\nâ€¢ Random Vertical Flip with a 50% probability  \r\nâ€¢ Random Rotation ranging from 30 degre es to 70 degrees.  \r\n \r\n6.5. Data Splitting  \r\nThe data was split in the ratio of 7:1:2 for training, validation,  and testing. The data split \r\nwas done without using any prebuilt libra ries. The data was sp lit into 70% train, 10% \r\nvalidation, and 20% test ensuring that all the dataset s contained the same distribution of \r\nclasses. This is important to ensure that the validation and test scores we are calculating \r\nwill be representative of re al-world  data.  \r\n \r\n48 | P a g e  \r\n 6.6. Model Architecture  \r\nSeeing the success of Residual Network s in classification task s for digestive endoscopy, \r\nI have used ResNet50 as my model. The number 50 refers to the depth of the network.  \r\nThe a dvantage of ResNet over other deep lea rning models is that this modelâ€™s \r\nperformance doesnâ€™t degrade with increase in layer s. The skip connection in ResNet \r\nallows for an easier flow of gradients.  49 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 36: Architecture of ResNet50  \r\n50 | P a g e  \r\n 6.7. Loss Function and Optimizer  \r\nCross Entropy Loss was chosen as the loss function for this task because the data is \r\nmulti -classe d. It is a measure of the difference between the predicted probability \r\ndistribution of the model and the actual probability distribution of the true labels. By using \r\nthis loss function, the optimizer tries to maximize the probability of an item  belonging to a \r\nclass. The main advantage of this loss function is that it penalizes the model when it \r\npredicts an incorrect class with high confidence.  \r\nSince th e specific classes were also imbalanced, weights were given  to the loss functions. \r\nFor classes with very little data (only 10 images of Ampulla of Vater), high weights were \r\ngiven. So, when the model misclassifies a class with high weightage, the normal los s is \r\nmultiplied by the weight. This allows the model to also focus on the class having very little \r\ndata.  \r\nAdam was chosen as the optimizer for this task because of its robustness compared to \r\nother optimizers. It includes features of both AdaGrad (to scale t he learning rate for each \r\nparameter based on historical gradients) and RMSProp (to smooth out gradients and \r\nspeed up convergence). These features of Adam make it robust for most machine \r\nlearning tasks including this one.  \r\n6.8. Evaluation Metric  \r\nThe primary evaluation metric chosen for this project was the F1 score. The F1 score is \r\nthe harmonic mean of Recall and Precision. Recall can be defined as the modelâ€™s ability \r\nto correct ly find all positive classes. A recall of 0.8 would mean that out of 100 positive \r\nclasses, the model was only able to predict 80% of those 100 classes. Precision can be \r\ndefined as the modelâ€™s ability to accurately make predictions. If a model makes 100 \r\npositive predictions but 20 of them are incorrect, the model is said to have 0.8 prec ision.  \r\nRecall gives the mean of these two terms.  \r\n 51 | P a g e  \r\n 6.9. Model Training and Opt imization  \r\nInstead of training one model and tuning it s hyperparameter, multiple models varying in \r\nboth architecture and hyperparameter were  trained and evaluated on both classification \r\nperformance and localization performance.  \r\nDisclaimer:  \r\nDuring the initial phases of training, while plotting the confusion mat rix, class ids were \r\nused instead of class names. Below is the mapping for the class index to names:  \r\nâ€¢ Ampulla of Vater: 0  \r\nâ€¢ Angiectasia: 1  \r\nâ€¢ Blood - fresh: 2  \r\nâ€¢ Blood - hematin: 3  \r\nâ€¢ Erosion: 4  \r\nâ€¢ Erythema: 5  \r\nâ€¢ Foreign body: 6  \r\nâ€¢ Ileocecal valve: 7  \r\nâ€¢ Lymphangiectasia: 8  \r\nâ€¢ Normal clean mucosa: 9  \r\nâ€¢ Polyp: 10  \r\nâ€¢ Pylorus: 11  \r\nâ€¢ Reduced mucosal view:  12 \r\nâ€¢ Ulcer: 13  \r\n \r\n6.9.1. Scratch ResNet 50 \r\nInitially , the plan was to train the model from scratch weights.  \r\nHyperparameters:  \r\nâ€¢ Batch Size: 32  \r\nâ€¢ Learning Rate: 0.001  \r\nâ€¢ Weighted Loss : No 52 | P a g e  \r\n â€¢ Dropouts: 0.2  \r\nâ€¢ Max Epochs: 100  \r\n \r\nFigure 37: Training and Validation loss of Scratch ResNet50  \r\n \r\nFigure 38: Training and Validation accuracy of ResNet50  \r\nIn the graph above, it can be observed that the validation loss and accuracy is fluctuating \r\na lot.  Even though there is a lot of fluctuation, the trends in loss seem to be going down, \r\nwhich indicates that the model is not overfitting. It could also be the cause of less batch \r\n53 | P a g e  \r\n size. All 14 classes may not  be in a single batch of validation, which could result in \r\nfluctuations. This can also be the cause of less data.   \r\n \r\nFigure 39: Confusion Matrix of ResNet50 for test data  \r\nIt can be seen from the confusion matrix that the model has performed well with an F1  \r\nScore of 0.876 and an accuracy of 90% on the test dataset.  Although this model can be \r\ndeemed fit for use in the real  world based on the metrics above, the localization was not \r\nvery appealing.  \r\n \r\nFigure 40: Localization visualization for scratch ResNet50 (1)   \r\n54 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 41: Localization visualization for scratch ResNet50 ( 2) \r\n \r\nFigure 42: Localization visualization for scratch ResNet50 ( 3) \r\n55 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 43: Localization visualization for scratch ResNet50 ( 4) \r\nIn the image groups above, the image on the left side of the group is the original image, \r\nand the one in the middle is the heatmap generated by Grad -CAM where red denotes \r\nthat the model is focusing on that part for prediction and blue denotes that the model has \r\nfewer  weights assigned to those parts. The image on the right side of the group is the \r\nheatmap overlayed on the original image.  \r\nIn the first three image groups, the anom alies are red and in the fourth one, the anomaly \r\nis the white part of the image.  While looking at the heatmaps, we can see that the model \r\nhas not learned properly and is not basing its prediction on the infected part of the image.  \r\nMost of the heatmaps abov e are covered by red which means that the model looks at all \r\nparts of the image with equal weightage. This problem could be the reason for training \r\nthe model from scratch weights. Since there w ere very fewer  data as compared to how \r\nlarge of a dataset these  models are trained on, the model was not able to learn high -level \r\ntask-specific features.  \r\n \r\n6.9.2. Finetuning ResNet50  \r\nTransfer Learning  \r\nWith limited hardware capability and limited data, it is hard to train a machine -learning \r\nmodel that can perform on par with other state -of-the-art models.  Instead of training a \r\nnew model from scratch, we can leverage the power of transfer learning. Transfer learning \r\n56 | P a g e  \r\n refers to the method of taking a machine learning model that has alre ady been trained on \r\na huge dataset and retraining it in our small dataset for our task. This works, especially  in \r\nCNN, because the initial layers of CNN are responsible for learning low -level features \r\nsuch as edges, lines, and shapes. These features are us eful for every kind of task. So, \r\nwe can take the initial layers of CNN models that ha ve already been trained, remove the \r\nfully connected layers responsible for learning the relationship, freeze the weights of the \r\nconvolutional layers , and add our own fully  connected layer suitable for our task.  \r\n \r\nFigure 44: Transfer Learning Methodology  \r\nFor this task, I chose ResNet50 trained on the ImageNet dataset (Stanford Vision Lab, \r\n2021) . Different variations of th e fully connected layers were used but I will be discussing \r\ntwo architectures in detail.  \r\n- Architecture 1 ( ResNet50  Pretrained  1) \r\no Architecture  \r\nâ–ª Dense Layer (14 neurons)  \r\no Epochs  \r\nâ–ª 20 \r\n \r\n- Architecture 2 ( ResNet50  Pretrained  2) \r\no Architecture  \r\nâ–ª Dense Layer (512 neurons)  \r\nâ–ª Dropout (0.5 probability)  \r\nâ–ª Dense Layer (14 neurons)  \r\no Epochs  \r\nâ–ª 5 \r\nWith very few changes in the architecture, there was a drastic change in the performance \r\nof the localization.  Unlike training the model from scratch, the training loss and validation \r\nloss decreased smoothly on both of these architectures.  \r\n57 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 45: Training and Validation loss for Pretrained ResNet50   \r\n \r\nFigure 46: Training and Validation accuracy for Pretrained ResNet50  \r\nThe training seems to saturate at about 20 epochs with less decrease in loss after that \r\npoint.  \r\n58 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 47: Confusion Matrix of ResNet50  Pretrained  1 \r\n \r\nFigure 48: Confusion Matrix of Re sNet50  Pretrained  2 \r\n \r\nFigure 49: AUC and Sensitivity of ResNet50 Pretrained 1  \r\n59 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 50: AUC and Sensitivity of ResNet50 Pretrained 2  \r\n \r\n \r\nThere seems to be a negligible change in classification performance with a change in \r\nmodel architecture.  Altogether, it seems to perform better than training the model from \r\nscratch.  \r\n \r\nLegend:  \r\n- Blue Glow: ResNet50  Pretrained  1 \r\n- Orange Glow: ResNet50  Pretrained  2 \r\n  \r\n60 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 51: Localization visualization for  ResNet50 Pretrained 1  (1) \r\n  \r\n \r\nFigure 52: Localization visualization for ResNet50 Pretrained 2 (1) \r\n61 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 53: Localization visualization f or ResNet50 Pretrained 1 ( 2) \r\n \r\nFigure 54: Localization visualization for ResNet50 Pretrained 2 (2) \r\n \r\n \r\n62 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 55: Localization visualization for ResNet50 Pretrained 1 ( 3) \r\n \r\nFigure 56: Localization visualization for ResNet50 Pretrained 2 (3) \r\n \r\n  \r\n63 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 57: Localization visualization for ResNet50 Pretrained 1 (4) \r\n \r\nFigure 58: Localization visualization for Res Net50 Pretrained 2 (4) \r\n \r\n  \r\n64 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 59: Localization visualization for ResNet50 Pretrained 1 ( 5) \r\n \r\nFigure 60: Localization visualization for ResNet50 Pretrained 2 (5) \r\nFrom the localizations provided above by  the two models, it can be seen that the first \r\nmodel gives localization in fewer  spaces with more confidence (darker reds and blues) , \r\nand the second model gives localization in multiple spaces with less con fidence (light \r\nreds, light blues, green, yellow).  The reason for this to happen could be because of less \r\namount of layers in the fully connected layer. The first model only has one dense layer \r\nwhereas the second model has two dense layer s. When there are less dense layers, the \r\nfeature maps genera ted by the convolutional layers should be more featureful and \r\n65 | P a g e  \r\n informative than can be used without much modification. This allows the model to learn \r\nvery high -level features which in  turn results in high -confidence localizations.  \r\n \r\n6.10. Integration with th e system  \r\nThe model was trained separately, and the weights of the models were saved. The \r\nconnection of the AI was done with the system using a REST API which was developed \r\nusing the Django REST framework. Instead of creating one API which does all the task s \r\nfrom data pre-processing  to classification and localization, I created multiple API s serving \r\nspecific purpose s. This was done to give the user information about the task that was \r\nbeing done in the present.  The API endpoints used for the connection of the  AI with the \r\nsystem are listed below in order of usage.  \r\n \r\n6.10.1. /patient -info API \r\nRequest Type: POST  \r\nPayload:  \r\n- name : Name of the patient  \r\n- patients_age : Age of the patient  \r\n- detail : Extra details of the patient  \r\n- file: Endoscopic video or image  \r\n \r\nThis API is called when the patientâ€™s  information is first given by the user. This API \r\nstores the data in the database and must be called before calling other APIs.   \r\n \r\n6.10.2. /crop API  \r\nRequest TYPE: POST  \r\nPayload:  66 | P a g e  \r\n - patient_id : ID of the patient who se video/image to crop.  \r\n- x: Start position of the crop in the x-axis. \r\n- y: Start position of the crop in the y-axis. \r\n- w: Width of output video/image  \r\n- h: Height of output video/image  \r\nThe model only takes input images with the aspect ratio of 1:1 but most of the vid eos and \r\nimages are in the format of 16:9. This problem left unattended seriously hampers the \r\nmodelâ€™s prediction capability. To solve this, all images/videos are cropped to the \r\ndimensions provided by the user.  \r\n \r\n6.10.3. /video -to-image  API \r\nRequest Type: POST  \r\nPayload:  \r\n- patient_id: ID of the patient whose videos to convert into images.  \r\nThe model also only takes images and inputs. So, videos need to be converted to images \r\nbefore they can be processed by the model. This endpoint  converts the pati entâ€™s video \r\nfile to images.  \r\n \r\n6.10.4. /resize -images  API \r\nRequest Type: POST  \r\nPayload:  \r\n- patients_id: ID of the patient whose images to resize.  \r\nSince the model takes images of a certain input size, it is necessary to convert all images \r\nto the size accepted by the model. This API resizes all images to the size so that they can \r\nbe fed into the model.  \r\n 67 | P a g e  \r\n 6.10.5. /predict  API \r\nRequest Type: POST  \r\nPayload : \r\n- patients_id: ID of the patient whose images to get classifications and localizations \r\nfor \r\nThis is the main API endpoint responsible for generating classifications and localizations.  \r\nFirst, it checks whether the patient id exists or not and if it does not, it throws an error. \r\nAfter that , it loads all of the images that need to be fed to the model into a DataLoader \r\nwhich feed s the data to the model in batches. The prediction model i s initialized and the \r\nweights fit into the model. All of the images are fed to the model in batches, a nd the \r\npredictions are stored in the database.  After predictions, the data is again forward passed \r\nthrough the model to generate heatmaps. The gradient of all feature maps of the final \r\nlayer is computed and summed up. The output is a low -resolution heatmap  that is scaled \r\nto the size of the image. The heatmap is also overlayed over the original image to better \r\nunderstand the heatmap. Both the heatmap and the overlayed image are saved in the \r\ndatabase.  \r\n \r\n6.10.6. /patient -info/<int:id> API  \r\nRequest Type: GET \r\nThis API endpoint is responsible for showing the results generated by the predict API. \r\nWhenever this endpoint is hit, the data stored in the database are collected and sent to \r\nthe front  end via this API. The results then are shown in a user -friendly way.  \r\n \r\n7. Conclusion  \r\nThe main objective of this project was to develop a system capable of classifying images \r\nof digestive endoscopy along with its localization.  The final model produced has a good \r\nclassification score with an F1 score of 0.95. Given the size of the  dataset and the 68 | P a g e  \r\n hardware the model was trained on, this is a good score. Localizations also seem to be \r\nperforming well which was compared with in cross -reference to a doctor.   \r\nDuring the development phase, the model was trained on a GPU, which is fast. Bu t to \r\nshift the model to production, it needs to run on a CPU to save costs. So, it takes a g ood \r\namount of time to generate predictions and localizations for video. From the results \r\npresented in this report, it is evident that better localizations can be ge nerated by using \r\nless amount of fully connected layers.  This happens because the model needs to \r\ngenerate better feature maps for the less powerful fully connected layers to make correct \r\npredictions . \r\nOverall, this project aimed to create a system capable of  streamlining the diagnosis \r\nprocess of Capsule Digestive Endoscopy by accurately classifying diseases and \r\ngenerating localization.  The localizations can be beneficial in making the model more \r\ntransparent and help attract more possible uses . \r\n8. Critical Ev aluation  \r\nAfter completion of this report, I can say that I have prepared a comprehensive and well -\r\nstructured document that present s the finding of my work.  By writing this report, I have \r\ngained an even deeper understanding of the project I have been doing.  It was truly a one-\r\nof-a-kind experience doing this project from scratch. The most significant finding of my \r\nreport is the change in localization confidence with the change in a number of fully \r\nconnected layers.  It was also a great learning experience as I  was able to familiarize \r\nmyself with technology stacks that are used in the real world for this use case . \r\nInitially, I found it difficult to start this project but as the scope of the project started \r\nbecoming more closed and focused, I was able to make fast progress. The model training \r\npart was also stressful as it took a lot of time to train the model and I needed to change \r\nhyperparameters every so often.  Overall, I believe I have created a system that can be \r\ndeployed to be used in a real hospital. The user interface is very user -friendly and minimal, \r\nand the machine learning model has good evaluation scores. The heatmaps generated \r\nare also of good quality.  69 | P a g e  \r\n Being someone who has always been interested in AI and wanted to start his career in \r\nAI, this proj ect has been a huge contributor to my success. During the lifecycle of this \r\nproject, I was able to land a job at a prestigious Nepali company as a n ML Engineer. I \r\nbelieve that the amount of research and time I had poured into this project was a key \r\nfactor in my getting that job.  70 | P a g e  \r\n 9. Evidence of Project Management  \r\n9.1. Log Sheet  71 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 61: Log Sheet 1  \r\n72 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 62: Log Sheet 2  \r\n73 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 63: Log Sheet 3 \r\n74 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 64: Log Sheet 4 \r\n75 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 65: Log Sheet 5 \r\n76 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 66: Log Sheet 6 \r\n77 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 67: Log Sheet 7 \r\n78 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 68: Log Sheet 8 \r\n79 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 69: Log Sheet 9 \r\n80 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 70: 