\n(Zhou, et al., 2016)  \r\nThe process of up-sampling allows for the identification of image regions that are \r\nresponsible for the prediction by scaling the mapping back up to the size of the original \r\nimage.Figure 30: Data coming  from UIS being stored in the database  \r\n40 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 31: Data coming from ICN and ILN  being stored in the database  (1) \r\n \r\nFigure 32: Data coming from ICN and ILN being stored in the database (2)  \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n41 | P a g e  \r\n 5.5.3.The first model only has one dense layer \r\nwhereas the second model has two dense layer s. When there are less dense layers, the \r\nfeature maps genera ted by the convolutional layers should be more featureful and \r\n65 | P a g e  \r\n informative than can be used without much modification.Artefact Designs  \r\nLegend  \r\nSub Systems:  \r\nâ€¢ UIS: User Interaction System  \r\nâ€¢ DPS: Data Pre-processing Network  \r\nâ€¢ ICS: Image Classification Network  \r\nâ€¢ ILN: Image Localization Network  \r\nâ€¢ SDM: Storage and Data Management  \r\nTypes of Requirements:  \r\nâ€¢ F: Functional Requirements  22 | P a g e  \r\n â€¢ NF: Non -Functional Requirements  \r\nâ€¢ UR: Usability Requirements  \r\n \r\n \r\n5.1 User Interaction Sy stem (UIS)  \r\n5.1.1.SDM : Software Requirements Specifications  \r\nRequirement \r\nCode  Requirement Description  Use Case  MoSCoW \r\nPrioritization  \r\nSDM -NF-1.0 All of the data coming from UIS \r\nshould be stored in the database  Data Storage  Must Have  \r\nSDM -NF-2.0 All of the outputs coming from ICN \r\nand ILN should be stored in the \r\ndatabase  Data Storage  Must Have  \r\nSDM -NF-3.0 All fields of the database should \r\nhave constraints to minimize \r\nspace complexity  Data Integrity  Shoul d Have  \r\nSDM -NF-4.0 Image s and videos should be \r\nconverted to hosted URL while \r\nsending a response  Data Handling  Must  Have  \r\n \r\n5.5.2.Figure 27: Heatmaps of images generated by the model   \r\n38 | P a g e  \r\n Test ILN-F-5.0 \r\nTest Description: The system should allow user s to view the image with and without a \r\nheatmap.58 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 47: Confusion Matrix of ResNet50  Pretrained  1 \r\n \r\nFigure 48: Confusion Matrix of Re sNet50  Pretrained  2 \r\n \r\nFigure 49: AUC and Sensitivity of ResNet50 Pretrained 1  \r\n59 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 50: AUC and Sensitivity of ResNet50 Pretrained 2  \r\n \r\n \r\nThere seems to be a negligible change in classification performance with a change in \r\nmodel architecture.Combined Model:  \r\n16 | P a g e  \r\n Two binary classification models were trained separately, and the results were \r\ncombined to create this model.Figure 16: System showing error for not entering data in all required fields  \r\n  \r\n27 | P a g e  \r\n Test UIS-F-5.0, UIS -NF-6.0 \r\nTest Description: The system should allow users to crop image s and videos  and show \r\nthe cropped image/video.18 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 12: Comparison of CNN model with endoscopists (Ikenoyama, et al., 2021)  \r\nFindings  \r\nEndoscopy images are very difficult to diagnose on an image -by-image basis.6 | P a g e  \r\n Data Preprocessing Network  \r\nMachine Learning models are constrained by the fact that they can only take data in the \r\nformat that they have been trained on.Image Classification Network  \r\nThe Image Classification Network is a crucial subsystem of the user interaction system, \r\nresponsible for analyzing and classifyi ng the images generated from the endoscopic data \r\nprovided by the doctors.Transfer learning \r\n56 | P a g e  \r\n refers to the method of taking a machine learning model that has alre ady been trained on \r\na huge dataset and retraining it in our small dataset for our task.47 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 35: In-memory data augmentation  \r\nFor all models mentioned below, the following data augmentations have been used:  \r\nâ€¢ Random Horizontal Flip with a 50% probability  \r\nâ€¢ Random Vertical Flip with a 50% probability  \r\nâ€¢ Random Rotation ranging from 30 degre es to 70 degrees.10 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 6: Class Activation Mapping (Zhou, et al., 2016)  \r\nCNN models usually consist of two parts: convolutional layers and a fully connected layer.Figure 17: User cropping the image according to user\'s choice  \r\n28 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 18: User viewing data for the final time before sending for prediction  \r\n \r\n5.2.Store \r\nPatientsâ€™ \r\nMetadata  Must Have  \r\nUIS-NF-1.1 Required fields should have a \r\nplaceholder  Ease of Use  Could Have  \r\nUIS-F-2.0 All fields must be filled by the user  Ensure Data \r\nIntegrity  Should Have  \r\nUIS-NF-2.1 Error should be shown if all field s \r\nare not filled  Error \r\nHandling  Could Have  \r\nUIS-UR-2.1 Errors should be highlighted in red  Better \r\nUsability  Could Have  \r\nUIS-NF-2.2 A success message should be \r\nshown after completion of the form Error \r\nHandling  Could Have  \r\nUIS-UR-2.2 Success messages should be \r\nhighlighted in green  Better \r\nUsability  Could Have  \r\nUIS-F-3.0 The system should allow users to \r\nenter patientsâ€™ endoscopic video s \r\nor images.9 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 5: Evaluation of ResNet models with other models (He, et al., 2016)  \r\nDifferent ResNet (Residual Networks) models were trained with a different number of \r\nlayers.Since the model takes images of a certain input size, it is necessary to convert all images \r\nto the size accepted by the model.Model Training and Opt imization  \r\nInstead of training one model and tuning it s hyperparameter, multiple models varying in \r\nboth architecture and hyperparameter were  trained and evaluated on both classification \r\nperformance and localization performance.46 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 34: Data Under sampling using Uniform Sampling  \r\nAfter sampling there w as an equal number  of images in the two general classes; Normal  \r\nand Pathological.Figure 15: User entering patientâ€™s details and endoscopic image  \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n26 | P a g e  \r\n Test UIS-F-2.0, UIS -NF-2.1, UIS -UR-2.1 \r\nTest Description: The system should show an error if not all required fields are input .After that , it loads all of the images that need to be fed to the model into a DataLoader \r\nwhich feed s the data to the model in batches.All data coming f rom the User  Interaction System \r\nshould be saved in the database and after classification and localization ha ve been \r\ncompleted, this system is responsible for providing data related to the results.For example, if we only have data that ha ve blood \r\npresent in the bottom -right part of the image, the model might not be able to recognize \r\nblood in other parts  of the image if it is in another shape or form.Image Localizati on Network  \r\nThe Image Localization Network is a complimentary part of the Image Classification \r\nNetwork as it takes data output by that sub -system.Given the size of the  dataset and the 68 | P a g e  \r\n hardware the model was trained on, this is a good score.Hyperparameters:  \r\nâ€¢ Batch Size: 32  \r\nâ€¢ Learning Rate: 0.001  \r\nâ€¢ Weighted Loss : No 52 | P a g e  \r\n â€¢ Dropouts: 0.2  \r\nâ€¢ Max Epochs: 100  \r\n \r\nFigure 37: Training and Validation loss of Scratch ResNet50  \r\n \r\nFigure 38: Training and Validation accuracy of ResNet50  \r\nIn the graph above, it can be observed that the validation loss and accuracy is fluctuating \r\na lot.49 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 36: Architecture of ResNet50  \r\n50 | P a g e  \r\n 6.7.Model Architecture  \r\nSeeing the success of Residual Network s in classification task s for digestive endoscopy, \r\nI have used ResNet50 as my model.Since it provides multiple useful extensions like Error Lens, Git Lens, Jupyter 21 | P a g e  \r\n Notebook, VS Code has been my primary IDE  for development of the web application \r\nand training of the model.12 | P a g e  \r\n  \r\nFigure 7: Classification Error of CNN models with CAM (Zhou, et al., 2016)  \r\nA bounding box was generated around the localization using simple thresholding in order \r\nto evaluate its accuracy .Since there w ere very fewer  data as compared to how \r\nlarge of a dataset these  models are trained on, the model was not able to learn high -level \r\ntask-specific features.So, \r\nwe can take the initial layers of CNN models that ha ve already been trained, remove the \r\nfully connected layers responsible for learning the relationship, freeze the weights of the \r\nconvolutional layers , and add our own fully  connected layer suitable for our task.For any machine learning model to be deployed continuous testing is \r\nrequired both on the testing data and the real word data.Binary Model: This model was trained to detect whether  the image contained any \r\nkind of anomalies (either Hemorrhagic or Ulcerative) or not.In \r\nessence, the Image Classif ication Network is a Machine Learning model that has been \r\ntrained on a vast dataset of endoscopic images.In the case of endoscopy, annotating \r\n13 | P a g e  \r\n data is very tedious so this advantage of CAM can be leveraged to generate localizations \r\nof diseases.Integration with th e system  \r\nThe model was trained separately, and the weights of the models were saved.The model training \r\npart was also stressful as it took a lot of time to train the model and I needed to change \r\nhyperparameters every so often.Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)  \r\nConvolutional Neural Network is a type of machine learning technique that extracts high -\r\nlevel spatial features from an image by convolving a kernel/filter through an image.Class Type  Class Name  Count  \r\nNormal  Normal Mucosa  34338  \r\nNormal  Pylorus  1529  \r\nNormal  Ileocecal Valve  4189  \r\nNormal  Ampulla of Vater  10 \r\nNormal  Reduced Mucosal View  2906  \r\nPathological  Ulcer  854 \r\nPathological  Polyp  55 45 | P a g e  \r\n Pathological  Foreign Bodies  776 \r\nPathological  Erythematous  159 \r\nPathological  Erosion  506 \r\nPathological  Blood - Fresh  446 \r\nPathological  Blood - Hematin  12 \r\nPathological  Angiectasia  866 \r\nPathological  Lymphangiectasia  592 \r\n \r\nThis was done for two reasons.', 1, '110_2059521_reportpdf-1', '2024-01-31 10:17:30', '2024-02-09 20:04:33'),
	(16, 2, 'Why do we shop.docx', 18247, 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document', 'Why do we shop?\n\nShopping is a complex activity that can be affected by various cultural, social psychological, natural, and economic factors. Analyzing the fundamental needs and motivations that encourage consumers to shop is essential to comprehend why we shop. Some of the reasons behind the shopping are;\n\n1, Essential Needs and Survival: Supplying for essentials like clothing, shelter, and food is the main purpose of shopping. These are survival needs the basic, and shopping represents a way of obtaining the supplies essential to everyday living.\n\n2, Personalized Expression: Among the ways for expressing themselves, using shopping Individuals often convey their personalities, tastes, and their sense of fashion through the items that they decide to put on, decorate, and use in various manners. Our purchases may act as an insight into the way we are and a means of expressing ourselves.\n\n3, Cultural and Festive Rituals: Shopping and social and celebratory traditions go together hand in hand. During seasons, anniversaries, and other occasions, individuals exchange gifts as an act of showing their feelings of affection, admiration, and kindness.\n\n4, Influence of Advertising and Promoting: It is difficult to underestimate the capacity of advertisements and marketing to influence. Businesses utilize an array of techniques to attract the curiosity of consumers, sell what they sell, and influence how they make purchases. The media, online platforms, and different kinds of advertising are extremely significant when assessing the personal preferences of customers.\n\nA, Teenagers might recognize hedonic adaptation as a personâ€™s tendency to swiftly adjust to positive changes in life and return to their first level of pleasure. The first rush of pleasure or joy fades off with a period much like the moment you get used to everything fun or interesting. As an example, the sense of achievement that comes with getting an updated cell phone ultimately fades off because, while it may feel awesome at first, it quickly turns into a new normal. Teenagers who understand hedonic adaptation will be more likely to value lifeâ€™s happenings and avoid relying excessively on material things for satisfaction.\n\nB, Teenagers\' finances could be affected by hedonic adaptation, which may outcome in expenditure habits that emphasize instant satisfaction. Teens who constantly search for innovative products that meet their temporary needs- such as the latest gadgets, or trendy clothing, may spend while ending up dissatisfied in the long term. This bias could lead to purchases on impulse, and this makes a challenging to save income for more important goals. Teens may mitigate the impact of this by adopting financial accountability, offering financial goals for the future the most importance, and seeking enjoyment and experiences in life instead of material things. David, for instance, often wastes money buying fashionable clothes to be up-to-date with the most recent trends. He feels pleased after each fresh piece of clothing he purchases, but his initial excitement diminishes very quickly as a result of the speed with which the latest fashions change. His collected expenses on trends may result in his financial trouble without providing him with long-term fulfillment.\n\nC, Teams can set specific budget objectives, including saving for a future vacation or university, to offset the effect of hedonic adaptation while making better choices regarding their finances. Set priorities and efforts that will end up resulting in lasting fulfillment over temporary pleasures. As opposed to hurrying into buying decisions, we can learn how to wait for things. Setting away money for a wanted item, which might improve its general worth and pleasure upon purchase can be considered. Spend money on opportunities (like vacations and activities) instead of goods. The longer-lasting joy and recollections are frequently generated by events. Money can be saved every single month from the allowance or payment as well.\n\nConclusion\n\nIn the end, shopping is a multifaceted activity that is shaped by advertising, customs of culture, individual expression, and fundamental needs. The concept of hedonic adaptation highlights the challenges of achieving a balance between short-term happiness and long-term fulfillment, and it is particularly relevant to teenagers. People may approach shopping with greater financial accountability and overall happiness when they set clear budgetary goals, give long-term goals importance, and find satisfaction through activities instead of material things.\n\n\n\n\n\nReflection ko answer\n\nTo overcome the impact of transitory impulses, we need to foster mindfulness and establish strategies for preventing impulsive decisions when scrolling via the Internet and paying attention to hedonic adaptation. The luxury of the choice to wait before purchasing something when we come across something that attracts us. Evaluation can be done to see if our desire to buy is a result of an urgent need or a passing pleasure. We may set an amount of time before buying any things that are not essential. We can give it at least one day to reflect on whether the product is value of money. There might also be a budget made aside for free money spent on unnecessary things. By identifying objectives for our buying decisions, we can make sure that our money gets spent on goods that improve our standards of living. Regularly update the feats we receive on social media by ignoring profiles that make us hesitate to make sudden purchases and unsubscribe from emails that provide special and savings opportunities all of the time. Urge ourselves regularly to be appreciative of everything that we have right now and to take inventory of our assets. The continuous craving for more could be mitigated by focusing on appreciation.