	(17, 2, 'Why Do We Shop (2).docx', 278975, 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document', '2\r\n\r\n1\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhy Do We Shop Video Assignment-W2\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nManisha Timalsina\r\n\r\nPresidential Business School\r\n\r\nMTH 120c-Personal Finance\r\n\r\nProfessor Dahal\r\n\r\n 21 January, 2024\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(Q.N.1)\r\n\r\nThe Social Media PSA Post has been inserted below; \r\n\r\n\r\nWhy do we shop?\r\n\r\nShopping is a complex activity that can be affected by various cultural, social psychological, natural, and economic factors. Analyzing the fundamental needs and motivations that encourage consumers to shop is essential to comprehend why we shop. Some of the reasons behind the shopping are;\r\n\r\n1, Essential Needs and Survival: Supplying for essentials like clothing, shelter, and food is the main purpose of shopping. These are survival needs the basic, and shopping represents a way of obtaining the supplies essential to everyday living.\r\n\r\n2, Personalized Expression: Among the ways for expressing themselves, using shopping Individuals often convey their personalities, tastes, and their sense of fashion through the items that they decide to put on, decorate, and use in various manners. Our purchases may act as an insight into the way we are and a means of expressing ourselves.\r\n\r\n3, Cultural and Festive Rituals: Shopping and social and celebratory traditions go together hand in hand. During seasons, anniversaries, and other occasions, individuals exchange gifts as an act of showing their feelings of affection, admiration, and kindness.\r\n\r\n4, Influence of Advertising and Promoting: It is difficult to underestimate the capacity of advertisements and marketing to influence. Businesses utilize an array of techniques to attract the curiosity of consumers, sell what they sell, and influence how they make purchases. The media, online platforms, and different kinds of advertising are extremely significant when assessing the personal preferences of customers (HorvÃ¡th & AdÄ±gÃ¼zel, 2018).\r\n\r\nA, Teenagers might recognize hedonic adaptation as a personâ€™s tendency to swiftly adjust to positive changes in life and return to their first level of pleasure. The first rush of pleasure or joy fades off with a period much like the moment you get used to everything fun or interesting. As an example, the sense of achievement that comes with getting an updated cell phone ultimately fades off because, while it may feel awesome at first, it quickly turns into a new normal. Teenagers who understand hedonic adaptation will be more likely to value lifeâ€™s happenings and avoid relying excessively on material things for satisfaction.\r\n\r\nB, Teenagers\' finances could be affected by hedonic adaptation, which may outcome in expenditure habits that emphasize instant satisfaction. Teens who constantly search for innovative products that meet their temporary needs- such as the latest gadgets, or trendy clothing, may spend while ending up dissatisfied in the long term. This bias could lead to purchases on impulse, and this makes a challenging to save income for more important goals. Teens may mitigate the impact of this by adopting financial accountability, offering financial goals for the future the most importance, and seeking enjoyment and experiences in life instead of material things. David, for instance, often wastes money buying fashionable clothes to be up-to-date with the most recent trends. He feels pleased after each fresh piece of clothing he purchases, but his initial excitement diminishes very quickly as a result of the speed with which the latest fashions change. His collected expenses on trends may result in his financial trouble without providing him with long-term fulfillment.\r\n\r\nC, Teams can set specific budget objectives, including saving for a future vacation or university, to offset the effect of hedonic adaptation while making better choices regarding their finances. Set priorities and efforts that will end up resulting in lasting fulfillment over temporary pleasures. As opposed to hurrying into buying decisions, we can learn how to wait for things. Setting away money for a wanted item, which might improve its general worth and pleasure upon purchase can be considered. Spend money on opportunities (like vacations and activities) instead of goods. The longer-lasting joy and recollections are frequently generated by events. Money can be saved every single month from the allowance or payment as well (Lyubomirsky, 2010).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nQ.N.4, (Reflection Question)\r\n\r\nTo overcome the impact of transitory impulses, we need to foster mindfulness and establish strategies for preventing impulsive decisions when scrolling via the Internet and paying attention to hedonic adaptation. The luxury of the choice to wait before purchasing something when we come across something that attracts us. Evaluation can be done to see if our desire to buy is a result of an urgent need or a passing pleasure. We may set an amount of time before buying any things that are not essential. We can give it at least one day to reflect on whether the product is value of money. There might also be a budget made aside for free money spent on unnecessary things. By identifying objectives for our buying decisions, we can make sure that our money gets spent on goods that improve our standards of living. Regularly update the feats we receive on social media by ignoring profiles that make us hesitate to make sudden purchases and unsubscribe from emails that provide special and savings opportunities all of the time. \r\n\r\nWe can urge ourselves regularly to be appreciative of everything that we have right now and to take inventory of our assets. The continuous craving for more could be mitigated by focusing on appreciation. Evaluate the impact that whatever we purchase is going to have on the natural world and how it affects our health. Instead of concentrating on the instant excitement, contemplate the item\'s long-term worth and satisfaction.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nIn the end, shopping is a multifaceted activity that is shaped by advertising, customs of culture, individual expression, and fundamental needs. The concept of hedonic adaptation highlights the challenges of achieving a balance between short-term happiness and long-term fulfillment, and it is particularly relevant to teenagers. People may approach shopping with greater financial accountability and overall happiness when they set clear budgetary goals, give long-term goals importance, and find satisfaction through activities instead of material things.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nReference\r\n\r\nHorvÃ¡th, C., & AdÄ±gÃ¼zel, F. (2018). Shopping enjoyment to the extreme: Hedonic shopping motivations and compulsive buying in developed and emerging markets. Journal of Business Research, 86, 300â€“310. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbusres.2017.07.013\r\n\r\nLyubomirsky, S. (2010). Hedonic adaptation to positive and negative experiences. In Oxford University Press eBooks. https://doi.org/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780195375343.013.0011\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nShort Summary\r\n\r\nBelow is the link to the video for the presentation on Why Do We Shop.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWeb Link to Video: \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nhttps://drive.google.com/file/d/1LhJfEAJEDIyoN-hCnST6KVReFwFseglg/view?usp=sharing', 'Shopping is a complex activity that can be affected by various cultural, social psychological, natural, and economic factors. Analyzing the fundamental needs and motivations that encourage consumers to shop is essential to comprehend why we shop. Some of the reasons behind the shopping are; Supplying for essentials like clothing, shelter, and food is the main purpose of shopping.', 0, 'why-do-we-shop-2docx', '2024-02-01 12:21:25', '2024-02-09 19:58:54'),
