	(26, 2, '6CS005 - Assessment 23-24 (1).pdf', 282946, 'application/pdf', 'University of Wolverhampton  \nFaculty of Science and Engineering  \nDepartment of Mathematics and Computer Science  \nHerald College Kathmandu  \n \nModule Assessment  \n \nModule  6CS005 â€“ High Performance Computing  \nModule Leader  Hiran Patel  / Jnaneshwar Bohara  \nSemester  1 \nYear  2023/24 \nAssessment  Portfolio  \n% of module mark  100%  \nDue Date  Date will be published on Canvas  \nHand -in â€“ what?  Portfolio as specified in this document  \nHand -in- where?  Canvas  \nPass mark  40% \nMethod of retrieval  Submit the resit assessment (will be distributed at the end of the \nmodule) by end of resit week (July)  \nFeedback  Individual feedback via Canvas, in addition verbal feedback is \navailable in class.  \nCollection of \nmarked work  N/A \n \nAssessment overview  \nThis portfolio is split up into 4 separate tasks which will test your knowledge of advanced \nmultithreading and GPGPU programming using CUDA. Each task should be zipped up into a single zip \nfolder containing all C/CUDA and resource files for the submission on Canvas.  \n1. Password cracking using multithreading  (15% - 100 marks)  \nIn this task, you will be asked to use the â€œcryptâ€ library to decrypt a password using \nmultithreading. You will be provided with two programs. The first program called \nâ€œEncryptSHA512.câ€  which  allows you to encrypt a password. For this assessment , you will be \nrequired to decrypt a 4-character  password consisting of 2 capital  letters, and 2 numbers. The \nformat of the password should be â€œLetterLetterNumberNumber.â€ For example, â€œHP93.â€ Once \nyou have generated your password, this should then be entered into your program to decrypt \nthe password.  The method of input for the encrypted password is up to you.  The second \nprogram is a  skeleton code to crack the password in regular C without any multithread ing \nsyntax. Your task is to use multithreading  to split the workload over many threads  and find the \npassword. Once the password has been found, the program should finish meaning not all \ncombinations of 2 letters and 2 numbers should be explored unless itâ€™s  ZZ99 and the last thread \nhappens to finish last.  \nCracks a p assword using multithreading and dynamic slicing based on thread count (75  marks)  \nProgram finishes appropriately when password has been found (25  marks)  \n  \n2. Matrix Multiplication using multithreadi ng (25% - 100 marks)  \nYou will create a matrix multiplication program which uses multithreading. Matrices are often \ntwo-dimensional arrays varying in sizes, for your application, you will only need to multiply two -\ndimensional ones. Your program will read in  the matrices from a supplied file (txt), store them \nappropriately using dynamic memory allocation features and multiply them by splitting the tasks \nacross â€œnâ€ threads (any amount of threads). You should use command line arguments to specify \nwhich file to read from (argv[1]) and the number of threads to use (argv[2]). If the number of \nthreads requested by the user is greater than the biggest dimension of the matrices to be \nmultiplied, the actual number of threads used in the calculation should be limited to  the \nmaximum dimension of the matrices. Your program should be able to take â€œanyâ€ size matrices \nand multiply them depending on the data found within the file. Some sizes of matrices cannot be \nmultiplied together, for example, if Matrix A is 3x3 and Matrix B is 2x2, you cannot multiply \nthem. If Matrix A is 2x3 and Matrix B is 3x2, then this can be multiplied. You will need to \nresearch how to multiply matrices, this will also be covered in the lectures (briefly). If the \nmatrices cannot be multiplied, your pro gram should output an error message notifying the user \nand move on to the next pair of matrices. Your program should store the results of your \nsuccessful matrix multiplications in a text file â€“ for every 2 matrices, there should be one \nresulting matrix. As  a minimum, you are expected to use the standard C file handling functions: \nfopen(), fclose(), fscanf(), and fprintf(), to read and to write your files. stdin and stdout \nredirection will not be acceptable.  \nRead data from file appropriately ( 20 marks)  \nUsin g dynamic memory (malloc) for matrix A and matrix B (10 marks)  \nCreating an algorithm to multiply matrices correctly (20 marks)  \nUsing multithreading with equal computations (30 marks)  \nStoring the correct output matrices in the correct format to a file (20 marks)  \n \n3. Password Cracking using CUDA  (30% - 100 marks)  \nUsing a similar concept as question 2, you will now crack passwords using CUDA. As a kernel \nfunction cannot use the crypt library, you will be given an encryption function instead which will \ngenera te a password for you.  Your program will take in an encrypted password and decrypt it \nusing many threads on the GPU. CUDA allows multidimensional thread configurations so your \nkernel function (which runs on the GPU) will need to be modified according to h ow you call your \nfunction.  \nGenerate encrypted password  in the kernel function (using CudaCrypt function)  to be \ncompared to original encrypted password (25  marks)  \nAllocating the correct amount of memory on the GPU based on input data. Memory is freed \nonce used (15  marks)  \nProgram works with multiple blocks and threads  â€“ the number of blocks and threads will \ndepend on your kernel function. You will not be penalised if your program only works with a set number of blocks and threads however, your program must u se more than one block (axis \nis up to you) and more than one thread (axis is up to you)  (40 marks)  \nDecrypted password sent back to the CPU and printed  (20 marks)  \n \n4. Box Blur using CUDA (30% - 100 marks)   \nYour program will decode a PNG file into an array and apply the box blur filter. Blurring an image \nreduces noise by taking the average RGB values around a specific pixel and setting its RGB to the \nmean values youâ€™ve just calculated. This smoothens the colour across a matrix of pixels. For this \nassessment, you will use a 3 x3 matrix. For example, if you have a 5x5 image such as the \nfollowing (be aware that the coordinate values will depend on how you format your 2D array):  \n \n0,4 1,4 2,4 3,4 4,4 \n0,3 1,3 2,3 3,3 4,3 \n0,2 1,2 2,2 3,2 4,2 \n0,1 1,1 2,1 3,1 4,1 \n0,0 1,0 2,0 3,0 4,0 \n \nThe shaded region above represents the pixel we want to blur, in this case, we are focusing on \npixel 1,2  (x,y) (Centre of the matrix). T o apply the blur for this pixel, you would sum all the Red \nvalues from the surrounding coordinates including 1,2 (total of 9 R values) and find the average \n(divide by 9). This is now the new Red value for coordinate 1,2. You must then repeat this for \nGreen and Blue values. This must be repeated throughout the ima ge. If you are working on a \npixel which is not fully surrounded by pixels (8 pixels), you must take the average of however \nmany neighbouring pixels there are.  \n \nYour task is to use CUDA to blur an image. Your number of blocks and threads should in an ideal  \nscenario reflect the dimension of the image however, there are limits to the amount of blocks \nand threads you can spawn in each dimension (regarding block and thread dimensions (x,y,z). \nYou will not be penalised if you do not use different dimensions of b locks and threads, for this \nassessment, we will accept just one dimensional blocks and threads, e.g. \nfunction<<<blockNumber, threadNumber>>>  \n \nReading in an image fi le into a single or 2D array (5  marks)  \nAllocating the correct amount of memory on the GPU ba sed on input data. Memory is freed \nonce used (15  marks)  \nApplying Box filter on image  in the kernel function  (30 marks)  \nReturn blurred image data from the GPU to the CPU (30 marks)  \nOutputting the correct image with Box Blur applied  as a file  (20 marks)  \n \n  Important Message  \n \nYou may be asked to clarify your assessment after moderation has taken place. This is to ensure the \nwork has been completed by the student . \n \nYou must achieve 40 percent overall to pass this module. There will be a resit opportunity during \nresit week (July) to achieve a pass.  \n \nSubmission of work  \nYour completed work for assignments must be handed in on or before the due date. You must keep \na copy or backup of any assessed work that you submit.  Failure to do so may result in your having \nto repeat that piece of work.  \n \nPenalties for late submission of coursework  \nStandard Faculty of Science and Technology arrangements apply.  \nANY late submission (without valid cause) will result in 0 marks being allocated  to the coursework . \n \nProcedure for requesting extensions  \nIf you have a valid reason for requiring an extension you must request an extension using e:vision. \nRequests for extension to assignment deadlines should normally be submitted  before the \nsubmission deadline and may be granted for a maximum of seven days (one calendar week).  \n  \nRetrieval of Failur e \nA pass of 40% or above must be obtained overall for the module (but not necessarily in each \nassessment task).  \nWhere a student fails a module they have the right to attempt the failed assessment(s) once, at \nthe next resit opportunity (normally July resit  period).   If a student fails assessment for a second \ntime they have a right to repeat (i.e. RETAKE) the module.  \n \nNOTE:  STUDENTS  WHO  DO NOT  TAKE  THEIR  RESIT  AT THE  NEXT  AVAILABLE  RESIT  OPPORTUNITY  \nWILL  BE REQUIRED  TO REPEAT  THE  MODULE .  \n \nMitigating Circumstances (also called Extenuating Circumstances).  \nIf you are unable to meet a deadline or attend an examination, and you have a valid reason, then \nyou will need to request via e:vision Extenuating Circumstances.   \n \nFeedback of assignments  \nYou will be given feedback when you demonstrate your work.  \n \nYou normally have two working weeks from the date you receive your grade and feedback to \ncontact and discuss the matter with your lecturer. See the Studentâ€™s Union advice page \nhttp://www.wolvesunion.org/adviceandsupport/  for more details.  \nRegistration  \nPlease ensure that you are registered on the module. You can check your module registrations via \ne:Vision You should see your personal tutor or the Student Support Officer if you are unsure about \nyour programme of study. The fact that you are attending mod ule classes does not mean that you \nare necessarily registered. A grade may not be given if you are not registered.  \n Cheating  \nCheating is any attempt to gain unfair advantage by dishonest means and includes plagiarism  and \ncollusion.  Cheating is a serious of fence. You are advised to check the nature of each assessment. You \nmust work individually unless it is a group assessment.  \n \nCheating  is defined as any attempt by a candidate to gain unfair advantage in an assessment by \ndishonest means, and includes e.g . all breaches of examination room rules, impersonating another \ncandidate, falsifying data, and obtaining an examination paper in advance of its authorised release.  \n \nPlagiarism  is defined as incorporating a significant amount of un -attributed direct quotati on from, or \nun-attributed substantial paraphrasing of, the work of another.  \n \nCollusion occurs when two or more students collaborate to produce a piece of work to be submitted \n(in whole or part) for assessment and the work is presented as the work of one st udent alone.  ', NULL, 0, '6cs005-assessment-23-24-1pdf', '2024-02-04 03:24:56', '2024-02-09 19:58:54'),
	(27, 2, '101_2116279_DraftReport.pdf', 581126, 'application/pdf', ' \n \n  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \nProject and Professionalism  \n(6CS007)  \n \nDraft Report  \nThe Game â€œFractured Memoriesâ€  \n \n \nUniversity ID   : 2116279  \nStudent Name   : Manoj Karki  \nGroup    : L6CG1  \nSupervisor    : Mr. Yamu Poudel  \nReader    : Mr. Akash Adhikari  \nSubmitted on   : 2023 -12-27.  \nTable of Contents  \n1. Introduction  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...........  1 \n2. Aims and Objectives  ................................ ................................ ............................  1 \n2.1 Aims  ................................ ................................ ................................ ..................  1 \n2.2 Objective  ................................ ................................ ................................ ....... 2 \n3. Problem Statement  ................................ ................................ ..............................  2 \n4. Project as Solution  ................................ ................................ ...............................  2 \n5. Scope and Limitations  ................................ ................................ .........................  3 \n5.1 Scope  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...............  3 \n5.2 Limitations  ................................ ................................ ................................ ........  3 \n6. Literature Review  ................................ ................................ ................................ . 4 \nThe Development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe Food and \nWater in Borneo Forest (Kurniawan, et al., 2020)  ................................ ...................  4 \n7. Functional Decomposition Diagram  ................................ ................................ ..... 5 \n8. Artifacts  ................................ ................................ ................................ ................  5 \n8.1 3D Assets  ................................ ................................ ................................ .........  5 \n8.2 UI/ UX  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...............  5 \n8.3 Audio Assets  ................................ ................................ ................................ ..... 5 \n8.4 Storyline  ................................ ................................ ................................ ............  5 \n9. Software Development Methodology  ................................ ................................ ... 6 \n10. Work Breakdown Structure (WBS)  ................................ ................................ ... 7 \n11. Gantt Chart  ................................ ................................ ................................ ....... 7 \n12. Tools and Technologies  ................................ ................................ ...................  8 \n12.1 Unity  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...............  8 \n12.2 Blender  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...........  8 \n12.3 Photoshop  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...... 8 12.4 VS Code  ................................ ................................ ................................ .........  8 \n12.5 C#  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...................  8 \n13.  Literature Review  ................................ ................................ ................................  9 \n13.1 The Development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe Food \nand Water in Borneo Forest  ................................ ................................ ....................  9 \n13.2 Opening the World of Contextually specific player experiences.  ..................  11 \n13.3 A descriptive -analytical study of the Open -World Game Design â€œGrand Theft \nAuto V and online versionâ€ with an emphasis on Role-Playing Capabilities  .........  14 \n13.4 Meaningful Place: A Phenomenological Approach to the Design of Spatial \nExperience in Open World Games  ................................ ................................ ....... 17 \n14. Functional Decomposition Diagram  ................................ ................................ .... 19 \n15. Legend  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...............  19 \n15.1 Sub Systems:  ................................ ................................ ................................  19 \n15.2 Types of Requirements:  ................................ ................................ ................  19 \n16. Environmental Design (ED)  ................................ ................................ ................  20 \n16. Asset (A)  ................................ ................................ ................................ ............  20 \n17. Dynamic World Events (DWE)  ................................ ................................ ...........  21 \n18. Interactivity with the Environment (IE)  ................................ ................................  24 \n19. User Interaction and Customization (UIC)  ................................ ..........................  28 \n20. References  ................................ ................................ ................................ ..... 32 \n \n \n \n  \n Table of Figures  \nFigure 1: Functional Decomposition Diagram  ................................ ............................  5 \nFigure 2 Work Breakdown Structure  ................................ ................................ ..........  7 \nFigure 3 Gantt Chart ................................ ................................ ................................ ... 7 \nFigure 4 Activity Diagram of DWE  ................................ ................................ ............  22 \nFigure 5 Use Case Diagram of DWE ................................ ................................ ........  23 \nFigure 6 Sequence Diagram of DWE  ................................ ................................ ....... 24 \nFigure 7 Activity Diagram of IE  ................................ ................................ .................  25 \nFigure 8 Use Case Diagram of IE  ................................ ................................ ............  26 \nFigure 9 Sequence Diagram of IE  ................................ ................................ ............  27 \nFigure 10 Activity Diagram of UIC  ................................ ................................ ............  29 \nFigure 11 Use Case Diagram of UIC  ................................ ................................ ........  30 \nFigure 12 Sequence Diagram of UIC  ................................ ................................ ....... 31 \n  1 | Page  \n 1. Introduction  \nThis project is game development which is related to open -world gameplay. It aims to \ncreate a 3D platform open -world game named â€œFractured Memoriesâ€. This open -world \nadventure game re -unities the mission of the family, the characters will have to survive \nin the wild with some skills and their available resources. This project focuses on a \ndynamic environment. The game has a realistic feature of change in time and weather \nof the game environment. The narrative will evolve alongside the changing time and \nweat her. Within this game the player will be able to interact and collect the resources \navailable. The game will consist of Non-Pedestrian  Characters (NPCs) making the \ngame more realistic.  \nThe targeted audience for this game primarily consists of individuals who have a keen \ninterest in open -world gaming experiences, particularly  within the survival game genre. \nThe game will cater  to a sense of freedom and exploration, allowing players to interact \nwith the dynamic and unpredictable virtual world.  This is the proposed overview of the \ngame where the players can also gather things available, and based on different \ntactics the player needs to survive.  \n \n2. Aims and Objectives  \n2.1 Aims  \n1. The player can feel nature and enjoy the gameplay without any restrictions.  \n2. This game will help the player to know the survival and crafting skills which can \nbe related in the real world.  \n3. This game also has some quests and missions which will help to increase the \ngeneral knowledge and IQ of the player.  \n4. The game can help in releasing stress and improve self -satisfaction on winning  \ndifferent stages of the game.  \n5. The game will help players  to live a life inside an environment where they can \nexperience a world they would enjoy.  2 | Page  \n 2.2 Objective  \n1. To provide the player with the opportunity to play the game with their own \nchoices whether they want to continue the mission or explore the world.  \n2. To develop a 3D open world game using Unity and Blender . \n3. To implement a realistic environment where the player can experience day, \nnight , and season change.  \n4. To implement survival tactics and character growth in the game while playing \nand experiencing it.  \n \n3. Problem Statement  \nGame enthusiasts face device compatibility issues since different platforms may have \ndifferent specifications which can lead to difficulties in making games work consistently \nacross different platforms.  The gamers do want to experience a game that can help \nboost their mood and help them to tackle stress, loneliness, and depression. The game \nthat has been proposed will help players to interact in an open world. Players do enjoy \na game where they are free to do anything. This gives them a sense of freedom and \njoy in exploration.  \n \n4. Project as Solution  \nAs the character progresses through the story, the skills and ability of the character \nwill develop, providing players feel like they made progress and achieved something \nin the real -world. This game will motivate the player to explore the expansive world of \nthe game, discovering hidden locations and exciting encounters. Lastly , this game will \ndeliver some feelings of importance, loss, love,  and happiness to the player.  \n \n \n \n 3 | Page  \n 5. Scope and Limitations  \n5.1 Scope  \n1. This is an open -world game, the player will have freedom to make significant \ndecisions that will impact the gameplay and can explore the world without any \nrestrictions.  \n2. A game for gamers  with low specifications computer interested in open world \ngames . \n3. During the gameplay, the player might get stuck at some point if the character \nis unable to solve the quests which may decrease the interest of continuing the \ngame. Also, some unidentified bugs may also ruin the gameplay.  \n \n5.2 Limitations  \n1. Although this is an offline story -based game, we can still face the optimization \nissues for the less powerful system of the player.  \n2. Budget constraints may affect the ability to acquire assets like trees, cars,  and \nother environmental elements in the developmental phase.  \n3. As an individual developer, challenges in debugging, identifying the bugs and \nglitches can be time consuming and complex.  \n \n \n \n \n \n 4 | Page  \n 6.  Literature Review  \nThe Development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe \nFood and Water in Borneo Forest (Kurniawan, et al., 2020)  \nTraditional methods of teaching survival skills, especially the ability to identify safe \nfood and water in challenging environments often rely on verbal approaches, which \nmay not properly convey practical information to students. Researchers have \ninvestiga ted the use of games as an alternative and useful learning medium to address \nthis restriction, particularly simulation games. This literature review aims to examine \nthe development and effectiveness of a 3D survival simulation game designed to teach \nplayer s how to identify safe food and water in the Borneo Forest.  \nThe concept of this game was developed based on the learning material, teaching \nmethod, gameplay, setting, and plot. The main scenario of this game is Borneo Island, \nknown for rich flora and natural beauty, making it an ideal location for adventure. The \nresearch aimed to address this issue by using a simulation game to help players \ndistinguish between edible and toxic substances.  \nThe game involves four missions, each increasing in complexity and difficulty. These \nmissions teach players different techniques for identifying safe food and water, such \nas recognizing plant characteristics and performing irritation testing. In the materi al \ncollection stage, the researchers collected images, 3D objects with textures, 3D \ncharacters, audio, and animations needed for the game. Most 3D assets were \nobtained from Unity Assets Store, and any necessary modifications were made using \nBlender. The as sembly stage involved the actual game development using Unity game \nengine and Visual Studio as a source code editor.  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 5 | Page  \n 7. Functional Decomposition Diagram  \n \nFigure 1: Functional Decomposition Diagram  \n \n8. Artifacts  \n8.1 3D Assets  \n3D assets include the characters, vehicles, buildings, objects, trees,  and other visible \ngame objects that the player will be able to see while playing the game.  \n8.2 UI/ UX  \nThis will help in the interaction of the player character model with the 3D assets that \nare available in the environment.  \n8.3 Audio Assets  \nThe audio effects such as in game interaction sound, realistic player movement sound, \nthe sound of vehicles and background  music will be the artifacts.  \n8.4 Storyline  \nThe storyline of the game will guide  players through a series of side quests, survival \nand interaction within the virtual world.  \n \n \n6 | Page  \n 9. Software Development Methodology  \nSoftware development methodology is a structured and organized process of \ndeveloping high -quality software quickly and efficiently. The development phase \nconsists of different stages from problem identification, planning, designing, building/ \ndeveloping , testing,  and then deploying the final product. The whole process in \nsoftware development methodology is called Software Development Life Cycle. SDLC \naims to avoid common mistakes in the development phase. The common SDLC \nmodels are waterfall method, spiral method, agile method (Alexandra, 2023) .  \nTo seamlessly track and manage this project, Kanban methodology for software \ndevelopment will be followed. Kanban is a term from the Japan that means billboard \nor signboard. The kanban methodology signifies its meaning as the major principle of \nKanban is t o visualize the work status and progress using the boards. Instead of \ndividing the work in teams, the stakeholder can add request to the backlogs. Kanban \nand Scrum are two agile approaches where Kanban doesnâ€™t define roles focusing on \ncycle whereas scrum h as fixed length sprints, specific roles (Mijacobs, et al., 2022) .   \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 7 | Page  \n 10. Work Breakdown Structure (WBS)  \n \nFigure 2 Work Breakdown Structure  \n \n \n11. Gantt Chart  \n \nFigure 3 Gantt Chart  \n \n \n \n \n8 | Page  \n 12. Tools and Technologies  \n12.1 Unity  \nUnity is a powerful tool used by many game developers to create and enhance their \ngames. It is a game engine that provides tools for creating the core functionality of \ngames and serves as an integrated development environment (IDE), helping in coding, \ndesigning, and managing the game elements. Some of the games made with Unity \nare Temple Run, Monument Valley, Ori, and the Blind Forest and many more (Sinicki, \n2021) . \n12.2 Blender  \nBlender is a free and opensource software that helps in creating 2D and 3D elements, \ncharacters and many other objects that require  2D or 3D modeling. Blender is mostly \nused in video, filmmaking, game development, architecture. Blender will be used to \nanimate the characters and design the models and assets of the game environment.  \n12.3 Photoshop  \nAdobe Photoshop is a software that is mostly used for editing, manipulating the photos \nand graphical contents. It is used by designers, photographers, artists,  and other \ncreative background individuals. In this project, photoshop will be used to create the \nbuttons and  images used in the game.  \n12.4 VS Code  \nVS Code is a code editor software developed by Microsoft. This is a good choice to \ninterpret codes  due to tis extensibility, flexibility, and many features that help coding \nseamlessly.  \n12.5 C# \nC# programming language will be used as the fundamental game development \nlanguage helping in implementing game logic with high efficiency. It can be utilized in \nthe Unity Game Engine for scripting, offering the ability to implement game logic, \nphysics, user interaction, and more (Kamau, 2021) .  \n \n \n 9 | Page  \n 13.  Literature Review  \n13.1 The Development of 3D Survival Simulation Game for Identifying Safe \nFood and Water in Borneo Forest  \nIn the Borneo Forest, where getting lost and having a few food and water options acts \nserious survival threats, this research is focused on addressing the difficulties that are \nfaced by the explorers. Traditional methods of teaching survival skills, especially the \nability to identify safe food and water in challenging environments often rely on verbal \napproaches, which may not properly convey practical information to students.  To \novercome this issue, the researchers plan to create a survival simulation game  that \ninstructs players how to identify safe food and water in the Borneo Forest  (Kurniawan, \net al., 2023) . \nBorneo Island, which is known for its rich flora, offers an ideal setting for an adventure \nbut can be dangerous due to its rainforests and vast variety of the plants. The \nadventurers need to have a strong survival skill, particularly the ability to differe ntiate \nthe toxic foods apart from the useful ones. So, the concept of this game was developed \nbased on the learning material, teaching method, gameplay, setting, and plot  \n(Kurniawan, et al., 2023) . \nThe research introduces the idea of using the serious games more specifically, \nsimulation games as a useful and entertaining method of teaching the survival skills \nto the players. The serious games are recognized for their potential to enhances the \nlearnin g experiences. By playing the simulation, it provides a safe environment for \nplayers to experiment and learn without risking in the real world. The game will provide \na practical approach to understand the complex situation and can be highly effective \nas an  educational tool  (Kurniawan, et al., 2023) . \nThe main objective of this research is to create a survival simulation game that teaches \nthe players how to find a clean water and food sources in the Borneo Forest. The plot \nof the game centers around a player and an elderly man getting lost in the forest  and \nhaving to survive while waiting for help. In order to preserve their health, energy and \nfluid levels, players must find food and water. Through a series of tests and \ninteractions, the player must identity safe sources while avoiding those that are tox ic \n(Kurniawan, et al., 2023) . 10 | Page  \n The game is designed with the four missions of increasing complexity to teach players \ngradually. These missions teach players different techniques for identifying safe food \nand water, such as recognizing plant characteristics and performing irritation test ing. \nIn the material collection stage, the researchers collected images, 3D objects with \ntextures, 3D characters, audio and animations needed for the game. Most 3D assets \nwere obtained from Unity Assets store, and any necessary modifications were made \nusing Blender. The assembly stage involved the actual game development using the \nunity game engine and visual studio as a source code editor  (Kurniawan, et al., 2023) . \nIn the testing phase, the gameâ€™s compatibility is determined. The effect of the game \non the players understanding of identifying the safe food and water is evaluated using \na pre -test and post -test methodology. The results indicate a significant increase in  \nknowledge after playing the game  (Kurniawan, et al., 2023) . \nIn conclusion, this research demonstrates the survival simulation game as a useful \nteaching tool for learning how to locate safe food and water sources in the Borneo \nForest. Future research should explore the practical application of this knowledge, \ncompar e the game with traditional verbal instruction, and assess other learning \noutcomes such as motivation. Lastly, survival simulation games have the potential to \nprovide a useful and entertaining method for teaching the survival skills  (Kurniawan, \net al., 2023) . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 11 | Page  \n 13.2 Opening the World of Contextually specific player experiences.  \nThe study of player experiences in games has developed, showing the variety of \nplayer enjoyment and gaming experiences. However, current research usually treats \ngames as standard entities or only looks at features in loneliness leaving little space \nfor the  unique characteristics of various gaming experiences. To fill this gap, the paper \npromotes a "contextually specific" approach that explores the distinctive features of \nvarious gaming experiences, concentrating on open world games that are known for \ngiving  players an unmatched level of freedom and choice  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \nIn order to connect game features with player experiences, game genres provide a \nlinking framework. This enables researchers to look at why players are drawn to \nparticular genres, like MMOs. The basic elements that contribute to the overall player \nexperien ce are not enough covered by this genre -focused approach. Instead of \nexploring into the details of these experiences, it frequently focuses on how game \nfeatures contribute to them  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \nOpen world games offer a unique perspective on the difference between what players \nare supposed to experience and the entirety of a game. These games give players the \nfreedom to pursue different interests without imposing a predetermined course of \naction, which leads to highly personalized gameplay. Curren t theories find it hard to \nexplain these various player behaviors  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \nHowever, the highly personalized nature of player experiences in open world games \nbegs the question of whether there are any universals that can be observed. \nAdditionally, players, designers, and researchers do not all agree on what constitutes \na "open wor ld" game, which makes it more difficult to comprehend the open world \ngaming experience. Regardless of these difficulties, open world games provide \ninsightful analyses of context -specific gaming experiences, could be shedding light on \nelements that players find interesting and enjoyable  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \nThe main objective of this study is to investigate how the open world gamers view their \nexperience and to recognize its unique features when compared to other gaming \ncategories. To understand how these games shares the similar experiences and to \nidentify t he features that defines the open world concept, the researchers are looking \nfor the similarities. The study used a method based on the qualitative research with \nthe objective of achieving the saturation of data, which is the process of collecting the 12 | Page  \n data up until the responses start to repeat themselves and stop adding to the studyâ€™s \ntheoretical themes  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \nIn the open world games, player have the freedom to engage and disengage with the \ntasks as they see fit, without any restrictions. Due to this flexibility, players can stay \nengaged with the game which avoid from getting bored. They also have the option to \nself-pace their gaming experience by deciding whether they want to follow the main \nstoryline or pursue the other activities of interest. The players can change to other \ntasks withing the game if one becomes too difficult or emotionally stressful. For \nexamp le, players set a high value on this control over their gaming experience \nbecause it gives them the freedom to select their preferred activities and levels of \nintensity for each gaming session  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \nThe ability to explore the virtual game world freely is a crucial aspect of the open world \ngames. Players enjoy having the option to explore while working towards the main \ngoal. The gameâ€™s settings must be interesting enough to draw the players in even as \nthey are concentrating on the main goal. One of the most important aspects of the \nopen world game design is the stress between the appeal of the main objective and \nthe attractiveness of the surrounding world. Players want a compelling story that gives \nthem  the opportunity to explore and discover the other interesting material  (Hughes & \nCairns, 2021) . \nOverall, open world games are designed to offer players the freedom to select their \ntasks and controls the speed of their gaming experiences. One of the key components \nof this experience is the freedom to roam around the virtual game world and interact \nwith the various content besides the primary objective of the game. These factors work \ntogether to enable players to self -pace their gaming adventures in the open world \ngames. The players freedom and world design both of them play the crucial roles in \nthis co ntext  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \nIn Conclusion, this paper suggests a unique way to understand how the players feel \nwhen they play the open -world games. They talked to the players and looked at what \nthey said to find out what makes an open world game more special. Even though open \nworld g ames are very different for the different players, this method helps us learn \nmore about what the players like in these games. Lastly, it also helps us to understand 13 | Page  \n why players enjoy the open world games and opening the door for more research \nabout the gaming experiences  (Hughes & Cairns, 2021) . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 14 | Page  \n 13.3 A descriptive -analytical study of the Open -World Game Design \nâ€œGrand Theft Auto V and online versionâ€ with an emphasis on Role -\nPlaying Capabilities  \nThis research explores how the â€œopen worldâ€ is used in the digital games, focusing on \nthe popular game â€œGrand Theft Auto Vâ€. It looks into how open -world games are non -\nlinear, whether cultural elements are present, and how artificial intelligence is used.  \nThe study conducts a critical analysis of the game\'s structure, design, and player -\naccessible paths to goal -accomplishing. It emphasizes how, despite how different \nprofessions and jobs are portrayed in the game, involvement in illegal activities like \ndrug dealing, organized robberies, and mafia involvement are frequently the key to \nsuccess, while playing the role of a police officer is difficult  (Ameli & Haghshenas, \n2023) . \nIt discusses the emergence and popularity of the GTA series, with the fifth edition \nreleased in 2013 breaking sales records . The game is described as an open -world \nadventure game set in fictional cities modeled after real -life American cities . GTA has \nreceived high ratings from game rating databases despite complaints about violence \nand cultural stereotypes.  The research\'s main question is whether GTA\'s open world \nreally gives players the freedom to select their roles, way of life, and missions, or if \nthere are preferred pathways built into the game that steer players toward risky and \nillegal activities.  Additionally, the study investigates whether the gameâ€™s design, \nstoryline and the rewards limit playerâ€™s choices and success possibilities  (Ameli & \nHaghshenas, 2023) . \nThis study\'s methodology focuses on using the case study method, a typical qualitative \nresearch strategy, to gain a thorough understanding of the open -world phenomenon \nin computer games, with a special focus on the Grand Theft Auto  (GTA)  game . Case \nstudy research involves an in -depth examination of a specific instance or case that \nhas been specifically selected to fulfill one of three main objectives : \na. Providing a complete and accurate description of the phenomenon.  \nb. Developing potential explanations for it.  \nc. Evaluating the phenomenon  (Ameli & Haghshenas, 2023) . \n 15 | Page  \n An objective of a case study is to present a thorough and in -depth analysis of the \nphenomenon, capturing its essence in its natural setting and relating it to important \nthemes and ideas.  The open world of video games, specifically GTA, has been looked \nat in this research using player observation as well as professional players analysis of \ngameplay videos . This approach allows for an examination of the game in its natural \nenvironment, with a focus on its design and open -world features  (Ameli & \nHaghshenas, 2023) . \nThe research shows that the GTAâ€™s world is vast and richly detailed, giving players a \nton of chances to explore, grow, and learn.  The design of the game includes \ncomplicated textures and interactive elements that increase its appeal to players and \nsurprise them.  The game\'s primary goals, which include buying and selling stocks and \ncars, players can take part in a variety of other activities, such as boating , \nmotorcycling, cycling, racing cars, tennis, golf, wrist throwing, high jumping, and \nrunning.  Additio nally, the game offers entertaining features like animal hunting, \nenhancing the depth and variety of the overall gaming experience.  GTA has \nsuccessfully integrated these interesting components and grown to be a well -known \nand significant game in the digital gaming sector  (Ameli & Haghshenas, 2023) . \nIn video games, the idea of role-playing has always been present and has developed \nover time to become more comprehensive, unique, and interactive.  The integration of \nthe virtual world into this field has further inspired developers and resulted in important \ndevelopments.  Role-playing in online digital games improves immersion and \nencourages players to communicate meaningfully, authentically, and interactively. The \npopularity of live broadcasting platforms has increased the range of interaction, \ninvolving not only players a nd in -game characters but also spectators and game fans. \nThese features have helped games that simulate different facets of life to gain a large \nfollowing of fans and enthusiasts  (Ameli & Haghshenas, 2023) . \nGTA is regarded as a game that changed the digital gaming industry and signaled a \ncritical turning point in the development of video games.  Players can now enjoy a wide \nrange of activities and experiences in a world with rich textures and interactive \nelements.  Additionally, with its representation of ruthless law enforcement and thrilling \nchases, GTA stands out as a representative of contemporary gangster cinema in the \nworld of digital gaming. The Los Santos Police Department, which is based on a real 16 | Page  \n police station in Los Angeles known for its aggressive approach to fighting crime, is \none example of how the game\'s design incorporates elements inspired by real -life \nsettings  (Ameli & Haghshenas, 2023) . \nIn conclusion, the online version of Grand Theft Auto has developed to provide a rich \nand immersive experience that goes beyond standard gaming. Players can explore \ndifferent professions, interact with others, and immerse themselves in a virtual world \nwher e they can fulfill their ambitions, even if those ambitions involve working for the \ngovernment or a criminal organization. GTA is a standout example of how video \ngames continue to evolve and offer players with distinctive and engaging experiences \nbecause o f the game\'s emphasis on role -playing, interactivity, and real -life \nappearances  (Ameli & Haghshenas, 2023) . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 17 | Page  \n 13.4 Meaningful Place: A Phenomenological Approach to the Design of \nSpatial Experience in Open World Games  \nRecent years have seen a rise in the popularity of large, open virtual worlds, but this \nhas also brought about a significant challenge: despite their size, these game \nenvironments frequently feel uninteresting and meaningless. This paper suggests a \nnovel s trategy to deal with this problem by emphasizing the idea of "place" within \nvirtual worlds as opposed to seeing them as merely empty "spaces." With a wider \nperspective intended to prepare for the future of virtual reality, it introduces the concept \nof "ori entation -identification -time" as a straightforward yet effective way to infuse these \ngame worlds with excitement and meaning  (Wang, et al., 2023) . \nOpen -world video games have become extremely popular due to their vast and \ndetailed virtual environments. However, in these huge game worlds, players frequently \nstruggle with a sense of repetition and emptiness. This paper explores the field of \nphenomenolo gy, the study of how users interact with virtual worlds, in an effort to \ntackle this challenge head -on. The paper aims to improve the overall gaming \nexperience by gaining a deeper understanding of player perceptions and interactions \nwith these spaces  (Wang, et al., 2023) . \nTraditionally, stories found in games have been the focus of game studies. However, \nwith the development of technology and the complexity of virtual worlds, people\'s focus \nhas shifted to the settings in which these games take place. Researchers and players  \ntoday concentrate on two main strategies: one treats game spaces as real -world \narenas created for particular activities, while the other looks at how players interact \nwith and perceive these spaces. With a focus on player perception and emotional \nengageme nt with the gaming environment, this essay takes the latter approach  \n(Wang, et al., 2023) . \nIt\'s important to distinguish between "space ontology" and "spatial experience" in order \nto find meaning in game worlds. The former sees game worlds as real -world locations \nfor particular pursuits, much like a playground made for games like tag or hide -and-\nseek. The latter perspective, known as "spatial experience," on the other hand, \nemphasizes how users interact with the entire virtual playground. The "spatial \nexperience" approach is the main focus of this essay, which aims to understand what \nmakes virtua l worlds interesting and alive outside of gaming  (Wang, et al., 2023) . 18 | Page  \n Looking for meaning in game environments leads to a crucial separation between \n"space" and "place." Imagine yourself in a large, open field, a place that might seem \nlifeless and uninteresting. In contrast, a "place" brings  up richer associations, \ncomparable to a warm bedroom or a beloved park that conjures up strong feelings and \nmemories. The paper makes the case that people need this sense of place in virtual \nsettings. It involves connecting with the virtual world as well as following the rules. \nEven in va st open -world environments, game designers are urged to put a priority on \ncreating meaningful "place" experiences  (Wang, et al., 2023) . \nIn Conclusion, this paper concludes that the three -dimensional concept known as \n"orientation -identification -time" should be adopted. This strategy involves helping \nplayers in understanding their position, goal, and the passage of time within the game\'s \nvirtual world. The  paper makes the claim that by doing this, it is possible to change \nuninteresting game environments into engaging ones. The paper also mentions the \nidea of the "Metaverse," a sizable virtual world where people may spend a lot of time \nin the future. It points out the potential problems that might develop if virtual worlds \nlack purpose and exhorts game developers and virtual reality developers to \nconcentrate on creating meaningful "place" experiences  (Wang, et al., 2023) . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 19 | Page  \n 14. Functional Decomposition Diagram  \n \n \n \n15. Legend  \n15.1 Sub Systems:  \nâ€¢ ED: Environmental Design  \nâ€¢ A: Asset  \nâ€¢ DWE: Dynamic World Events  \nâ€¢ IE: Interactivity with the environment  \nâ€¢ UIC: User Interaction and Customization  \n \n15.2 Types of Requirements:  \nâ€¢ F: Functional Requirements  \nâ€¢ NF: Non -Functional Requirements  \n \n \n20 | Page  \n 16. Environmental Design (ED)  \nRequirement Code  Requirement \nDescription  Use Case  MosCow \nPrioritization  \nED-F-1 Creating a variety of \nassets around the \nworld.  World Building  Must Have  \nED-F-2 Designing the unique \nmountains  World Building  Must Have  \nED-NF-3 Noticing the birds \nhigh in the sky  World Building  Should Have  \n \n \n \n16. Asset (A)  \nRequirement Code  Requirement \nDescription  Use Case  MosCow \nPrioritization  \nA-F-1 Creating the world \nwith the NPCs for \nrealistic interaction \nwith the player  NPCs  Must Have  \nA-F-2 Creating a huge \nrange of wildlife and \ncreatures with its \nunique behavior  NPCs  Must Have  \nA-F-3 Adding the \ninteractable object, \nsuch as treasure and \nother easter eggs.  Interact object  Must Have  \n \n 21 | Page  \n 17. Dynamic World Events (DWE)  \nRequirement Code  Requirement \nDescription  Use Case  MosCow \nPrioritization  \nDWE -F-1 Adding the realistic \ntimecylcle  and \nweather patterns.  World Events  Must Have  \nDWE -F-2 Implementing the \nenvironmental \nhazards, such as \nthunderstorm which \ncan affect the \ngameplay while \nfollowing the \nstoryline.  World Events  Must Have  \nDWE -NF-3 Different wildlife may \nappear, while each of \nthem will have their \nunique behaviour.  World Events  Should Have  \nDWE -F-4 Tooltips for \ninteractive elements  Providing context \ninformation  Should Have  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 22 | Page  \n  \nFigure 4 Activity Diagram of DWE  \n \n23 | Page  \n  \nFigure 5 Use Case Diagram of DWE  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n24 | Page  \n  \nFigure 6 Sequence Diagram of DWE  \n \n \n18. Interactivity  with the Environment (IE)  \nRequirement Code  Requirement \nDescription  Use Case  MosCow \nPrioritization  \nIE-F-1 Enables the player to \ninteract with the \nenvironment around \nthe world.  World Interaction  Must Have  \nIE-F-2 Enables the player to \ndestruct the \nenvironment.  Destructible Object  Must Have  \nIE-NF-3 Allowing the player to \nsneak through the \nvegetation for \nattacking enemies  Interaction  Should Have  \n \n25 | Page  \n  \nFigure 7 Activity Diagram of IE  \n \n26 | Page  \n  \nFigure 8 Use Case Diagram of IE  \n \n  \n27 | Page  \n  \nFigure 9 Sequence Diagram of IE  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n28 | Page  \n 19. User Interaction and Customization (UIC) \nRequirement Code  Requirement \nDescription  Use Case  MosCow \nPrioritization  \nUIC-F-1 Main menu UI for \neasy navigation  Accessing the game \nmenu  Must Have  \nUIC-F-2 Settings menu for \ncustomization  Adjusting graphics, \ncontrols, audio, looks \nsensitivity  Must Have  \nUIC-F-3 In game HUD for \nhealth and inventory  Monitoring player \nstatus  Should Have  \nUIC-NF-4 Customizable key \nbindings  Configuring \nkeyboard shortcuts  Should Have  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n 29 | Page  \n  \nFigure 10 Activity Diagram of UIC  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n30 | Page  \n  \nFigure 11 Use Case Diagram of UIC  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n31 | Page  \n  \nFigure 12 Sequence Diagram of UIC  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n32 | Page  \n 20. R eferences  \nA., 2023. What Is SDLC? Understand the Software Development Life Cycle. [Online]  \nAvailable at: https://stackify.com/what -is-sdlc/ \n[Accessed 08 August 2023].  \nAmeli , S. R. & Haghshenas, M. M., 2023. A descriptive -analytical study of the Open -\nWorld Game Design "Grand Theft Auto V and online version" with an emphasis on \nRole-Playing Capabilities. Journal of Cyberspace Studies, 7(1), pp. 1 -22. \nHughes, N. G. & Cairns, P., 2021. Opening the world of contextually -specific player \nexperiences. Entertainment Computing, p. 12.  \nKamau, V., 2021. C# or C++ for Game Development?. [Online]  \nAvailable at: https://www.section.io/engineering -education/c -sharp -or-c++-for-game -\ndevelopment/  \n[Accessed 12 August 2023].  \nKurniawan, Y. F., Isnanda, R. G. & Asroni, A., 2023. The Development of 3D Survival \nSimulation Game for Identifying Safe Food and Water in Borneo Forest. Emerging \nInformation Science and Technology, Volume 1, pp. 1 -7. \nM., E., V. -t. & A., 2022. What is Kanban?. [Online]  \nAvailable at: https://learn.microsoft.com/en -us/devops/plan/what -is-kanban  \n[Accessed 12 August 2023].  \nSinicki, A., 2021. What is Unity? Everything you need to know. [Online]  \nAvailable at: https://www.androidauthority.com/what -is-unity -1131558/  \n[Accessed 12 August 2023].  \nWang, B., Gao, Z. & Shidujaman, M., 2023. Meaningful Place: A Phenomenological \nApproach to the Design of Spatial Experience in Open -world Games. Games and \nCulture, pp. 1 -24. \n \n ', NULL, 0, '101_2116279_draftreportpdf', '2024-02-04 03:26:20', '2024-02-09 19:58:54'),
