	(52, 1, '6CS005 - Assessment 23-24 (1)-1.pdf', 282946, 'application/pdf', 'University of Wolverhampton  \r\nFaculty of Science and Engineering  \r\nDepartment of Mathematics and Computer Science  \r\nHerald College Kathmandu  \r\n \r\nModule Assessment  \r\n \r\nModule  6CS005 â€“ High Performance Computing  \r\nModule Leader  Hiran Patel  / Jnaneshwar Bohara  \r\nSemester  1 \r\nYear  2023/24 \r\nAssessment  Portfolio  \r\n% of module mark  100%  \r\nDue Date  Date will be published on Canvas  \r\nHand -in â€“ what?  Portfolio as specified in this document  \r\nHand -in- where?  Canvas  \r\nPass mark  40% \r\nMethod of retrieval  Submit the resit assessment (will be distributed at the end of the \r\nmodule) by end of resit week (July)  \r\nFeedback  Individual feedback via Canvas, in addition verbal feedback is \r\navailable in class.  \r\nCollection of \r\nmarked work  N/A \r\n \r\nAssessment overview  \r\nThis portfolio is split up into 4 separate tasks which will test your knowledge of advanced \r\nmultithreading and GPGPU programming using CUDA. Each task should be zipped up into a single zip \r\nfolder containing all C/CUDA and resource files for the submission on Canvas.  \r\n1. Password cracking using multithreading  (15% - 100 marks)  \r\nIn this task, you will be asked to use the â€œcryptâ€ library to decrypt a password using \r\nmultithreading. You will be provided with two programs. The first program called \r\nâ€œEncryptSHA512.câ€  which  allows you to encrypt a password. For this assessment , you will be \r\nrequired to decrypt a 4-character  password consisting of 2 capital  letters, and 2 numbers. The \r\nformat of the password should be â€œLetterLetterNumberNumber.â€ For example, â€œHP93.â€ Once \r\nyou have generated your password, this should then be entered into your program to decrypt \r\nthe password.  The method of input for the encrypted password is up to you.  The second \r\nprogram is a  skeleton code to crack the password in regular C without any multithread ing \r\nsyntax. Your task is to use multithreading  to split the workload over many threads  and find the \r\npassword. Once the password has been found, the program should finish meaning not all \r\ncombinations of 2 letters and 2 numbers should be explored unless itâ€™s  ZZ99 and the last thread \r\nhappens to finish last.  \r\nCracks a p assword using multithreading and dynamic slicing based on thread count (75  marks)  \r\nProgram finishes appropriately when password has been found (25  marks)  \r\n  \r\n2. Matrix Multiplication using multithreadi ng (25% - 100 marks)  \r\nYou will create a matrix multiplication program which uses multithreading. Matrices are often \r\ntwo-dimensional arrays varying in sizes, for your application, you will only need to multiply two -\r\ndimensional ones. Your program will read in  the matrices from a supplied file (txt), store them \r\nappropriately using dynamic memory allocation features and multiply them by splitting the tasks \r\nacross â€œnâ€ threads (any amount of threads). You should use command line arguments to specify \r\nwhich file to read from (argv[1]) and the number of threads to use (argv[2]). If the number of \r\nthreads requested by the user is greater than the biggest dimension of the matrices to be \r\nmultiplied, the actual number of threads used in the calculation should be limited to  the \r\nmaximum dimension of the matrices. Your program should be able to take â€œanyâ€ size matrices \r\nand multiply them depending on the data found within the file. Some sizes of matrices cannot be \r\nmultiplied together, for example, if Matrix A is 3x3 and Matrix B is 2x2, you cannot multiply \r\nthem. If Matrix A is 2x3 and Matrix B is 3x2, then this can be multiplied. You will need to \r\nresearch how to multiply matrices, this will also be covered in the lectures (briefly). If the \r\nmatrices cannot be multiplied, your pro gram should output an error message notifying the user \r\nand move on to the next pair of matrices. Your program should store the results of your \r\nsuccessful matrix multiplications in a text file â€“ for every 2 matrices, there should be one \r\nresulting matrix. As  a minimum, you are expected to use the standard C file handling functions: \r\nfopen(), fclose(), fscanf(), and fprintf(), to read and to write your files. stdin and stdout \r\nredirection will not be acceptable.  \r\nRead data from file appropriately ( 20 marks)  \r\nUsin g dynamic memory (malloc) for matrix A and matrix B (10 marks)  \r\nCreating an algorithm to multiply matrices correctly (20 marks)  \r\nUsing multithreading with equal computations (30 marks)  \r\nStoring the correct output matrices in the correct format to a file (20 marks)  \r\n \r\n3. Password Cracking using CUDA  (30% - 100 marks)  \r\nUsing a similar concept as question 2, you will now crack passwords using CUDA. As a kernel \r\nfunction cannot use the crypt library, you will be given an encryption function instead which will \r\ngenera te a password for you.  Your program will take in an encrypted password and decrypt it \r\nusing many threads on the GPU. CUDA allows multidimensional thread configurations so your \r\nkernel function (which runs on the GPU) will need to be modified according to h ow you call your \r\nfunction.  \r\nGenerate encrypted password  in the kernel function (using CudaCrypt function)  to be \r\ncompared to original encrypted password (25  marks)  \r\nAllocating the correct amount of memory on the GPU based on input data. Memory is freed \r\nonce used (15  marks)  \r\nProgram works with multiple blocks and threads  â€“ the number of blocks and threads will \r\ndepend on your kernel function. You will not be penalised if your program only works with a set number of blocks and threads however, your program must u se more than one block (axis \r\nis up to you) and more than one thread (axis is up to you)  (40 marks)  \r\nDecrypted password sent back to the CPU and printed  (20 marks)  \r\n \r\n4. Box Blur using CUDA (30% - 100 marks)   \r\nYour program will decode a PNG file into an array and apply the box blur filter. Blurring an image \r\nreduces noise by taking the average RGB values around a specific pixel and setting its RGB to the \r\nmean values youâ€™ve just calculated. This smoothens the colour across a matrix of pixels. For this \r\nassessment, you will use a 3 x3 matrix. For example, if you have a 5x5 image such as the \r\nfollowing (be aware that the coordinate values will depend on how you format your 2D array):  \r\n \r\n0,4 1,4 2,4 3,4 4,4 \r\n0,3 1,3 2,3 3,3 4,3 \r\n0,2 1,2 2,2 3,2 4,2 \r\n0,1 1,1 2,1 3,1 4,1 \r\n0,0 1,0 2,0 3,0 4,0 \r\n \r\nThe shaded region above represents the pixel we want to blur, in this case, we are focusing on \r\npixel 1,2  (x,y) (Centre of the matrix). T o apply the blur for this pixel, you would sum all the Red \r\nvalues from the surrounding coordinates including 1,2 (total of 9 R values) and find the average \r\n(divide by 9). This is now the new Red value for coordinate 1,2. You must then repeat this for \r\nGreen and Blue values. This must be repeated throughout the ima ge. If you are working on a \r\npixel which is not fully surrounded by pixels (8 pixels), you must take the average of however \r\nmany neighbouring pixels there are.  \r\n \r\nYour task is to use CUDA to blur an image. Your number of blocks and threads should in an ideal  \r\nscenario reflect the dimension of the image however, there are limits to the amount of blocks \r\nand threads you can spawn in each dimension (regarding block and thread dimensions (x,y,z). \r\nYou will not be penalised if you do not use different dimensions of b locks and threads, for this \r\nassessment, we will accept just one dimensional blocks and threads, e.g. \r\nfunction<<<blockNumber, threadNumber>>>  \r\n \r\nReading in an image fi le into a single or 2D array (5  marks)  \r\nAllocating the correct amount of memory on the GPU ba sed on input data. Memory is freed \r\nonce used (15  marks)  \r\nApplying Box filter on image  in the kernel function  (30 marks)  \r\nReturn blurred image data from the GPU to the CPU (30 marks)  \r\nOutputting the correct image with Box Blur applied  as a file  (20 marks)  \r\n \r\n  Important Message  \r\n \r\nYou may be asked to clarify your assessment after moderation has taken place. This is to ensure the \r\nwork has been completed by the student . \r\n \r\nYou must achieve 40 percent overall to pass this module. There will be a resit opportunity during \r\nresit week (July) to achieve a pass.  \r\n \r\nSubmission of work  \r\nYour completed work for assignments must be handed in on or before the due date. You must keep \r\na copy or backup of any assessed work that you submit.  Failure to do so may result in your having \r\nto repeat that piece of work.  \r\n \r\nPenalties for late submission of coursework  \r\nStandard Faculty of Science and Technology arrangements apply.  \r\nANY late submission (without valid cause) will result in 0 marks being allocated  to the coursework . \r\n \r\nProcedure for requesting extensions  \r\nIf you have a valid reason for requiring an extension you must request an extension using e:vision. \r\nRequests for extension to assignment deadlines should normally be submitted  before the \r\nsubmission deadline and may be granted for a maximum of seven days (one calendar week).  \r\n  \r\nRetrieval of Failur e \r\nA pass of 40% or above must be obtained overall for the module (but not necessarily in each \r\nassessment task).  \r\nWhere a student fails a module they have the right to attempt the failed assessment(s) once, at \r\nthe next resit opportunity (normally July resit  period).   If a student fails assessment for a second \r\ntime they have a right to repeat (i.e. RETAKE) the module.  \r\n \r\nNOTE:  STUDENTS  WHO  DO NOT  TAKE  THEIR  RESIT  AT THE  NEXT  AVAILABLE  RESIT  OPPORTUNITY  \r\nWILL  BE REQUIRED  TO REPEAT  THE  MODULE .  \r\n \r\nMitigating Circumstances (also called Extenuating Circumstances).  \r\nIf you are unable to meet a deadline or attend an examination, and you have a valid reason, then \r\nyou will need to request via e:vision Extenuating Circumstances.   \r\n \r\nFeedback of assignments  \r\nYou will be given feedback when you demonstrate your work.  \r\n \r\nYou normally have two working weeks from the date you receive your grade and feedback to \r\ncontact and discuss the matter with your lecturer. See the Studentâ€™s Union advice page \r\nhttp://www.wolvesunion.org/adviceandsupport/  for more details.  \r\nRegistration  \r\nPlease ensure that you are registered on the module. You can check your module registrations via \r\ne:Vision You should see your personal tutor or the Student Support Officer if you are unsure about \r\nyour programme of study. The fact that you are attending mod ule classes does not mean that you \r\nare necessarily registered. A grade may not be given if you are not registered.  \r\n Cheating  \r\nCheating is any attempt to gain unfair advantage by dishonest means and includes plagiarism  and \r\ncollusion.  Cheating is a serious of fence. You are advised to check the nature of each assessment. You \r\nmust work individually unless it is a group assessment.  \r\n \r\nCheating  is defined as any attempt by a candidate to gain unfair advantage in an assessment by \r\ndishonest means, and includes e.g . all breaches of examination room rules, impersonating another \r\ncandidate, falsifying data, and obtaining an examination paper in advance of its authorised release.  \r\n \r\nPlagiarism  is defined as incorporating a significant amount of un -attributed direct quotati on from, or \r\nun-attributed substantial paraphrasing of, the work of another.  \r\n \r\nCollusion occurs when two or more students collaborate to produce a piece of work to be submitted \r\n(in whole or part) for assessment and the work is presented as the work of one st udent alone.  ', 'This portfolio is split up into 4 separate tasks which will test your knowledge of advanced multithreading and GPGPU programming. Each task should be zipped up into a single zip  containing all C/CUDA and resource files for the submission on Canvas. Submit the resit assessment (will be distributed at the end of the  module) by end of resit week (July)', 0, '6cs005-assessment-23-24-1-1pdf-1', '2024-02-10 04:48:08', '2024-02-10 10:33:19'),
	(53, 1, '2065697_DhirajKumarSahKanu_FinalReport-1.pdf', 273163, 'application/pdf', '  \n \n  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \nComplex Systems  \n(6CS0 14) \nA Review on Target Customer \nSegmentation and Ad Prediction \nusing Machine Learning  \nStudent Id    : 2065697  \nStudent Name   : Dhiraj Kumar Sah Kanu  \nGroup     : L6CG14 \nModule Leader      : Mr. Deepson Shrestha  \nInstructor    : Mr. Shiv Kumar Yadav  \nWord Count          : 2507 \nSubmitted on          : 20 January , 202 4   \n \n Table of Contents  \nAbstract  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...........................  1 \n1. Introduction  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...............  2 \n2. Aims  ................................ ................................ ................................ ..........................  2 \n3. Objectives  ................................ ................................ ................................ .................  2 \n4. Literature Review  ................................ ................................ ................................ ...... 3 \n4.1. Ad Prediction using Click Through Rate and Machine Learning with \nReinforcement  ................................ ................................ ................................ .............  3 \n4.2. Ad Click Prediction in Sequence with Long Short -Term Memory Networks: An \nEternality -aware Model  ................................ ................................ ................................  4 \n4.3. Deep User Segment Interest Network Modeling for Click -Through Rate \nPrediction of Online Advertising  ................................ ................................ ...................  5 \n4.4. Customer Segmentation using Machine Learning  ................................ ............  6 \n4.5. Analysis of Unsupervised Machine Learning Techniques for an Efficient \nCustomer Segmentation using Clustering Ensemble and Spectral Clustering  ............  7 \n4.6. K-Means and K -Medoids Clustering Methods for Customer Segmentation in \nOnline Retail Datasets  ................................ ................................ ................................ . 8 \n4.7. AdRobot: A Smart Segmentation Application for Automated & Personalized \nMarketing Campaigns  ................................ ................................ ................................ .. 9 \n5. Findings  ................................ ................................ ................................ ..................  10 \n6. Conclusion  ................................ ................................ ................................ ..............  11 \n7. References  ................................ ................................ ................................ .............  12 \n \n \n  \n  6CS014  \n1 \n Abstract  \nThis literature review discusses the recent advancement, implement ation , and impacts of \nAI algorithms in ad prediction, click through rate optimization, and customer \nsegmentation . The primary aim is to understand the development in use of AI in digital \nmarketing, evaluating the algorithms, assessing the impact of AI on advertising \nperformance, and helping in improving personalized marketing. The review explores \ntechniques like rei nforcement  learning, deep learning (LSTM networks) and DUSIN for \nad prediction  and rate optimization. It also evaluates clustering methods such as K -\nMeans, K -Medoids and spectral clustering for customer segmentation.  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n  6CS014  \n2 \n 1. Introduction  \nAI has been influencing different domains currently, understanding and harnessing the \npower of Artificial Intelligence using the models and concepts for optimizing digital \nadvertising strategies  can bring a revolution in digital marketing. In recent years, the \nintegration of machine learning algorithms in customer segmentations has become pivotal \nfor businesses aiming to enhance customer satisfaction, retention, and overall \nprofitability. The research contributes to the understanding of cust omer behavior in  online \nretail, emphasizing the need for addressing outliers and providing actionable insights for \nbusinesses seeking to optimize their online retail strategies.  \n2. Aims  \nâ€¢ To know about recent advancement in the ad prediction, click -through rate \noptimization and customer segmentation.  \nâ€¢ To evaluate different algorithms employed in ad prediction and customer \nsegmentation.  \nâ€¢ To know how AI algorithms are impacting performance of post, campaign \neffectiveness, optimization of ad spends.  \nâ€¢ To investigate role of artificial intelligence in automating and personalizing \nmarketing strategies.  \n3. Objectives  \nâ€¢ Explore use of advanced techniques such as reinforcement learning, deep learning \n(LSTM networks), DUSIN in ad prediction and rate optimization.  \nâ€¢ Evaluate impact of clustering methods like K -Means, K -Medoids and spectral \nclustering for customer segmentation.  \nâ€¢ Analyze key performance metrics such as post -performance, campaign \neffectiveness, and the optimization of ad spending.  \nâ€¢ Address practical implications, enhancement in models such as automatic \nsegmentation methods, alternative ML approaches.           6CS014  \n3 \n 4. Literature Review  \n4.1. Ad Prediction using Click Through Rate and Machine Learning with  \nReinforcement  \nThis conference paper  written by (Lakshmanarao, et al., 2021)  focuses on Upper \nConfidence Bound (UCB) and Thompson Sampling, represent ing significant stride in \nonline advertising optimization. It addresses  the steps of dataset collection, utilizing the \nAds_CTR_Optimizsation dataset from Kaggle, consisting of information on 10 \nadvertisements and 10,000 user clicks. The exploration of the dataset reveals a binary \nnature (0 and 1) representing user clicks on a dvertisements, forming the basics for the \nreinforcement learning models. Introduction of reinforcement learning as a field within \nmachine learning sets the stage for the subsequent application of UCB and Thomspon \nSampling. Reinforcement learning, with its focus on maximizing rewards, is appropriately \nframed within the context of online  advertising, where the algorithm learns from its \nexperiences rather than relying on predefined answers. The methodology  section \nelaborates the use of UCB algorithm and the Thompson Samling algorithm.  UCB \nalgorithm involves calculating average rewards and confidence intervals for each \nadvertisement, while Thompson Sampling relies on randomly generated beliefs to select \nads. The experimentation phase, spanning 1000 rounds, highl ights the efficiency of the \nalgorithms. Random Selection surprisingly identifies Ad -9 as the best -performing ad  \namong the 10 ads , laying the foundation for comparison with the more sophisticated UCB \nand Thompson Samling algorithms. UCB, when applied for different rounds, exhibits \nvarying performances, with Ad -5 and Ad -8 emerging as top -performing ads in different \nscenarios. Thompso n Sampling consistently prioritizes Ad -5 across all rounds, \noutperforming UCB in predictive accuracy.  Potential challenges relat ed to algorithm \nsensitivity, assumption of stationarity in user behavior, and the impact of feature \nrepresentation  could be some  of the limitations . \n \n \n  6CS014  \n4 \n 4.2. Ad Click Prediction in Sequence with Long Short -Term Memory \nNetworks: An Eternality -aware Model  \nThis paper addresses  the problem related to click -through  rate (CTR) in sponsored ads, \nwhere the data for accuracy of the click prediction impacts the user search experience \nand business revenue  significantly . The proposed approach / methodology utilizes \nRecurrent Neural Networks (RNN) with Long Short -Term Memory (LSTM) cells for \nsequential click prediction. The LSTM -RNN architecture is detailed, involving the \nsequential feeding of ads from ML1 to ML4,  where ML1 is the first  ad displayed in \nmainline, conside ring the information from previous ads. Authors have conducted  \nanalysis of externalities, demonstrating the impact of the CTR of the first ad (ML1) on the \nCTR of the second ad (ML2). The  final performance of the proposed  model  above is \nevaluated with the help of  standard metrics such as AUC Curve  and Relative Information \nGain (RIG), showcasing the improvements over a baseline Deep Neural Network (DNN) \nmodel. Acknowledg ing certain  challenges , the primary concern covered is the high \ncomputational cost associated with the LSTM -RNN model, which may hinder its real -time \napplicability in dynamic advertising environments. To address this, a simplified version is \nproposed, reducing computation costs while maintaining a substanti al portion of the \naccuracy gains. The analys is of externalities reveals that the quality of the first ad impacts \nthe CTR of subsequent ads, establishing the influence of ad quality on sequential CTR. \nThe LSTM -RNN model outperforms the baseline DNN model, demonstrating \nimprovements in AUC and RIG acr oss various ad positions. To address computation cost, \na simplified version with a new externality feature is proposed, achieving significant gains \nwith reduced complexity  (Deng, et al., 2018) . \n \n \n \n  6CS014  \n5 \n 4.3. Deep User Segment Interest Network Modeling for Click -Through  \nRate Prediction of Online Advertising  \nThe model architecture uses Deep User Segment Interest Network (DUSIN) model to \ncomprise key layers, including an Embedding Layer transforming user behavior \nsequences, an Individual Interest Extractor Layer utilizing a Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) \nfor extracting individual user interests, a Segment Interest Activating Layer updating \nsegme nt interests based on the last hidden vector, and a Segment Interest Activating \nLayer inspired by Deep Interest Network (DIN). Employing  the Tobacco dataset, \nresearchers unde rtake  preprocessing steps like under sampling for class imbalance and  \ndefine  user segments based on features related to age and gender.  Baseline algorithms \nsuch as MLP, PNN, DeepFM and DIN are compared using evaluation metrics like AUC \nand log loss.  Insights from segment interest are gained by visualizing differences using \nEuclidean distances, providing valuable perspectives on user preferences within the \npredefined segments. The model performance comparison demonstrates the superiority \nof DUSIN, with  notable AUC gains over baseline models. Specifically, DUSIN achieved \nan AUC gain of 0.0017 over MLP and with a sequence length of 100, a  further gain of \n0.0029  is noticed . The analysis of different behavior sequence lengths emphasizes the \nsignificance of historical user behavior, indicating optimal performance with longer \nsequence for DUSIN. The findings offer valuable insights into user segment dynamics, \nemphasizing the p ractical relevance of DUSIN in real -time advertising systems. The \nability of model to outperform baseline algorithms underscores its potential for enhancing \nCTR prediction accuracy. The consideration of different behavior sequ ence lengths \nprovides nuanced perspectives on the temporal aspects of user behavior. It also \nacknowledges certain limitations, including the reliance on predefined user segments and \nthe potential of dataset high dimensional spare features (Kim, et al., 2021) . \n \n \n  6CS014  \n6 \n 4.4. Customer Segmentation using Machine Learning  \nThe research performed by (Patel, et al., 2020)  focused on customer segmentation  \nintroduces diverse methodologies of clustering models, including the widely utilized K -\nmeans algorithm known for its computational efficiency, the hierarchical clustering \napproach that builds a hierarchy of data points, the density -based clustering repres ented \nby DBSCAN, and the Affinity Propagation Algorithm, which stands out for its ability to \nidentify clusters without a predefined number.  The methodology underscores the \nsignificance of CRM in modern marketing, emphasizin g its role in customer value analysis \nand the development of persistent  customer -company relationships. Customer \nsegmentation emerges as a crucial aspect, involving the division into distinct buyers  of \nsimilar  behaviors and characteristics. The use of clustering algorithms becomes evident \nas a powerful tool in predicting consumption trends and refining marketing strategies. The \ncomparative analysis of these clustering algorithms reveals valuable insights into t heir \nperformance across dimensions such as comp utation speed, adaptability to dataset \ncharacteristics, and overall efficiency. K -Means, for instance, exhibits high computational \nefficiency. K -Means, exhibits high computational efficiency bur grapples with the \nchallenge of dependency on the initial numb er of clusters. Hierarchical clustering, \nalthough versatile in cluster formation, faces limitations in computational speed, making \nit more suitable for smaller datasets . The finding shows the importance of choosing the \nappropriate clustering algorithm base d on specific dataset characteristics and analytical \ngoals. Moreover, it acknowledges the limitations associated with interpreting cluster \nmeanings and suggests a potential enhancement by addressing these challenges . \n \n \n  6CS014  \n7 \n 4.5. Analysis of Unsupervised Machine Learning Techniques for  an \nEfficient Customer Segmentation using Clustering Ensemble and \nSpectral Clustering  \nAn insightful analysis by the models employed for unsupervised machine learning \ntechniques include Mini Batch K -Means, DBSCAN, K -Means, Mean Shift, and Spectral \nClustering. Data is extracted , collected  from Moroccan resident s, resulting in a dataset of \n1357 individuals with eight distinguishing  freatures . The methodology involves applying \nindividual clustering models to the dataset and combining their results using clustering \nensemble and spectral clustering. The proposed model is then applied to a real dat aset, \nshowcasing its effectiveness in clustering diverse populations. Performance evaluation  \nusing metrics such as Adjusted Rand Index (ARI), Normalized Mutual Information (NMI), \nSilhouette Coefficient (SC), and Davies -Bouldin Index (DI), demonstrating the superiority \nof model over old method of  clustering approaches is performed . The findings showcase  \nthe distinct clusters based on demographics and socioeconomic attributes. Cluster 3 \ncomprises educated, high income, non -single females in large cities, whil e Cluster 4 \nconsists of single men with higher incomes in urban centers. Median age comparisons \nhighlight variations across clusters, with Cluster 2 and 3 showing younger ages (28.5 and \n29), and Clusters 1 and 4 exhibiting notably older ages (36 and 37). A pplication to a real \ndataset identifies five clusters, with Cluster 0 representing middle class single men and \nCluster 4 comprising married women with high income and education. The proposed \nmodel outperforms traditional models in performance metrics, with  ARI, NMI, SC, and DI \nvalues of 0.7014, 0.7175, 0.7289, and 0.7515, respectively, indicating its efficacy in \ncapturing complex patterns within datasets.  However, the study has limitations. It primarily \nrelies on traditional clustering models, g eneralizing may be limited to the specific \ncharacteristics of the Moroccan residents surveyed  (Karim & Hicham, 2022) .  \n \n  6CS014  \n8 \n 4.6. K-Means and K -Medoids Clustering Methods for Customer  \nSegmentation in Online Retail Datasets  \nIn this research  conducted by (Mufarroha, et al., 2022) , gives  light on the application of \nK-Means and K -Medoids clustering methods for customer segmentation in  the online \nretail datasets. The research employed a methodology encompassing various stages. \nData collection involved the utilization of online retail customer data obtained from Kaggle, \ncomprising parameters such as invoice, stock code, description, invoice data, price, \ncustomer ID, and country. The subsequent data preprocessing steps included handling \nmissing values, conducting regency, frequency, and  monetary (RFM) analysis, \naddressing outliers using the Interquartile Range (IQR), and normalizing the data. The \nclustering methods applied were K -Means and K -Medoids, each requiring the \ndetermination of the optimal number of cluster (K). The elbow method was employed for \nthis purpose. For K -Means, the study identified the optimal K value as 4, resulting in four \ndistinct clusters with specific characteristics related to customer behavior. K -Medoids, \nwith an optimal K value of 6, formed six clusters, offerin g a more detailed segmentation \nbased on RFM analysis . The results analysis involved an examination and interpretation \nof the characteristics of each cluster obtained from both clustering methods. Making the \nimportance of preprocessing steps and  highlighting the implications for businesses in \ntailoring their strategies based on the identified customer clusters , findings  are explained \nproperly . The generalization of the findings maybe be constrained due to the specific \ncharacteristics of the dataset and  focus  on clustering techniques neglects the exploration \nof other potential factors influencing customer behavior. The reliance on the elbow \nmethod for finding  the most favorable  number of clusters may not be universally \napplicable, and analysis with alternative clustering algorithms is absent . \n \n \n  6CS014  \n9 \n 4.7. AdRobot: A Smart Segmentation Application for Automated & \nPersonalized Marketing Campaigns  \nThis paper addresses a critical challenge in contemporary marketing connecting the right \npromotional campaign with the right audience in the digital area. The authors present \nAdRobot as a solution, harnessing the power of artificial intelligence to automat e and \npersonalize the marketing strategies. The proposed algorithm investigates profiling and \nconversational data, employing AI heuristics to adeptly match audiences with tailored \npromotional campaigns. The methodology comprises two key data collection app roaches. \nFirstly, conversational constraints are automatically gathered from interactions with the \nChatfuel chatbot, encompassing  details such as age, field of work, marital  status, and \ninterests. Secondly, customer responses to marketing agent posts on social media \nplatforms, including likes, dislikes, ratings, and comments, are collected.  Distance \ncorrelation, Levenshtein distance, and Euclidean distance to match customers with the \nmost suitable  promotional campaigns based on characteristics like departur e place, \narrival place, departure date, ticket type and price  are utilization for the research . The \nintegration of Chatfuel ch atbot and DialogFlow is pivotal to the process. Chatfuel \nfacilitates user interactions, while DialogFlow contributes to natural language \nunderstanding, aiding in the determination of customer intents during conversations. The \noverall process involves the i nitiation of conversation, data collection through forms or \npredefined questions, and the generation of targets for customized adv ertising \ncampaigns . The results showcase the effectiveness of the algorithm, with a positive user \nresponse indicating a 70% satisfaction rate regarding the accuracy of matched offers. \nHowever, the paper acknowledges certain limitations. Notably, the reliance on data \nexclusive ly from Facebook interactions raises concerns about the generalization of \nfindings across diverse social media platforms. The researchers have  primarily focuse d \non a specific industry potentially limiting its applicability to other doma ins (Hafaiedh, et \nal., 2020) . \n \n \n  6CS014  \n10 \n 5. Findings  \nThe research and analysis of papers on ad prediction showcases the effectiveness of \nadvanced techniques such as Upper Confidence Bound (UCB), Thompson Sampling, and \nLSTM in enhancing predictive accuracy. The comparison of UCB and Thompson \nSampling demonstr ates different performances. The LSTM -RNN model, while \noutperforming baseline models, faces challenges related to computational costs. Similarly \nfor customer segmentation, the clustering algorithms such as K -Means, K -Medoids, and \nSpectral Clustering provid es valuable insights into the strengths and weaknesses of each \nalgorithm, emphasizing the importance of choosing the appropriate method based on \ndataset characteristics and analytical goals.  Deep User Segment Interest Network \n(DUSIN) showcased promising result for click through rate prediction. The papers analyze \nthe impact of AI in post -performance, campaign effectiveness, and optimization of ad \nspending. An example shown for AdRobot uses AI for automating promotional campaigns \nbased on customer profiles a nd interactions. The study has certain limitations such as \nalgorithm sensitivity, assumptions about user behavior, and potential biases in data \ncollection.  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n  6CS014  \n11 \n 6. Conclusion  \nThe analysis of papers strides in the application of AI in advertising and customer \nsegmentation. With the use of reinforcement learning algorithms to the insights gained \nthrough clustering techniques implication in a system that can first track the custom er \nactivity and based on the performance of the customer activity segregate them offering \nthe businesses valuable insights for enhancing the marketing strategies based on \ncustomer behavior. I t provides valuable insights into the practical application of \nreinforcement learning for ad prediction . This innovation emerges as a solution for \nautomated and personalized marketing campaigns, leveraging AI and advanced \nalgorithms to enhance audience targeting. However, there is a need for real -world cases  \nto illustrate the practical application of clustering algorithms in diverse business scenarios, \nbridging the gap between theoretical insights and practical implications.  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n   6CS014  \n12 \n 7. References  \nDeng, W. et al., 2018. Ad Click Prediction in Sequence with Long Short -Term Memory. \nAnn Arbor, MI, USA,, The 41st International ACM SIGIR Conference on Research & \nDevelopment in Information Retrieval, pp. 1065 -1068.  \nHafaiedh, K. et al., 2020. AdRobot: A smart segmentation application for automated & \npersonalized marketing campaigns. Tunisia, DTUC \'20: Proceedings of the 2nd \nInternational Conference on Digital Tools & Uses Congress, pp. 1 -6. \nKarim, S. & Hicham, N., 2022. Analysis of Unsupervised Machine Learning Techniques \nfor an Efficient Customer Segmentation using Clustering Ensemble and Spectral \nClustering. (IJACSA) International Journal of Advanced Computer Science and \nApplications, Volume 13, p. 10.  \nKim, K., Kwon, E. & Park, J., 2021. Deep User Segment Interest Network Modeling for \nClick -Through Rate Prediction of Online Advertising. IEEE Access, Volume 9, pp. 9812 -\n9821.  \nLakshmanarao, A., Ushanag, S. & Leela, B. S., 2021. Ad Prediction using Click Through \nRate and Machine Learning with Reinforcement Learning. Endore, India, 2021 Fourth \nInternational Conference on Electrical, Computer and Communication Technologies \n(ICECCT).  \nMufarroha, F. A. et al., 2022. K-Means and K -Medoids Clustering Methods for Cusomer \nSegmentation in Online Retail Datasets. Surabaya, Indonesia, 2022 IEEE 8th Information \nTechnology International Seminar (ITIS).  \nPatel, M. et al., 2020. Customer Segmentation using Machine Learning. International \nJournal for Research in Applied Science & Engineering Technology (IJRASET), 8(VI), pp. \n2104 -2108.  \n \n \n  ', NULL, 0, '2065697_dhirajkumarsahkanu_finalreport-1pdf', '2024-02-10 04:48:51', '2024-02-10 10:33:52'),
